<HEAD>
<TITLE> DRJ Expo </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="stone.jpg">
<center>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
<img src="drjlogo.gif"><br>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
</center>

<center><font size="6">
THE
EIGHTH<br> 
INTERNATIONAL<br> 
DISASTER 
RECOVERY <br>
SYMPOSIUM 
AND
EXHIBITION<br></font size>
<br>
<font size="4">
September 9 - 11, 1996<br>
Atlanta, GA<br>
Disaster Recovery Journal presents its 15th conference<br></center></font size>
<br>
<hr>
<font  size=5><center>Sunday  Workshop Sessions<br>
Sept 8, 1996   2:00-4:30<br>
<blink>ATTENDEES MUST PREREGISTER FOR THESE SPECIAL WORKSHOPS BEFORE THE CONFERENCE <br>
- SEATING IS LIMITED -</blink><br>
<hr></font size></center>

<br>

<b>"What is a LAN? What are the Issues Dealing With Lan?"<br><IMG SRC="speakers/budb.gif" img align=right>		
SWS 1     Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate<br></b>
Regis "Bud" Bates, Jr.<br>
TC International Consulting Inc.<br>
<br>
Understanding the inner workings of a LAN is crucial before a recovery plan can be developed. This session will include an introductory discussion of how the Local Area Network works and how it can be beneficial to a company.  The basics of developing a recovery plan will also be included.<br>
Mr. Bates has more than 29 years of experience in telecommunications and management information systems, with specific experience in end-user management, systems integration, disaster avoidance and recovery planning, strategic planning and network design. Mr. Bates is the president of TC International Consulting, Inc. in Phoenix, Ariz. He is an active lecturer and the author of numerous articles and books.<br>
<br>
<br>


<b>"Obtaining and Maintaining Management Commitment to B.R.P."<br><IMG SRC="speakers/barney.gif" img align=right>	
SWS 2     Target Audience: Intermediate/Advanced	<br></b>		
Barney Pelant, CDRP<br>
Barney F. Pelant & Assoc.<br>
<br>
Yes, it's a management thing, but what if management doesn't understand that? What can you do to obtain "top-down" commitment and what can you do to ensure that you don't lose it? Are you really doing all you can do? This will be an interactive workshop to address these and related issues. Such as, what do you do when disaster recovery loses priority? Bring your experiences and be prepared to share, learn and develop your own action item to-do list!<br>
Mr. Pelant is owner and managing director of Barney F. Pelant & Associates. Previously he was a senior manager serving Ernst & Young's National Business Continuity Program, and Director of Contingency Services, SunGard Recovery Services consulting practice. Mr. Pelant serves on the Board of Directors of the Canadian Centre for Emergency Preparedness. He is the past Executive Director, Chair of the Certification Board and member of the Board of Directors of the Disaster Recovery Institute.<br>
<br>
<br>


<b>"Using the Internet as a Disaster Recovery Resource"	<br>
SWS 3    Target Audience:  Novice/Intermediate/Advanced	<br></b>
<IMG SRC="speakers/bob.gif" img align=right><IMG SRC="speakers/colee.gif" img align=right>		
		
Cole Emerson, CDRP<br>
Cole Emerson and Associates<br>			
and Robert Arnold<br>
Disaster Recovery Journal<br>
<br>
This session will guide you through the process of how and where to find business continuity resources on the Internet. The Internet is the fastest growing information exchange in the world and is an easy place to become overwhelmed by the vast amount of information available. Participants will be able to view some of the various hot spots for business continuity and learn where many disaster recovery planners turn when they need answers and/or opportunities networking with peers.<br>
Mr. Emerson, president of CEA, has more than 20 years of domestic and international experience in computer and information security, investigations, encryption, contingency and disaster recovery planning, computer site recovery, training, and project management.<br>
Mr. Arnold is currently the webmaster and advertising manager for the Disaster Recovery Journal. His responsibilities as Webmaster include maintaining an Internet web server, writing HTML files, and updating DRJ's website. Mr. Arnold graduated with a BS in Business Administration from Southeast Missouri State University. <br>
		
