<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> DRJ Expo </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="stone.jpg">
<center>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
<img src="drjlogo.gif"><br>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
</center>

<center><font size="6">
THE
EIGHTH<br> 
INTERNATIONAL<br> 
DISASTER 
RECOVERY <br>
SYMPOSIUM 
AND
EXHIBITION<br></font size>
<br>
<font size="4">
September 9 - 11, 1996<br>
Atlanta, GA<br>
Disaster Recovery Journal presents its 15th conference<br></center></font size>
<br>
<hr>
<font  size=5><center>General Sessions<br>


<hr></font size></center>

<br>

<b>

"Facing the Extreme Challenges"<br>		<IMG SRC="speakers/djh.gif" img align=right>	
General Session 1     Monday 8:30 - 9:45 a.m.	</b><br>		
D.J. Harrington<br>
Phone Logic, Inc.<br>
<br>

In today's challenging times we must don many hats to function under some extreme conditions...even when looking at global events and relating them to everyday business challenges.  In today's fast paced world, you must be prepared for anything at anytime.  Recent disasters such as bombings, terrorist attacks, and earthquakes have proven that contingency planners must be able to react in an instant.  You can't do today's business with yesterdays thinking and hope to be ahead tomorrow.  Discover new ways of looking at life, and then deliver back to your workplace a new you.  Find the one hat which is right for you and how to wear it under any condition.<br>
Mr. Harrington is president and chief executive officer of Phone Logic, Inc., an international telemarketing and training company based in Atlanta, Ga. He serves as a consultant to over 600 privately owned businesses throughout the country, training personnel at all levels of the company. Mr. Harrington appears every week on ASTN, the national cable training network. As a syndicated columnist for 33 newspapers, Mr. Harrington writes a monthly article that appears in publications from Atlanta to Chicago to Los Angeles. He is a recipient of the Vicom Group Video Training Award and has been a featured speaker at numerous conferences and seminars.<br>
<br><br>
<b>"Life on the Edge"			<br><IMG SRC="speakers/brentw.gif" img align=right>
General Session 2     Monday 10:15 - 11:30	</b>	<br>	
Brent Woodworth<br>
IBM Crisis Response Team<br>
<br>
In a crisis situation, how does the plan that looked so good on paper actually work? This session will review real life experiences and provide an opportunity to contrast the reality vs. the planning stages.  Situations to be discussed include the Oklahoma City Bombing and Hurricane Marilyn, as well as other recent disasters. The lessons which were learned in each of  the crisis  will be studied in-depth. Also discussed will be the role of the media, human factors, and insurance concerns.<br>
Mr. Woodworth is a Director of Services and Manager of IBM's Worldwide Crisis Response Team. He is responsible for the development and implementation of IBM's Business Resumption Services in 52 countries.  He is certified in emergency medical services, and crisis management.<br>
<br>
<br><b>
"Linking Government Agencies With the Private Sector In a Disaster"	<br><IMG SRC="speakers/dales.gif" img align=right>
General Session 3     Tuesday 8:30 - 9:45 a.m.</b>	<br>			
Dale Stewart<br>
FieldTek Logistics<br>

<br>
	
Consider the difficulties of logistical deployment in a major disaster.  Significant difficulties have occurred during the interfacing of govenment agencies and private industry during crisis situations.  When an area wide disaster strikes, where food and water supplies are contaminated, infrastructure is heavily damaged, and support services are out of commission the interfacing of government and private sectors is very difficult.  Mr. Stewart will speak on the issues and methodologies involved in linking Government agency rescue operations with business recovery efforts in a major disaster.  Mr. Stewart will discuss WAN crisis communications linking the Government with private entities and satellite up-linking to support crisis communications.<br>
Mr. Stewart is known worldwide by many different industries as a leader in remote site logistics, services and operations. He has direct experience in Arctic, Jungle, Desert, and Mountain terrain. Mr. Stewart is a leader in using innovative approaches and proven methodologies that can be applied to discovering solutions to the most demanding situations. <br>
<br><b>
"Lessons Learned from Previous Disasters"	<br>	<IMG SRC="speakers/johnm.gif" img align=right>	
General Session 4     Tuesday 10:15 - 11:30 a.m.</b>	<br>		
John W. Marini<br>
Adjusters International<br>
<br>
This session will offer interesting details on several of the losses Adjusters International has handled and insights as to how these clients might have better prepared themselves for the unthinkable. Disasters to be studied include the bombings of  the World Trade Center and the Federal Building in Oklahoma City, several hurricanes and others. The audience will learn from the company's experiences and take home information to apply to their - or their clients - disaster plans.<br>
Mr. Marini is the Director of Sales and Marketing of Adjusters International (AI), one of the world's largest public adjusting and loss consulting firms. Mr. Marini was part of the management of AI's Hurricane Andrew storm operation, and responded to the Midwest Flood and California Earthquake. He was involved in the AI team named to the Governor's Task Force on Damage Assessment following the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, Okla. Mr. Marini's professional affiliations include memberships in the Building Owners & Managers Association, National Apartment Association as well as numerous others. He is a published author, a  licensed public adjuster, and holds a bachelor's degree in business administration from Columbia College.<br>
<br><b>
"Disaster Recovery Into The Next Millennium"	<br>	<IMG SRC="speakers/wesm.gif" img align=right>	
General Session 5     Wednesday 8:30 - 9:45 a.m.</b>	<br>		
Wes Melling<br>
Digital Equipment Corp.<br>
<br>
Computing can be survival - when it is not available business stops and very often does not come back. The best way for a computer system to "recover" from a disaster is for it not to stop running in the first place. Plummeting hardware prices are making multi-site configurations economical and increases in software sophistication are making them easy to install and manage. Mr. Melling will discuss pragmatic approaches to systems configurations which can survive destruction of a computer room or a building or an entire metropolitan area without interruption of on-line service.<br>
Mr. Melling is vice president of Digital Equipment Corporation's Open VMS Systems Business Group. With over 33 years in the industry, he has special consulting expertise in the areas of open systems, mission-critical transaction processing, and the development of enterprise information architectures. <br>
<b>
"Issues and Answers"	<br>		
General Session 6     Wednesday 10:15 - 11:30 a.m.	</B>	<br>	<IMG SRC="speakers/patti.gif" img align=right><IMG SRC="speakers/delvin.gif" img align=right>
Ed Devlin, CDRP<br>
Strohl Systems<br>
Patti Fitzgerald, CDRP<br>
SIAC<br>
<br>
This session will provide a networking opportunity to enable attendees to find answers to questions or problems they're having in their business environment. During this session, an "open mike" format will allow various issues to be addressed and answers to be addressed and answers to be presented, so that attendees may choose the best solution for their situation. Issues to be presented in the session must be sent in prior to the start of the conference. A space has been provided on the registration form on page 16 for each attendee (or any interested person) to send in one question or concern.
Mr. Devlin is a leading consultant, author, instructor and speaker in the field of business continuity and business resumption planning. He is a Certified Disaster Recovery Planner, a member of the Editorial Advisory Board of the Disaster Recovery Journal and a member of the Advisory Board of the National Association of Contingency Planners. Presently, Mr. Devlin is senior vice president for Strohl Systems.<br>
Ms. Fitzgerald is manager of corporate contingency services for Securities Industry Automation Corporation (SIAC)  in Brooklyn, NY. Prior to this position, she served as conference coordinator/advertising manager for Disaster Recovery Journal for six years. Ms. Fitzgerald has also served as an instructor for the Disaster Recovery Institute.<br>
 




		
<br>


