<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> DRJ Expo </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="stone.jpg">
<center>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
<img src="drjlogo.gif"><br>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
</center>

<center><font size="6">
THE
EIGHTH<br> 
INTERNATIONAL<br> 
DISASTER 
RECOVERY <br>
SYMPOSIUM 
AND
EXHIBITION<br></font size>
<br>
<font size="4">
September 9 - 11, 1996<br>
Atlanta, GA<br>
Disaster Recovery Journal presents its 15th conference<br></center></font size>
<br>
<hr>
<font  size=5><center>Breakout Sessions<br>


<hr></font size></center>
<center><strong>Monday, Sept. 9--  2:00-3:00<br></center></strong><br><br>
<b>"How to Define and Develop Disaster Recovery Teams"<IMG SRC="speakers/ralphb.gif" img align=right><br>			
SS-1    Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced</b>	<br>		
Ralph Borzyczkowski, CDRP<br>
Borzy Consulting Inc.<Br>
  <br>
The initial definition and development of disaster recovery teams sets the stage for a successful implementation of your disaster recovery plan. By identifying the proper roles, staffing and mobilization of recovery teams, you can help to insure that your disaster recovery plan has complete team coordination. Make your team activities look like a Broadway production, not a third grade skit.<br>
Mr. Borzyczkowski is the President of Borzy Consulting, Inc. He has been involved in disaster recovery planning since 1979. <br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Resumption Planning in Manufacturing"	<IMG SRC="speakers/gearym.gif" img align=right>		<br>
MS-1   Target Audience:  Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG>	<br>	
Gerard Minnich, CDRP<br>
EDS			<br>
<br>
This session goes beyond current practices and explores "business continuity" planning for manufacturing processes. You will see a process for sorting critical outputs from those not as critical. The session will assist you in identifying key resources and developing resumption strategies for those resources as well as working with suppliers to ensure their disaster doesn't become yours.<br>
Mr. Minnich has been dedicated to the recovery planning field for over 10 years. In addition to his CDRP, he completed a Bachelors Degree in Emergency Administration and Planning from the University of North Texas. <br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Global Corp. Data Protection and Recovery - Trends & Experiences" <IMG SRC="speakers/nancyt.gif" img align=right>	<br>
TS-1   Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate	</STRONG>	<br>	
Nancy Thompson<br>
Comdisco<br>
<br>
The use of "real-time" information is becoming increasingly more critical and accessible. Current and future data recovery strategies and services will have to address this issue. Electronic vaulting, remote journaling, data base shadowing and disc mirroring are just a  few of the strategies we will address in this session. This presentation will include discussions on mainframe through distributed systems platforms.<br>
Ms. Thompson is product manager of advanced recovery services for Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services.  She is responsible for continued research and development of AR services across all technologies.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"The Federal Response Plan Overview"		<IMG SRC="speakers/benv.gif" img align=right>	<br>
ES-1    Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG><br>		
Ben Venturella<br>
USACE (Retired)<br>
<br>
This session is designed to give all participants (especially local and state government emergency management personnel) a better understanding of how the federal government responds to a catastrophic disaster event, after a Presidential declaration. Also, this session will cover the 28 signatory agencies and along with their emergency support functions to this plan.<br>
Mr. Venturella, retired from the US Army Corps of Engineers (USACE), St. Louis District in September 1993. During his 32-year government career, he spent more than 20 years working in Emergency Management where he developed national, natural and technological contingency plans. <br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Chemical Bank's Common User Area - Part II"		<IMG SRC="speakers/arthurg.gif" img align=right><IMG SRC="speakers/lawrenck.gif" img align=right>	<br>
CS-1   Target Audience:  Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG>		<br>
Lawrence Kalmis<br>
Arthur Graves, CDRP <br>
Chemical Bank<br>
<br>
This session will review, from a business perspective, the rationale for construction, expand on the development methodology, and explain the lessons learned. You will learn how Chemical Bank developed a common solution to satisfy the diverse technological needs of a multitude of business groups and how they dealt with some of the "surprises along the way." This session will provide an understanding of how  the  lessons learned can be applied to the development of your own recovery capability.<br>
Mr. Kalmis is vice president, business continuity management for the Chase Manhattan Bank. A Fellow of the Business Continuity Institute, Mr. Kalmis joined Chemical Bank in June 1987.<br>
Mr. Graves is vice president, business continuity management for Chase Manhattan Bank. A Certified Disaster Recovery Planner, Mr. Graves joined Manufacturers Hanover Trust in January 1981.<br>
<br>
<strong><hr>
<center>Monday, Sept 9 1996 --  3:30-4:30</center></strong><br><hr><br><br>
<STRONG>"The Right Skills at the Right Time"			<IMG SRC="speakers/gregt.gif" img align=right><IMG SRC="speakers/billw.gif" img align=right>	<br>
 Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG>		<br>	
William Worsley, Jr., CDRP SS-2    <br>
The Dow Chemical Company<br>
Greg Therkalsen<br>
Comdisco Professional Serv.<br>
<br>
One of the obstacles in creating a continuity plan is the need for a diverse amount of specialized skills.  To develop a successful plan and execute it properly, one must have the ability to organize a WAN, LAN, data recovery, work area recovery, and hardware specifications.  This session will explore the concept of having available a team  of resources from which knowledge can be pulled as it is needed.  This provides a means of gaining access to the right skills, experience and methods at just the right time.<br>
Mr. Worsley is a business continuity specialist with the Dow Chemical Company.  Mr. Worsley has been a  member of the Editorial Advisory Board for Disaster Recovery Journal since 1995.<br>
Mr. Therkalsen was named vice president of Comdisco Professional Services in 1992. He is a member of the Professional Services Management Committee.				<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Keeping Business on an Even Keel in the Wake of Disaster?"<IMG SRC="speakers/billb.gif" img align=right>	<br>	
MS-2    Target Audience: Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG>	<br>		
William B. Bruce, CDRP<br>
Fidelity Investments<br>
<br>
This session will cover actual practices that have worked for over 100 business units. Mr. Bruce will cover the details of, and how to develop a Strategic Contingency Program. He will discuss targeting exposures and reducing risk, practices for recovery, and details for the comprehensive testing and alternate site programs. <br>
Mr. Bruce has over 20 years experience in contingency planning and information security. For the last six years he has been responsible for the Corporate Contingency Planning Program for over 45 Fidelity Investment companies. Mr. Bruce is founder and President of the Northern New England Disaster Recovery Information X-change Inc. (NEDRIX) which has over 800 professionals dealing with business continuity.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Data Replication in Computer Systems"		<IMG SRC="speakers/toms.gif" img align=right>	<br>	
TS-2     Target Audience: Intermediate/Advanced	</STRONG>	<br>		
Tom Speake<br>
Digital Equipment Corp.<br>
<br>
A corporation's data is one of its most valuable assets. If a disaster strikes, you can purchase replacement computers, disks and other computer related equipment, but you can't purchase replacement data. Choosing the correct level of replication is a business decision. However, it is a business decision that is based on understanding today's technology. In this session we will compare and contrast the different methods available for replicating data with respect to such things as safety, cost, system overhead and management overhead.<br>
Mr. Speake is a technical marketing consultant with Digital Equipment Corporation's OpenVMS Marketing organization. Mr. Speake's primary responsibility is the 24x365 computing program.<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Disaster Preparedness - Protecting Your Vital Records"		<IMG SRC="speakers/davidm.gif" img align=right>	<br>	
ES-2     Target Audience:  Novice/Intermediate		</STRONG>	<br>	
Dave McDaniel<br>
BMS Cat<br>
<br>
The vital records of a company are not just a collection of papers. Today they include a complex mix of paper, microfilm, microfiche, computers, and different sizes of magnetic tape drives. If a disaster strikes, restoration becomes an important part of business survival. This means that the corporation must be able to respond with the appropriate actions for all of the above media and equipment.<br>
As Chief Scientist for BMS Catastrophe Special Technologies Division, Mr. McDaniel is responsible for post loss analysis, recommendations for recovery procedures, protocols and remediation.<br>
 <br>
<STRONG>"Disaster Recovery Plan Development and Testing"	<IMG SRC="speakers/fredl.gif" img align=right><br>			
CS-2     Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate</STRONG>	<br>			
Fred Luevano, CDRP<br>
Northrup Grumman<br>
<br>
This session will cover basic principles of disaster recovery planning for mainframe and distributed environments: off-site data backup, alternate processing capability, and a response manual which will include recovery actions, command post requirements, a damage assessment matrix, and team procedures. <br>
Mr. Luevano has more than 30 years of management experience in information systems in virtually all facets of data processing. <br>



 




		
<br>


