<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> DRJ Expo </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body background="stone.jpg">
<center>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
<img src="drjlogo.gif"><br>
<img src="line.gif"><br>
</center>

<center><font size="6">
THE
EIGHTH<br> 
INTERNATIONAL<br> 
DISASTER 
RECOVERY <br>
SYMPOSIUM 
AND
EXHIBITION<br></font size>
<br>
<font size="4">
September 9 - 11, 1996<br>
Atlanta, GA<br>
Disaster Recovery Journal presents its 15th conference<br></center></font size>
<br>
<hr>
<font  size=5><center>Workshop Sessions<br>
Tuesday, Sept. 10 --  2:00-5:00<br>

<hr></font size></center>

<strong>"Ready, Set, ... Exercise!"<br>		<IMG SRC="speakers/steveng.gif" img align=right>	
WS-1     Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced</strong>	<br>		
Steven Goldman<br>
Tech*Plan Associates<br>
<br>

Successful crisis management and disaster recovery takes more than a plan: it requires realistic testing and validation. How do you do that properly? Are your exercises smoke and mirrors or do they provide as-close-to-real situations as possible? During this workshop, the attendee will learn how to set up and conduct a successful contingency plan exercise. Attendees will master the aspects of effective exercise preparation and execution, including the scenario team, objectives, extent of play, scheduling, coordination, resources, and props, as well as creativity and leadership. Also, exercise evaluation and critiquing methods will be discussed. The focus of this workshop is non-IS: exercise realism will be stressed and videos of exercises will be presented.<br>
Mr. Goldman has developed, conducted and evaluated scores of drills and exercises ranging from two-hour table-tops to massive three-day exercises involving hundreds of responders. He has been involved in all aspects of crisis management since 1978. Mr. Goldman has published many articles on crisis management and has lectured at several crisis management seminars, both domestic and international. He is President of TECH*PLAN Associates, a leading Crisis Management and Crisis Communications consulting firm providing quality services to corporations, industry and all levels of government.<br>
<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"LAN Recovery for the Advanced Planner"	<br>	<IMG SRC="speakers/budb.gif" img align=right>	
WS-2     Target Audience: Intermediate/Advanced	<br></STRONG>		
Regis J. "Bud" Bates, Jr.<br>
TC International Consulting, Inc.<br>


This workshop will focus on how to write and implement a disaster recovery plan for LANs. Through role play and group discussion, participants will learn the objectives of the plan, options for developing the plan, how to minimize risks and how to write the plan and testing policy. Security and backup concerns will also be discussed.<br>
Mr. Bates has more than 29 years of experience in telecommunications and management information systems, with specific experience in end-user management, systems integration, disaster avoidance and recovery planning, strategic planning and network design. Mr. Bates is the president of TC International Consulting, Inc. in Phoenix, Ariz.<br>
		<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Business Impact Analysis"			<br><IMG SRC="speakers/barney.gif" img align=right>
WS-3      Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate		</STRONG><br>	
Barney F. Pelant, CDRP<br>
Barney F. Pelant and Assoc.<br>

<br>
The Business Impact Analysis provides the business rationale for developing a business continuity plan. Additionally, it provides the basis for validating the ongoing viability of that plan meeting the organization's needs. However, it is often seen as an impossible task and one that lack's credibility when it's completed. This session will explore the purpose of the Business Impact Analysis. Additionally, it will examine the successful methods of achieving timely desired results. This workshop will be interactive and encourage group participation.<br>
Mr. Pelant is owner and managing director of Barney F. Pelant & Associates. Previously he was a senior manager serving Ernst & Young's National Business Continuity Program, and Director of Contingency Services, SunGard Recovery Services consulting practice. Mr. Pelant serves on the Board of Directors of the Canadian Centre for Emergency Preparedness. He is the past Executive Director, Chair of the Certification Board and member of the Board of Directors of the Disaster Recovery Institute.<br>
<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Master the Disaster: At The EduComp Corp"	<br>	<IMG SRC="speakers/campbell.gif" img align=right><IMG SRC="speakers/morganti.gif" img align=right>	
WS-4    Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced	<br>	</STRONG>
Michael Morganti, CDRP<br>
Tom Campbell, CDRP<br>
Arkwright Mutual Ins. Co.<br>
<br>
In this exercise you will work in groups of six. Your goal will be to protect the profits, market share, and share-holder equity of the EduComp Corporation by applying sound prevention, control, and planning principles. The five operating units of the EduComp Corporation face numerous man-made and natural threats. Attend this workshop, apply your experience and learn more about prevention and control.<br>
Mr. Morganti is a customer education specialist at Arkwright Mutual Insurance Company. He is responsible for developing and delivering customized training presentations and seminars on a range of loss control and disaster recovery topics to current and prospective Arkwright Customers.<br>
Mr. Campbell joined Arkwright in January 1983 as Customized Education Services Manager. He was instrumental in the development of Arkwright's Disaster Recovery Seminar and has been teaching this program since 1992.<br>
<br>
<br>
<STRONG>"Mitigating Risk Throughout Your Enterprise"			<br><IMG SRC="speakers/pauld.gif" img align=right>
WS-5    Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced		<br></STRONG>	
Paul Doyle<br>
IBM Corporation<br>
<br>
This workshop focuses on the identification and mitigation one can and should take to reduce risk and prevent disasters from happening. Emphasis is placed not only on the traditional data center, but the entire enterprise-wide enterprise-wide environment, covering the physical as well as logical threats an organization can face. In addition, implementing an effective risk management program that includes aspects of education, human resources, security services, and anti-virus, throughout the enterprise. A "Quick Assessment Checklist" will be demonstrated as well as a blueprint on how to start implementing a risk management program. There will also be an introduction to risk analysis tools available. <br>
Mr. Doyle is a senior consultant with IBM Business Recovery Consulting (BRC) group. Mr. Doyle has 17 years experience in the computer industry. He specializes in consulting on business recovery management and systems programming.<br>
<br>

<br>
<STRONG>"Intra-Day Recovery: Closing the Recovery Window"		<br><IMG SRC="speakers/johnl.gif" img align=right>	
WS-6    Target Audience: Novice/Intermediate/Advanced		<br></STRONG>	
John Lindeman<br>
SunGard Rec. Serv., Inc.<br>
George J. Hakun<br>
SunGard Planning Solutions<br>
<br>

This workshop  will begin with a panel discussion. Workshop leaders will provide an overview of the business case, discussing the issues, potential business impacts, options for recovery, costs, and associated risks, followed by a discussion of current and emerging vaulting technology. Following this in-depth introduction, workshop participants will be divided into teams. Each team will be presented with a real-life scenario and, with the help of the experts, will determine whether to execute a vaulting recovery strategy.<br>
Mr. Lindeman is manager, product development for SunGard Recovery Services, Inc. In this capacity, Mr. Lindeman manages SunGard's SunVault Services electronic vaulting offerings, and end-user recovery offerings. His responsibilities include establishing marketing alliances, product development, and product marketing.<br>
Mr. Hakun joined SunGard Planning Solutions in 1995 as a consultant. His background includes Information Systems Operation, Network design/network management and disaster planning. Mr. Hakun spent 15 years with CIGNA Corporation where he held key positions including assistant director of environment change assurance and the director of network and computer services.      <br>
<br>

<br>


