<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Scraping in</h2>
 <p>
Despite his transgressions, <b>Newt Gingrich</b>, speaker of the House of Representatives, was re-elected by 216 votes to 205. Four Republicans voted against him, and five abstained. Mr Gingrich thus became the first Republican speaker to be re-elected in 68 years. The House must still decide later this month how to punish him for his misuse of tax-exempt funds for political purposes. <p>
The president's advisory council on <b>Social Security </b> (state pensions) reported that the system would probably go bankrupt by 2029, and recommended that a large part of the Social Security trust fund should be invested in the stockmarket rather than in government securities. <p>
The Supreme Court began to hear arguments for and against <b>euthanasia</b>. Two states are appealing against rulings by lower courts that have overturned state bans on assisted suicide.<p>
The Canadian government apologised to a former prime minister, <b>Brian Mulroney</b>, who had sued it over suggestions that he had received kickbacks from the sale of Airbus aircraft to Air Canada in 1988. <p>
<b>Nicaragua</b>'s newly elected president Arnoldo Aleman took office. The defeated Sandinists complained bitterly that the Supreme Court had annulled self-serving laws passed by their side of the outgoing legislature while the right wing boycotted it.<p>
<h2>Middle East</h2>
Tension mounted between <b>Syria, Lebanon and Israel</b>. Syria blamed Israeli agents for recent bomb attacks in Syria and Lebanon. Israeli troops and Hizbullah guerrillas clashed in south Lebanon; one Israeli soldier was killed. Katyusha rockets were fired into northern Israel. Israeli aircraft attacked guerrilla positions.<p>
Despite American mediation, and a meeting between Binyamin Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, a deal on Israeli redeployment in <b>Hebron</b> continued to be held up. <p>
Iraq blamed Iran for three mortar shells fired from a truck at the Baghdad headquarters of the Iranian opposition<b> mujahiddin</b>. A hospital laboratory and an Iraqi writers' building were wrecked and a dozen people injured. <p>
A <b>Rwandan</b> court swiftly sentenced two men to death for their part in the 1994 genocide. The international genocide tribunal in Arusha, Tanzania, trying the bigger criminals, proceeded at a more formal pace. <p>
A member of a right-wing group called the <b>Boer Attack Troops</b> was rearrested on suspicion of planting bombs in South Africa that have killed several people.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
After the killing of two French officers who were trying to mediate between rebels and the <b>Central African Republic</b> government, French soldiers attacked a rebel-held part of the capital, Bangui, killing at least ten people.<p>
<h2>Mounting strife</h2>
 <p>
Union leaders in <b>South Korea </b>threatened to extend industrial action to the public services unless new labour laws were repealed. <p>
The People's Action Party won 81 of the 83 seats in <b>Singapore's Parliament</b>, gaining 65% of the vote, up from 61% in 1991.<p>
<b>India's Congress party</b>, defeated in last year's general election, was expected to make an early bid for power under its new leader, Sitaram Kesri.<p>
<b>Pakistan </b>created a "security council", giving the army a "non-binding" say in government affairs.<p>
<h2>Partial climbdown</h2>
Serbia's government recognised opposition parties' electoral victory in Nis, the second-biggest city. The opposition staged the <b>biggest demonstration</b> yet in Belgrade on the eve of the Orthodox Christmas. The head of the army told students that his troops would not crush the protests. A bomb was thrown at the headquarters of a party allied to the government.<p>
Russia's president, <b>Boris Yeltsin</b>, was admitted to hospital with signs of pneumonia. <p>
Russia said it has withdrawn its last 18,000 troops from <b>Chechnya</b>, paving the way for elections in the separatist region this month.<p>
The <b>Irish Republican Army</b> carried out bomb and rocket attacks in Northern Ireland, raising fears that loyalist groups will end their ceasefire in retaliation. In Spain, an army officer was killed, apparently by <font size=-1>ETA</font>, a <b>Basque separatist</b> group. A French paramilitary policeman was shot, apparently by a separatist, in <b>Corsica</b>.<p>
Bulgaria's ruling Socialist Party nominated <b>Nikolai Dobrev</b>, the tough-on-crime interior minister, as the new prime minister.<p>
The <b>Greek-Cypriot government </b>ordered a ground-to-air missile system from Russia, raising tensions with the Turkish-controlled part of Cyprus.<p>
The Swiss government said it might set up a fund to compensate <b>Holocaust victims</b> who may have lost money in Swiss banks. The outgoing president had earlier described demands for such a fund as "blackmail", prompting Jewish groups to threaten a boycott of Swiss banks.<p>
Europe's <b>unusually cold weather </b>has killed over 200 people and may depress economic growth.<p>
Seasonally adjusted unemployment in <b>Germany </b>rose to 10.9% of the workforce in December, a post-war record.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
