<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/11-01-97/bw0769.html 199.173.162.110 19970113122900 text/html 6594
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 12:25:18 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 12:23:33 GMT
Content-length: 6411
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Defence tactics</h2>
 <p>
Another huge round of consolidation is under way in <b>America's defence industry</b>. Raytheon made an agreed $2.95 billion offer for the missile and defence-electronics operations of Texas Instruments, beating a rival offer from Northrop Grumman. Bidding also closed for the defence unit of Hughes Electronics (whose parent is General Motors), which could be worth up to $9 billion. Again, Raytheon and Northrop Grumman are thought to be the main contenders.<p>
With the impending merger of Boeing and McDonnell Douglas concentrating their minds, the four European partners of <b>Airbus Industrie</b>, whose lumbering structure at present means each controls its own manufacturing facilities, agreed to pool most of those assets when the consortium goes corporate in 1999.<p>
After a rush of deals at the end of last month, <b>Boeing </b> announced orders in 1996 (net of cancellations) for 559 aircraft, worth $42.8 billion. <b>Airbus</b>, on a comparable basis, had 473 net orders, worth $36.4 billion<i>.</i><p>
<b>Philips Electronics</b> is withdrawing its support from Grundig, a troubled German consumer-electronics firm in which the Dutch giant has a controlling 31.6% stake. Philips, which has taken charges of $955m because of Grundig, will now become a "passive minority shareholder".<p>
A venture by India's Tata group and Singapore Airlines to set up <b>a domestic airline in India </b>cleared one big regulatory hurdle: the Foreign Investment Promotion Board. But the civil-aviation minister was uncivil about the prospect: foreign airlines would be barred from investing-- and that includes any existing holdings, he said.<p>
Two car makers, Germany's <b>BMW</b>, in its first foray into South America, and America's <b>Chrysler</b>, formed a $500m joint venture to build 400,000 engines a year in Brazil from 1999. <font size=-1>BMW</font> will also build a factory to make 5,000 Land Rovers annually.<p>
<h2>Building a bank</h2>
<b>Woolwich Building Society</b>, Britain's third-largest, said it will have a market capitalisation of up to &#163;3.4 billion ($5.8 billion), a bit higher than expected, when it floats on the London Stock Exchange in July, and hopes to be one of Britain's top ten banks in terms of assets.<p>
Gil Amelio, head of <b>Apple</b>, said the computer maker would still make a comeback despite a warning that the first quarter would show an operating loss of $100m-150m. Apple's takeover of <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font> Software, he said, would result in a new operating system for its troubled Macintosh within 18 months. Nevertheless, Apple's share price fell by nearly 20%.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Two American investment banks hit record profits in 1996. Net income at <b>Morgan Stanley</b>, though weaker than expected, rose to $1.03 billion in the year to November, up from $720m in 1995. Strong results from <b>Lehman Brothers</b> produced income of $416m, after an after-tax charge of $50m, well up from $242m in 1995.<p>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Central banks, particularly European ones, sold off huge quantities of <b>gold</b> in the second half of last year. At $335 per ounce, the price of gold now stands at its lowest level in more than three years.<p>
<h2>Chinese puzzle</h2>
Li Ka-shing announced sweeping changes to his Hong Kong business empire. His main company, <b>Cheung Kong Holdings</b>, will raise its stake in Hutchison Whampoa, whose interests run from ports to telecoms. Hutchison Whampoa is also making a general offer for Hongkong Electric. Mr Li then intends to hive off part of the utility into Cheung Kong Infrastructure, whose interests lie on the mainland.<p>
German prosecutors charged <b>J&uuml;rgen Schneider</b>, whose property empire crashed three years ago in one of Germany's biggest corporate scandals, with credit fraud, fraudulent bankruptcy and forgery. They found no criminal evidence against the creditor banks he had tried to implicate in his downfall.<p>
Shares in Italy's <b>Olivetti</b> jumped on talk that the beleaguered information-technology group may at last shed its loss-making personal-computer operations for upward of 200 billion lire ($130m). The buyer may well be Centenary Group, a private investment company backed by a number of industrialists.<p>
An arrest warrant was issued for <b>Giancarlo Parretti</b>, who left America a few days before he was due to be sentenced for perjury and tampering with evidence in a 1991 case that cost him control of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. Mr Parretti claims he has returned to Italy because of an unrelated tax investigation.<p>
France began charging 20.6% valued-added tax on <b>telephone services </b>offered from outside the European Union to customers within it, anticipating a change in <font size=-1>EU</font> legislation that will end the tax advantage gained by companies outside the <font size=-1>EU</font> that offer call-back and other services.<p>
As part of its internal investigation into racial discrimination, <b>Texaco </b>dismissed one manager, suspended another and withdrew benefits from two retirees.<p>
<h2>Nippon blues</h2>
 <p>
(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Japanese investors </b>returned from the new-year break nervous about their government's tax plans. The Nikkei average fell and fell, to a 13-month low.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
