<html><head><title>Cell-shocked</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Prisons</b></p>
<h1>Cell-shocked</h1>

IN LATE February or early March, the Prison Service will reach--and exceed-- its current maximum capacity of nearly 60,000 prisoners. In its desperation to come up with extra accommodation the agency is trying everything from inserting prefabricated cell-blocks into existing prisons to converting a former Pontins holiday camp into a new jail. It has even applied for planning permission to moor an American prison ship off Portland in Dorset. With the prison population continuing to rise rapidly and no new jails scheduled to open before the end of this year, no emergency measure seems too far-fetched.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not that the Prison Service will ever turn people away. If the worst comes to the worst, it can always cram more inmates into the existing cells. Cells in police stations could also be pressed into service, although this practice attracted endless criticism before its abolition in the early 1990s. Working from optimistically low projections of the prison population over the next few months, planning officials expect to get by somehow. But the government's policy of tougher sentences and tighter budgets will ensure a continuous struggle to squeeze in new prisoners.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The crush for places dates from 1993 when Michael Howard, the home secretary, announced a crackdown on crime under the slogan "Prison Works". Soon afterwards, the Home Office predicted that the prison population would rise from 49,000 in 1994 to 58,000 in 2002. But the zeal with which judges enforced the new policy had raised it to 58,000 by the end of 1996. The Prison Service, which had been concentrating on reducing overcrowding after the Strangeways riot in 1990, suddenly found itself with neither time nor money for anything except housing more inmates.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But creating extra capacity is difficult. It takes at least three years from the planning stage to opening a new prison. Moreover, local authorities are reluctant to grant planning permission: Doncaster council blocked one application last year; another in Shropshire had to be withdrawn, and more were delayed by local protests. In existing prisons the installation of flushing toilets in all cells has made it impossible to squeeze in extra beds. The need to house prisoners as close to their homes as possible and at varying levels of security creates further problems: Category B prisons in the north-west, for example, are already full.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite the prisons' current straits, politicians plan to increase the pressure. The government has introduced mandatory-sentencing proposals which by its own account will eventually raise the prison population by 11,000. That assumes, with extraordinary optimism, a 20% fall in crime due to the deterrent effect of stiffer sentences. Even if the government's figures prove correct, it has budgeted for a mere 4% increase in spending by the Prison Service over the next two years, even though the growth of almost 15% in the prison population over the past two years shows no signs of slowing. Nor has Labour promised any relief, since it wants to look tough on crime in the run-up to the general election.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Liberal-minded pressure groups, such as the Howard League and the Prison Reform Trust, claim that overcrowding combined with likely staff reductions and sharp cutbacks in education will inevitably make prison life increasingly difficult. Sir David Ramsbotham, the chief inspector of prisons, warned against such pressures in his most recent report. As it is, 1996 saw 64 suicides in prisons in England and Wales-- the highest number ever recorded.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reformers point out that the number of inmates could be cut by eliminating custodial sentences for non-threatening offenders. People who do not pay their fines account for over 20% of all prison sentences each year. 800 illegal immigrants are now in detention while their status is being decided. About 60% of the 12,000 people in jail awaiting trial or sentencing will not ultimately receive custodial sentences. And thousands more prisoners are serving short sentences for non-violent crimes. To house the big criminals, the government could do worse than set the small fry free.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
