<html><head><title>Don't panic</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Food safety</b></p>
<h1>Don't panic</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font><p>
MAD-COW disease was bad. But the food poisoning epidemic which struck in Lanarkshire last November and has so far killed 16 of its 270 victims has arguably been even more damaging for the government in Scotland. And more deaths are possible; six people are still seriously ill in hospital. On January 7th, government ministers considered the report of an inquiry they set up soon after the outbreak began, by Hugh Pennington, a professor of microbiology at Aberdeen University. They did not like what it had to say.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Scottish deaths have certainly challenged old assumptions about food safety. The bug which caused the Lanarkshire outbreak, the 0157 variant of<i> Escherichia coli</i> (<font size=-1>E</font> coli), is much nastier than other bugs which existing rules were designed to control. In people, it produces a poison which can kill old people and damage the kidneys of children. Other side-effects, some scientists think, may appear years later. It is also extremely virulent--just ten organisms are enough to cause infection, whereas around 100,000 salmonella bugs are needed to cause illness. It can appear to be dead, and then, under certain conditions, it can recover. Unlike most bugs, it seems to like stomach acid. Normal precautions against infection are not necessarily enough: barrier nursing of the Lanarkshire victims did not prevent a nurse from falling victim.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Raw meat which is not properly cooked is the usual source of infection. The Lanarkshire epidemic was traced to a butcher's shop. But the virulence of <font size=-1>E</font> coli 0157 means that minor hygiene slip-ups can contaminate other foods. In 1995, an outbreak affecting 62 people (one of whom died) in America was traced to apple juice.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Pennington's report argued that tough new regulations are needed to prevent further mass poisonings. Licensing food retailers, so that environmental-health officers can close firms not following strict hygiene rules, should boost existing powers to close suspect premises, which are subject to so many legal complexities that officials are reluctant to use them. New rules requiring food to be labelled with its origins would also allow health officials to act; a big problem in Lanarkshire was discovering whom the butcher had supplied.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But ministers reckon that this would be too Draconian. Britain's food industry is already heavily regulated, and is not necessarily to blame for the upsurge in <font size=-1>E</font> coli 0157 cases. The worst epidemic so far was in Japan last year, where 8,000 people were infected and 11 died. Ministers also think that the government over-reacted when it introduced the tough Food Safety Act in 1990 after scares about salmonella in eggs. They are not keen to add a lot of new rules now. And there may be better ways to tackle the problem. Most British food-poisoning cases are not mass affairs, but isolated incidents caused by poor hygiene, often at home. To bring down significantly the thousand or so <font size=-1>E</font>-coli 0157 poisonings which occurred in Britain in 1995, and the 80,000 other food poisoning cases, the British need only to be persuaded to cook food properly, and to wash their hands.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
