<html><head><title>Local calls</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img
src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0> <p><font size=-1> These articles in the Britain section are
published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions. </font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0> </td></tr></table>

<h1>Local calls</h1>

THE Tories continue their recovery in local by-elections which began a year ago--but are still doing much worse than they did in the
run-up to the past three general elections. They gained 16 local-authority seats in October-December 1996, according to <i>The
Economist</i>'s regular survey, and 31% of the 121,756 votes cast in three-cornered contests. However, they remain six percentage
points behind Labour. In the corresponding quarter before their general-election victories in 1983, 1987 and 1992, they were an
average of seven points ahead of Labour (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>).<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The worst
losers in the quarter were the Liberal Democrats, who lost 17 seats and held only 12. This may be bad news for Labour, too, which in
the past has relied on the Lib Dems to attract disaffected Tory voters who do not want to back Labour. These results suggest that some
of those voters are returning to the Tories, which may make it harder for Labour to win its target seats.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Scotland, there are too few by-elections to yield quarterly trends. But in 1996 as a whole
there was a 6.6% swing from Labour to the Scottish National Party (<font size=-1>SNP</font>) compared with May 1995, when the
seats were last fought. This is less than the 10.3% swing which occurred in by-elections before the 1992 general election. That swing
hit Labour hard in seats they hoped to win from the Tories. The Tories saw off their challenge in two marginal seats, Ayr and Stirling
(which is held by Michael Forsyth, a possible post-election Tory leadership candidate). <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This time, Mr Forsyth is already in deep trouble because the Tories are doing particularly
badly in Scotland. Although their vote was 1% higher in 1996 than in 1995, the Tory share of the vote in Scottish local by-elections is
still 6% below what it was in the year running up to the 1992 general election. If the swing from <font size=-1>SNP</font> to Labour at
the general election is lower this time, too, Mr Forsyth can bid farewell to his seat and, with it, to his leadership ambitions.<br>

