<html><head><title>After TWA 800</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>After TWA 800</h1>

AT PRESENT the cause of air safety lurches from crash to crash. Each disaster in turn produces a minor panic throughout the whole air industry. One recent example was the angst caused by <font size=-1>TWA 800</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the 24-year-old Boeing <font size=-1>747</font> exploded in mid-air off Long Island, most people at first suspected a terrorist bomb of causing the explosion; others thought it could be a missile test gone wrong. But the air industry was haunted by another (to it, more frightening) explanation: that the investigators would find some horrible technical fault associated with the aircraft's age. That might have grounded at least the older half of the world's fleet of about 1,000 jumbos, which are on average 18.8 years old. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the event this did not happen. In late December the American investigators of the National Transportation Safety Board (<font size=-1>NTSB</font>) gave a much more muted verdict. They concluded that the explosion which wrecked the aircraft was probably caused by the ignition of fuel vapour in a nearly empty fuel tank attached to the centre of a wing. The source of the ignition could have been a small bomb or a missile, but was more probably the result of some malfunction such as a spark caused by faulty wiring.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Normally the only electric current to come near such a tank is for instrumentation and is too feeble to produce sparks. But flight <font size=-1>TWA 800</font> had been standing on the tarmac at Kennedy airport for several hours in hot weather, with the aircraft's cabin air-conditioning unit running at full blast. The central wing fuel tank, situated next to the air-conditioning machinery, was empty because the flight to Paris would use only the main wing tanks. But the tanks did contain fuel vapour. The exhaust heat generated by the air-conditioning unit would have raised the temperature of the vapours to the point of maximum volatility, so the slightest spark could cause an explosion. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>NTSB</font> has proposed a series of measures which it wants the Federal Aviation Administration, the regulator, to introduce. The <font size=-1>FAA</font>, which normally follows such recommendations, has until the middle of March to announce what it will do. But the changes are relatively minor and unlikely to ground many of these workhorses of the world's airways. The recommendations range from compelling airlines to keep the tanks full of fuel, or put in nitrogen gas, to fitting gauges to tell the pilots on the flight deck if a tank is overheating. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has brought great relief to Boeing and to the world's airlines. But an industry that ships people around in machines half of which are on average almost two decades old may not be so lucky next time.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
