<html><head><title>What's in a name?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Virgin</b></p>
<h1>What's in a name?</h1>

<p><b>Is Virgin, Britain's best-known company, anything more than a conglomerate? If so, thank its daredevil boss</b></p><br>
NO OTHER company chairman has quite the taste for adventure or the genius for publicity of Richard Branson, boss of the sprawling Virgin group. His latest escapade, a brush with death on January 8th in an attempt to float around the world suspended from a helium balloon, exemplified both qualities. Since 1984, when a goggled and helmeted Mr Branson announced the first Virgin Atlantic flight from London to New York, his exuberant personality has defined Virgin far better than a bare description of what it sells. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From a boisterous infancy fuelled by Virgin Cola to retirement on a Virgin pension--via trips to Virgin cinemas and Virgin Megastores to buy records heard on Virgin Radio, Virgin Holidays reached on Virgin Atlantic flights, and perhaps even a wedding planned by Virgin Brides--a consumer today can look forward to a life of perpetual Virginity. Indeed, the ubiquitous Virgin name often appears to be the only glue, apart from Mr Branson, that holds the group together. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Does that matter? After all, other companies have ranged widely before now. Hanson, a British-American conglomerate, made bricks, cigarettes, industrial chemicals and food. Procter & Gamble covers fewer industries, but still makes products as diverse as toothpaste, peanut butter and paper towels. But these are different from Virgin: most consumers neither know nor care about the name of the parent company. Investors may know that Procter & Gamble makes shampoo; customers buy Head & Shoulders or Pantene.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The name Virgin, by contrast, appears on a huge range of disparate products. So is Virgin simply a conglomerate unafraid to speak its name? No, because most "Virgin" businesses are less than 100% Virginal. Contrary to appearances, no single umbrella group owns them. Virgin Retail <font size=-1>UK</font>, for instance, which runs a chain of vast urban music shops known as Virgin Megastores, is only 25% owned by Virgin. The other 75% is owned by WH Smith, a British newsagent and bookshop chain. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Only one widely known Virgin business is in fact wholly owned by the group. That is Virgin Atlantic Airways, the largest subsidiary of the Virgin Travel Group. Virgin also owns 100% of <font size=-1>V2</font>, a record company started in November 1996 that has just released its first record. But Virgin Records, which is well known, is no longer a Virgin business at all; it was sold to Thorn <font size=-1>EMI</font>, a (recently demerged) British record and electrical-goods company, for &#163;560m in 1992. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, not every business in which Virgin has a stake carries the magic name. Rodney Fitch and Company, 50% owned by Virgin and 50% by Mr Fitch, its founder, is a design consultancy which advises companies on developing brand image. Although Virgin has excelled in building its own brand, clients might not want to feel they were getting a Virgin makeover. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The structure of the Virgin empire is complex. Eager to cut costs, Mr Branson has established a network of holding companies and offshore trusts which help the group to minimise its tax liability. More than 20 companies operate the main businesses, which can be broadly grouped into eight divisions (see <a href="wb5.gif">box</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So what is Virgin if not a conglomerate or a single company? In terms of turnover, multiplied by Virgin's share of the business, the airline is dominant. Its turnover is considerably bigger than the Virgin share of all the other businesses combined. But Virgin is not an airline with sidelines in cola and music either. Mr Branson's answer is that Virgin's structure is more like an Asian business empire, in which divisions making different products operate as separately traded companies, owning stakes in each other and sharing a name and an ethos. In "The World in 1997", an <i>Economist</i> publication, he cites the example of Mitsubishi, a family of companies making cars, textiles, electrical goods and including a bank. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jeff Rayport of Harvard Business School suggests another analogy. The only brands that can match Virgin for scope are entertainment and celebrity brands. Disney can tap hamburger boxes and toys with its wand and help them to sell, or construct an entire village in Florida--besides making films and running theme parks. Michael Jordan plays lucrative basketball but also exudes endorsements for shoes, sports equipment, cosmetics and a host of other products. Brands of this sort are tied not to the characteristics of a set of products, but to emotional associations. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence the importance of Mr Branson to Virgin's fortunes. Apart from owning much of the company, he embodies several appealing and, in Britain, rare qualities: the upstart who takes on big bullies and wins; the daredevil whose risks sometimes land him in trouble; and the innovator who finds a better way to do something than stodgy established businesses. Whenever the British are asked by opinion pollsters to suggest ideal prime ministers, replacements for the queen, or even authors for a modern ten commandments, Mr Branson's name is often first on their lips. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This gives Virgin tremendous suppleness as a company, but there are risks. The most serious is of starting a business that fails to embody Virgin values. A Virgin operation that served customers badly would poison the magic potion. The group's recent rapid growth enlarges this risk, since Virgin has started to buy existing businesses rather than to build them from scratch. Virgin Express, for example, was operating as Euro Belgian Airlines when Virgin bought it in April 1996, and the staff have not been steeped in Virgin culture. Maintaining Virgin's commitment to quality and friendliness in an operation whose mission was to provide bargain-basement travel will be particularly tricky. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other sort of risk that Virgin faces is that something will happen to its celebrity chairman. The dangerous descent into the North African desert of the <i>Virgin Global Challenger</i> balloon is not the first time Mr Branson's life has been in jeopardy. During an early skydiving lesson Mr Branson had to be rescued by his instructor, James Bond-style, in mid-air after he accidentally unhooked his parachute. Hair's-breadth escapes enrich the Branson image, but a less happy ending would leave Virgin hollow. Hence recent talk by Mr Branson and his colleagues of Virgin's "brand values"-- quality, innovation, value for money, and fun--in an attempt to distinguish the company's strength from the vigour of its boss. For Virgin's sake, and that of its well entertained customers, the hope must be that they are being overcautious. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
