<html><head><title>Darkness at noon</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Darkness at noon</h1>

<p><b>The Gulf war against Iraq in 1991 was swift, and allied casualties were few. But since then, some veterans of the war have suffered from a mysterious illness known as "Gulf-war syndrome". Although theories--and conspiracy theories--abound, it may be impossible ever to know for sure what caused it</b></p><br>
ON MARCH 1st 1991, the day after fighting ended in the Gulf war against Iraq, the noon skies in parts of the theatre of war were black with the smoke from burning oil wells. Three days later, American soldiers destroyed an Iraqi munitions depot at Khamisiyah in the south of the country. This site is now thought to have contained chemical weapons--in particular, sarin nerve gas. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Throughout the conflict, and in the months before it began, fear of chemical weapons had led large numbers of allied troops to take a drug called pyridostigmine bromide (<font size=-1>PB</font>). Fear of biological weapons and infectious diseases had led to the large-scale vaccination of troops against many different organisms and biological toxins. In order to control insects--both for sanitation and for the prevention of insect-borne diseases--pesticides were used frequently and heavily in some army camps. And blazing sun, blowing sand and biting sandflies further increased the discomfort and stress of military life in the desert.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So although the fighting on the ground lasted for only 100 hours and inflicted fewer casualties on the victors' side than any other modern war, the living and fighting conditions were harsh and unpleasant. But did they make people sick?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Answering this question is a little like an enormous game of Cluedo (or Clue as Americans know it) with half the cards missing. There are too many suspects, not enough alibis, and much of the necessary information has vanished. Even the simplest problems--how, for instance, did the French mysteriously avoid illnesses that British and American troops complain of?--are hard to answer. The fundamental ones--Who? Where? And with what?--will probably never be solved--even assuming there was a crime in the first place.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Malingering doubts</b></b><br>
The maladies claimed by veterans of the conflict are many and various. They include skin rashes, nausea, digestive problems, muscle spasms, fatigue, joint pain, lethargy, headaches, memory loss, concentration problems, sleep disorders, mood changes and birth defects--an unpleasant but amorphous group. Each of the environmental hazards described above has been suspected as a cause. And, both in America and in Britain, the way in which the military establishments have tried to explain what happened has been sufficiently incompetent that they are now suspected by many of hiding something.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This means that the latest (though by no means the last) word on the matter--the lengthy final report by the Presidential Advisory Committee on Gulf-war veterans' illnesses, presented to President Clinton on January 7th--is likely to be controversial. The report, by far the most extensive to date, has been assembled from a review of all the available epidemiological and medical data--and testimony from the defence department, the Veterans' Administration, American Gulf-war veterans and scientists.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The report concludes that although many Gulf-war veterans are indeed unwell, there is no single, clinically recognisable disease that can be called "Gulf-war syndrome". It goes on to argue that none of the symptoms can be attributed to any of the putative risk factors (although it emphasises that more information on troops' exposure to chemical weapons does need to be collected), and that the most likely cause of health problems is stress.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In America, the pet theory of many groups of servicemen and women (and the general public) has been that those troops who are suffering are sick because of exposure to chemical weapons. On the face of it, the argument looks pretty good. Nerve gas was noticed by Czech military teams (which are among the best in the world at detecting biological and chemical weapons) on January 19th 1991--two days after the beginning of the war on the ground. Five days later, the same teams detected mustard gas. Moreover, chemical-weapons alarms went off frequently during combat--and were as frequently ignored (the detectors often reacted to such things as petrol fumes).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But since the war, <font size=-1>UNSCOM</font>, the United Nations Special Commission on Iraq, which is charged with the unenviable job of eliciting information from the Iraqis on their weapons programmes, has found that while Iraq did possess chemical weapons, there is no evidence that they were used during the Gulf war. The most likely explanation for any low-level exposure to mustard gas or nerve gas is that these poisons were accidentally released by allied destruction of Iraqi weapons stores.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the defence department has been slow to admit that this could have been the case. It was not until last summer that it was conceded that American troops could have been exposed to sarin during and after the demolition of the Khamisiyah munitions depot. And, at first, the Pentagon's estimates of exposure were low-- around 400 troops. It was then forced to revise them upwards to around 20,000. All this has led to allegations of a conspiracy and cover-up. Members of the Presidential Advisory Committee did not find any evidence that there has been such a cover-up, although they have strongly condemned the Pentagon's behaviour. However, there are a number of scientific arguments against the chemical-weapons hypothesis for Gulf-war illnesses.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Nasty stuff</b></b><br>
At the start of the Gulf war, the Iraqis were suspected of having at least four different chemical weapons. Besides mustard gas and sarin, they were believed to have stockpiled soman and tabun, two other nerve gases. The risk that these weapons might have been used was real: Saddam Hussein had already dropped mustard gas, at least, on Iranians during the Iran-Iraq war, and on Iraqi Kurds.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mustard gas made its debut during the first world war. It burns tissues it comes into contact with, and in large doses, it can reach the bone marrow--where many cells of the immune system are made--and may cause severe depression of the immune system one to two weeks after exposure.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nerve gases belong to a class of compounds called organophosphates. They work by blocking the action of an enzyme known as acetylcholinesterase. This enzyme is crucial for the proper action of nerves and the muscles they control. Acetylcholine is a neurotransmitter--one of the chemical messengers that carry signals from one nerve to another. The job of the enzyme is to mop up surplus acetylcholine. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the mopping up is prevented, the nerve does not know when to stop firing-- and muscles go into spasms. At low concentrations, symptoms of nerve-gas poisoning include loss of vision, salivation, breathlessness and headaches. At high concentrations, people may stop breathing altogether. It was to combat this that many American and British troops were issued with <font size=-1>PB</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The drug works against nerve gases in a counter-intuitive way: it also blocks the action of acetylcholinesterase. The difference between <font size=-1>PB</font> and a nerve gas is that <font size=-1>PB</font> is reversible. Whereas a nerve gas takes acetylcholinesterase out of commission forever, <font size=-1>PB</font> slowly lets it loose again. So the idea was that if <font size=-1>PB</font> was already interrupting the action of say 20-40% of the enzyme, then that 20-40% would not be available to be blocked by nerve gases. Instead, as troops came into contact with nerve gases, they would not suffer as much because <font size=-1>PB</font> would slowly render more of the crucial enzyme available again.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem with this idea is that <font size=-1>PB</font> does have the potential to make people feel sick at the time, and an overdose could be quite severe. This has led to suggestions that even if troops were not exposed to nerve gases, some of their current problems could be due to <font size=-1>PB</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there was another class of acetylcholinesterase inhibitor present in the Gulf: pesticides. The pesticides used by many troops involved in the conflict were also organophosphates--in effect, they were nerve gases for bugs. In order to be fatal in people, such substances need to be taken in much higher doses than an anti-human nerve gas. Nonetheless, they are nasty.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the autumn of 1996, Nicholas Soames, Britain's armed forces minister, was forced to admit that the House of Commons had been misled about the use of pesticides in the Gulf, and that such use had been far more extensive than anyone had said. Whether this concealment was deliberate or just a result of bungling is not clear--but again, it did not look good, and it damaged public confidence.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each of these possibilities--low level exposures to nerve gases, the use of <font size=-1>PB</font> and the deployment of pesticides--has fallen under suspicion as a possible cause of Gulf-war illnesses. But so far, the data (which are still incomplete) are inconsistent with what is known about these substances.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For one thing, the symptoms should have been apparent from the start. However, according to members of the Presidential Advisory Committee, there are no records of health complaints during the war that are consistent with mild nerve-gas exposure. And although some sheep farmers who have used organophosphates in sheep dips have complained of ill health that is similar to that experienced by veterans of the Gulf war, sheep farmers, according to Alastair Hay, a chemical pathologist at the University of Leeds, usually report feeling bad at the time, as well as going on to have subtle neurological problems later.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After reviewing the available data--including what little there is on neurological damage among Gulf-war veterans--the Presidential Advisory Committee failed to find credible evidence that any of these substances could have caused the problems seen among American forces in the Gulf. This result is likely to be hotly disputed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Goran Jamal, a neurologist at the University of Glasgow, for instance, argues that his results show clear neurological damage among Gulf-war veterans. In a report to be published in the January 15th issue of the <i>Journal of the American Medi cal Association</i>, Robert Haley, of the University of Texas South Western Medical Centre, in Dallas, reports similar data--and claims that he has found evidence for three distinct Gulf-war illnesses. However, the sample sizes for all the neurological work done so far are tiny, making it difficult to draw firm conclusions. Moreover, it is possible that in combination, the effects of organophosphates could be more dangerous-- something on which the committee recommends further study. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What of the other alleged risk factors? Despite claims of a number of unusual diseases--for example, Garth Nicolson, a doctor at the University of California, Irvine, says he has found a strange organism called <i>Mycoplamsa fermentans</i> in the bodies of some veterans of the Gulf war--infection, whether naturally occurring or deliberately triggered as an act of war, does not seem to be implicated in the unexplained illnesses of veterans.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Iraqis have now confessed to <font size=-1>UNSCOM</font> that they had indeed developed a frightening array of biological weapons (although the claims have proved extremely difficult to verify). But there is no evidence that biological weapons were used in the war; nor is there evidence that biological agents were accidentally released as a result of allied bombing. Indeed, as one British general has observed, the war in the Gulf led to fewer deaths from disease than any previous conflict involving the British army. During the Crimean war, for instance, far more British troops died of cholera than died in battle.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Actual disease is not the only suspect, however. Many British servicemen reckon that their ill health was caused by preventative measures against disease: vaccinations. Both British and American troops were vaccinated against an enormous array of diseases--including possible biological weapons. But again, although some people did report feeling unwell after vaccination, there is no evidence other than anecdote that suggests that the vaccines were at fault.<br>
</p><p><b><b>What about the data?</b></b><br>
Out of any large group of people, as time goes by, some will get sick. So in order to establish whether or not service in the Gulf has caused an illness, or a number of illnesses, it is important to compare different groups of people, to see what the differences are. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For example, the rate of birth defects in the population at large is quite high. According to the Presidential Advisory Committee's final report, from any sample of 200,000 American children, you would expect to see about 6,000 born with defects. So in order to address the emotive question of whether service in the Gulf causes birth defects, it is important to determine that there are more birth defects than expected. So far, the data suggest that this is not the case (although the British are just about to start a large study to investigate it in their forces).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor is there any evidence so far that service in the Gulf was more likely to kill mysteriously than service elsewhere at the same time--or than life as an American civilian. A study published in the <i>New England Journal of Medicine</i> in November 1995 compared the death rates of 695,516 American troops who had served in the Gulf with 746,291 troops on active duty elsewhere. It found that although Gulf-war veterans were significantly more likely to have died between the end of the war and September 30th 1993 (the date the study ended), the extra deaths were caused by accidents, not disease. In addition, members of both groups of servicemen were less likely to have died than the average American--reflecting the fact that in order to be in the armed forces at all, physical fitness must be high. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, although it is clear that some people are sick with diseases that cannot easily be explained, except by service in the Gulf, it is not certain how many of them there are. Among American troops, estimates have ranged from 1,000 to 80,000.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best guesses come from the numbers of people who have presented themselves for physical examinations, either on their own initiative, or at the behest of veterans' groups. In America, according to the advisory committee, roughly 62,000 individuals have had physical examinations in the Veterans' Administration Persian Gulf Health Registry, and more than 34,000 people have requested examination by the defence department's Comprehensive Clinical Evaluation Programme. However, of these, roughly 10% have no detectable health problems, and the complaints of many others are just run-of-the-mill. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Britain, where alleged cases of Gulf-war illness have generally been reported more slowly, roughly 1,100 (out of around 51,000) troops have come forward with complaints. According to a spokesman at Britain's Ministry of Defence, of the roughly 900 who have been examined so far, 20% have health problems that are hard to explain. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But meanwhile, in France, which also sent troops to the Gulf, no one has complained of Gulf-war illnesses, despite extensive publicity about the syndrome as described in Britain and America, and despite apparent efforts by the French armed forces to conduct random studies and health tests of their troops. This is curious--and is so far unexplained.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To account for it, three hypotheses can be imagined. First, members of the French forces might be less likely to complain of feeling sick--perhaps because of cultural differences within the army. Second, British and American troops might be more likely to over-report illnesses--perhaps because of differences in benefits that could be claimed in compensation. Third--and most tantalising--there may have been real differences between what happened to different groups of soldiers in the Gulf.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The French contingent was smaller than the British one--in all, 13,500 French troops served in the Gulf. Moreover, as the French were not part of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s joint military command at the time, they could not be integrated into British or American units. This meant that the French were not in the same places as the other allied forces. However, French units did serve in the front line--and according to French military sources, were sometimes far in advance of other troops at the front. Also, French liaison officers worked alongside Anglo-American liaison officers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there are some potentially interesting differences. According to Fran&ccedil;oise Rota, who served in the Gulf as a medical officer and is now a senior doctor in the French army, her fellow citizens did two things differently.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Firstly, they did not use many of the vaccines that the British and the Americans used. In particular, they did not vaccinate against anthrax, a common component of biological weapons, and a disease endemic to the Gulf anyway. Nor did they take preventative measures against botulinum toxin--another component of biological weapons, and one of the most poisonous substances known. Indeed, according to Colonel Rota, they did not even administer <font size=-1>PB</font> to their troops.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Secondly, the French camps were not sprayed with insecticides as a preventative measure--rather, spraying was done only when it was needed to control pest populations. And, according to some reports, when they did spray, the French did not use organophosphates.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Also, in addition to these differences, the French troops were nowhere near the munitions depot at Khamisiyah when the destruction took place.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, no studies have compared the experiences of different groups of servicemen who were in the Gulf. Doing so will be difficult. In order to tell whether people with headaches, say, had one set of vaccinations while people with joint pain had another, it is necessary to have extensive information on who took what and was exposed to what when. This information does not exist. Both the Americans and the British have lost vaccination records. In any case, though records were kept as to which units were where in the Gulf, more often than not individuals did not stay with their units, rendering accurate assessment of risks impossible.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is unfortunate, and unsatisfactory (especially to those who are seriously sick). But perhaps it is not unexpected. The primary job of an army is to fight battles, not to collect medical data. But after every major war this century, ex-soldiers have complained of mysterious diseases. And as the nature of war changes, so that death and disease at the time become less likely, it is right that greater attention should be paid to the future health of troops.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Devising ways to collect data reliably without interfering with military operations, and pursuing research into the effects of the toxic and debilitating compounds used in modern war, and into the effects of prolonged stress on the body, should have a higher priority. That way, problems after the next conflict may be resolved more quickly. For despite the latest report, the arguments over Gulf-war illnesses will not go away for many years to come.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
