<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Bibliography for Survey of Defence Technology</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H1>The Softwar Revolution </H1><H3>A survey of defence technology</H3><HR><P>This is a bibliography for the survey of defence technology thatappeared in the June 10th 1995 issue of <A href="http://www.economist.com/econ.html"><i>The Economist</i></A>.It includes some interpolations--works that were not used butcited so frequently in other material that they seemed to belonghere. Annotations are merely for guidance; they are not meantto single out the most important and influential works. Apologiesfor no hot-links to the sources listed.<HR><P><B>Bibliography</B> <P>Aftergood, Steve; Monitoring Emerging Military Technologies; FASPublic interest report, Vol. 48, No.1; Federation of AmericanScientists 1995<P>Alexander, John; Non-lethal weapons as force options for the armyLos Alamos National Laboratory LA-UR 94-861<P>Alexander, John; Non-lethal weapons and the future of war; LosAlamos National Laboratory LA-UR 95-699<P>Anderson, Jon Lee; Guerrillas: The inside stories of the world'srevolutionaries; Harper Collins 1993<P>Arnett, Eric; Welcome to hyperwar; Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists,48,7 September 1992<P>Arquilla, John and Ronfeldt, David; ``Cyberwar is coming!''; Comparativestrategy 12,2 1993 <I>Particularly thought provoking. </I><P>Atkinson, Rick Crusade: The Untold Story of the Gulf War; HarperCollins 1994<P>Barnes, Julian; Trap. Dominate. Fuck; Granta 47 1994 <I>An enthrallingaccount of strategy on the chessboard in the Short-Kasparov match</I><P>Bergman, Magnus et al; Smyge-YS 2000 Future Projects: Swedishdevelopment of state of the art surface combatants; Paper presentedat IMDEX '95<P>Boyd, John R; A discourse on winning and losing unpublished lectureslides <I>One of those interpolations; I'd love to get a set.</I><P>Burrows, William E; Deep Black The secrets of space espionage;Bantam 1986<P>Burrows, Williams E &amp; Windrem, Robert; Critical Mass: Thedangerous race for superweapons in a fragmenting world Simon &amp;Schuster 1994<P>Burton, James G; The Pentagon Wars Reformers challenge the OldGuard; Naval Institute Press 1993<P>Canavan, Gregory; Simulation, computing, information and futurewarfare; Los Alamos National Laboratory LA-12490-MS<P>Canavan, Gregory; The future of conventional defence researchat Los Alamos; Los Alamos National Laboratory 1993 LA-12576-MS<I>Here be chickens</I> <P>Canavan, Gregory and Teller, Edward; Strategic Defence for the1990s; Nature 344, pp 699-704 19th April 1990 <I>Canonical brilliantpebbles paper</I> <P>Clancy, Tom; Debt of Honour; Harper Collins, 1994 <I>A lot ofpeople I interviewed were reading this or had just finished it.</I><P>Clausewitz, Carl von; On War (Howard, Michael &amp; Paret, PeterEds); Princeton University Press 1984<P>Cohen, Eliot; The Mystique of US Air Power; Foreign Affairs Jan/Feb1994<P>Cohen, Eliot; Down the hatch; The New Republic, March 7, 1994<I>A critique of the bottom up review</I> <P>Cooper, Jeffrey R; Another view of the revolution in militaryaffairs; Strategic Studies Institute US Army War College 1994<P>Coulombe, Stephen A; The Airborne Laser: Pie in the sky or visionof future theater missile defense?; Airpower Journal VIII, Fall1994<P>Creveld, Martin van; Command and War; Harvard University Press1985<P>Creveld, Martin van; Technology and War From 2000 BC to the present;Free Press 1989<P>Creveld, Martin van; The Transformation of War; Free Press, 1991Also pub'd as ``On future War''<P>Creveld, Martin van; Nuclear Proliferation and the Future of Conflict;Free Press 1993<P>Davies, James &amp; Bagulich, Richard; An introduction to go;Ishi press 1984<P>Davis, Paul K (Ed.); New challenges for Defense Planning: Rethinkinghow much is enough; RAND 1994<P>Davis, Richard et al/GAO; Cruise Missiles: Proven capability shouldaffect aircraft &amp; force structure requirement; General AccountingOffice, 1995<P>Defense Budget Project; Funding innovation: Low-cost options forleveraging the military revolution (discussion paper) 1995 <I>Aneat shopping list</I> <P>De Landa, Manuel; War in the Age of Intelligent Machines; Zonebooks, 1991<P>Deleuze, Gilles &amp; Guattari, Felix; Nomadology: The War Machine;Semiotext(e) 1986 <I>Hard core French philosophising. Intriguingon chess and go.</I> <P>Der Derian, James; Antidiplomacy: Spies, Terror, Speed, and War;Blackwell 1992<P>Der Derian, James; Cyber-deterrence; Wired 2.09 1994<P>The Digital Battlefield; Proceedings of a conference; TechnicalMarketing Society of America 1995 <I>This may have more acronymsand initialisations in it than any other document I have everseen; which just shows that I ain't seen nothing yet.</I> <P>Dixon, Norman; On the psychology of military incompetence; JonathanCape 1976 (Pimlico 1994)<P>Dyson, Freeman; Weapons &amp; Hope; Harper &amp; Row 1984 <I>Thoughit addresses the nuclear cold war, this is still extremely relevant</I><P>Dyson, Freeman; Infinite in all directions; Harper and Row 1998<P>Ederington, L Benjamin and Mazarr, Michael J (Eds); Turning Point:The Gulf war and US military strategy; Westview 1994<P>Ellis, John; The Social History of the Machine Gun; Croom Helm1976 (Pimlico 1993) <I>How a weapon can change things</I> <P>Fitzsimonds, James &amp; Jol, James van; Revolutions in militaryaffairs; Joint Force Quarterly, Spring 1994 <I>A straightforwardversion of the Andrew Marshall line</I> <P>Flanagan, Edward M; Lightning: The 101st in the Gulf War; Brasseys1994 <I>How helicopters fought in the desert</I> <P>Franklin, H. Bruce; War Stars: The Superweapon and the AmericanImagination; Oxford U.P. 1988 <I>A mixture of social history,literary criticism and polemic, excellent in all departments</I><P>Freedman, Lawrence (Ed); War; Oxford 1994 <I>A reader</I> <P>Haldeman, Joe; The Forever War; Orbit, 1976 <I>A fictional accountof what relativity can do to your OODA loop, and a memorable critiqueof the following</I> <P>Heinlein, Robert; Starship Troopers; Putnam, 1959 <I>The definitivepiece of science fiction militarism; stresses esprit de corpsand communications as much as fire power</I> <P>Helvajian, H. &amp; Robinson, E Y; Micro &amp; Nanotechnologyfor space systems: An initial evaluation; The Aerospace corporation1993 <I>Really tiny satellites</I> <P>Hirsch, John L &amp; Oakley, Robert B; Somalia and operation restorehope: Reflections on peacemaking &amp; peacekeeping; United StatedInsitute of Peace 1995<P>Homer-Dixon, Thomas; On the Threshold: Environmental changes ascauses of acute conflict; International security, Fall 1991<P>Jones, Joseph; Stealth technology: The art of black magic; Tubbooks 1989 <I>Not entirely accurate, I suspect, but apparentlya good primer</I> <P>Kahaluni, Avigdor; The Heights of Courage: A tank leader's waron the Golan; Greenwood Press 1984 <I>A demonstration of how muchcommunciations matter</I> <P>Kanter, Arnold &amp; Brooks, Linton F; US intervention policyfor the Post-Cold war world: New challenges &amp; new responses;W W Norton 1994<P>Keegan, John A; history of Warfare; Pimlico 1994<P>Kelly, Kevin; Out of Control: The rise of neo-biological civilization;Addison-Wesley 1994 <I>Contains more on what distributed systemsmight be, might mean and might become than anything else</I> <P>Kidder, Tracy; The Siege of Mirebalais; The New Yorker April 17th1995 <I>An illuminating account of the special forces in Haiti</I><P>Konrad, George; Antipolitics; Trans. Richard Allen; Quartet books1984<P>Krepinevich, Andrew F; Keeping pace with the Military-Technologicalrevolution; Issues in Science &amp; Technology Summer 1994 <I>Athorough assessment of the policy implications of a military revolution</I><P>Krepinevich, Andrew F; Cavalry to Computer: The pattern of militaryrevolutions; The National Interest Fall 1994<P>Lakoff, Sanford and York, Herbert; A shield in space: Technology,Politics and the Strategic Defense Initiative; University of CaliforniaPress <I>A thorough, critical, assessment</I> <P>Leonhard, Robert R; The Art of Maneuver: Maneuver-warfare theoryand AirLand battle; Presidio 1991 <I>I found this an excellentintroduction to a number of debates</I> <P>Leonhard, Robert R; Fighting by minutes: Time and the art of war;Prager 1994<P>Letot, Laurent &amp; Vignand, Bernard; Evolution in Surface Combatant;Stealth Paper given at IMDEX '95<P>Libicki, Martin C; The Mesh and the Net: Speculations on ArmedConflict in a Time of free silicon; National Defense University1994 <I>Bravura stuff</I> <P>Libicki, Martin and Haglett, James; Do we need an informationcorps?; Joint Force Quarterly Autumn 1993<P>MacKenzie, Donald; Inventing Accuracy: A historical sociologyof nuclear missile guidance; MIT press 1990<P>Mandelbaam, Michael; Lessons of the next nuclear war; ForeignAffairs March/ April 1995<P>Mann, Edward; Desert Storm: The first information war?; Airpowerjournal VIII No. 4 Winter 1994<P>Mazarr, Michael et al; The Military Technical Revolution: a structuralframework; Centre for Strategic and International Studies 1993<I>A fine overview</I> <P>Metz, Steven &amp; Kievit, James; The revolution in military affairsand conflict short of war; Strategic Studies Institute US ArmyWar College 1994<P>Millot, Marc Dean, Molander, Roger &amp; Wilson, Peter A; ``TheDay After...'' study: Nuclear Proliferation in the Post-Cold WarWorld; RAND 1993 3 vols<P>Molander, Roger and Wilson, Peter; On dealing with the prospectof nuclear chaos; The Washington Quarterly 17:3 Summer 1993<P>Morris, Janet &amp; Morris, Chris; Nonlethality: a global strategy;Morris &amp; Morris, 1994 <I>Two of the prophets of non-lethality</I><P>Munro, Neil; Electronic Combat &amp; Modern Warfare: The Quickand the Dead; Macmillan 1991<P>Norris, Christopher; Uncritical Theory: Postmodernism, Intellectuals&amp; the Gulf War; Laurence &amp; Wrihart 1992 <I>A worthwhileattack on Baudrillard</I> <P>Owens, William A; JROC: Harnessing the Revolution in MilitaryAffairs; Joint Forces Quarterly, Summer 1994<P>Owens, William A; High Seas: The Naval Passage to an UncharteredWorld; Naval Institute Press 1995<P>Paschell, Rod L.I.C.; 2010 Special operations &amp; unconventionalwarfare in the next century; Brassey's 1990<P>Pike, John; Waiting for Starfleet (discussion paper) 1995<P>Rich, Ben R &amp; Janos, Leo; Skunk Works: A personal memoir ofmy years at Lockheed; Little, Brown 1994 <I>Fascinating and fun</I><P>Rosen, Stephen Peter; Winning the next war: Innovation &amp; themodern military; Cornell University Press 1991 <I>A set of studiesof successful and unsuccessful innovations</I> <P>Skukman, David; The Sorcerer's Challenge: Fears and Hopes forthe Weapons of the next Millennium; Hodder &amp; Stoughton 1995<P>Smallwood, William L; Warthog: Flying the A-10 in the Gulf War;Brassey's 1993 <I>A fan's account that shows how much resourcefulinnovation is possible when a weapons system finally goes to war.</I><P>Spacecast 2020; Air University 1994<P>Star 21: Strategic technologies for the army of the 21st century;National Research Council 1993<P>Sterling, Bruce; We see things differently in Semiotext(e) SF;Semiotexte 1989 <I>Rock music, assassination, drugs and geopolitics</I><P>Sterling, Bruce; War is virtual hell; Wired 1.01, 1993<P>Sun Tzu; The Art of War (Translated by Samuel B. Griffith); OxfordUniversity Press 1971<P>Szafranski, Richard; A theory of information warfare: Preparingfor 2020; Airpower Jou