</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>Warp speed</H1><P><I> Technology is rapidly changing the way financial services are designed and delivered, argues Andrew Freeman. That is because businesses have at last learnt how to use it</I><p ><br>CONSIDER this vision of finance. Artificially intelligent agents plan their clients' investment and transaction needs, constantly finding the best prices on 24-hour electronic financial markets and managing their assets to meet defined risk-reward targets. Businesses send and settle their bills instantly (or, as the jargon has it, in real time), and raise any working or other capital they need by advertising to investors on global computer bulletin boards. And, operating under the auspices of a global sales-tax authority, digital money systems make electronic commerce indistinguishable from physical trade.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How realistic is that vision&#063; On the face of it, not very. Some of the technologies, notably artificial intelligence, are only nascent today. Other details, such as a global tax authority, seem pretty unlikely. And, according to some observers, digital money is riddled with hopeless security flaws.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet a deeper look at today's financial-services industry makes the vision seem suddenly more plausible. Automated financial planning is appearing rapidly in retail finance. Electronic marketplaces are developing for insurance and mutual funds, as well as for low-cost share trading. Some small firms already raise money by appealing direct to investors, bypassing traditional financial intermediaries (though not yet lawyers and accountants). Companies everywhere are racing to offer consumers electronic access to their products, usually by setting up a Web site on the Internet. "Virtual" banks are touting cyber-payment systems. Investment banks are using mind-boggling mathematics to run complex portfolios of financial instruments, borrowing liberally from quantum physics. Financial firms are pouring money into information technology, and are expected to go on doing so (see <a href="tf1.gif">chart</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So even radical forecasts should, it seems, be taken seriously. If they are not, today's insurers, banks and brokers could turn out to be dinosaurs, with new technologies playing the role of the destructive meteor, and only a few surviving in unpredictable new forms. More technologically adept creatures may take over, remaking the industry along entirely different lines.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps. Yet rapid technological change is confusing--and radical forecasts are easily hyped. Past waves of innovation produced forecasts that proved wildly inaccurate. Remember electronic home banking, which was accorded revolutionary status in the early 1980s, but failed to take off&#063; Embarrassed bankers do, and their experience is a good reason for financial firms' careful attitude towards such novel phenomena as the Internet.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, many banks have learnt that revolutions are not made by new machines alone. Changing the way people behave is often more important. As Martin Taylor, chief executive of Britain's Barclays Bank, says: "The industry taught people to associate banking with visiting marble halls that were almost like cathedrals. Now we're telling them it's all right to pray at home. But we have to understand that money, our product, has a lot of sociological encrustations which we can't remove simply by changing the way we view our business."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As this survey explores technology and its impact on finance and financial services (mainly in America, which is the furthest ahead in this field), it will therefore pay close attention to two groups of people. One is the managers of financial firms. After several decades of wrestling with technology, the best have recently begun to harness and use it more intelligently. Their recognition that firms can do things in new ways lies behind this survey's central proposition: that, thanks to technology, financial services are on the cusp of dramatic change.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second group is composed of people who buy and use financial services. Their increasing familiarity with technology is a powerful force for change. But they can be recalcitrant, resisting innovations in favour of tried and tested procedures. Metal coins, paper money and cheques are still ubiquitous (see <a href="tf2.gif">chart</a>) compared with electronics. Consumer preferences are often at odds with the innovative impulses of service providers.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence this survey's crucial caveat. In so far as technology is changing finance, it is not because of a particular invention or insight. Rather, it is doing so when the new techniques are broadly in sympathy with how people and firms wish to conduct their financial affairs. For almost the first time, leading financial-services firms are trying to understand their customers' desires and to shape their businesses to meet them--at a suitable profit.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That may mean moving into areas far removed from the traditional terrain of finance. Or it may mean breaking from traditional process-driven ways of doing things and re-examining what a financial firm actually does. This is the financial-services equivalent of "business-process re-engineering", the management fad of the early 1990s. It has the potential to change an entire commercial model. And that, after decades of false dawns, is what technology may at last be delivering.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf2.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
