<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>The machine age</H1><P><I>Past technologies merely automated the processes of finance</I><p ><br>"THE system is used in factories of all sorts, in steel mills, by insurance companies&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;by textile mills, automobile companies, numerous railroads, municipalities and state governments. It is used for compiling labour costs, efficiency records, distribution of sales, internal requisitions for supplies and materials, production statistics, day and piece work&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;for analysing risks in life, fire and casualty insurance&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;for distributing sales and cost figures as to salesmen, department, customer, location, commodity, method of sale."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The odd archaism aside, this quote&#042; reads uncannily like a description of a 1960s mainframe computer system. In fact it dates from half a century earlier. An enthusiastic American journalist is describing the impact of the electro-mechanical punch-card machines that preceded digital computers. By 1911 Herman Hollerith's Tabulating Machine Company had around 100 customers. That year Hollerith sold the firm for $2.3m and watched it merge with two other companies to become the Computer Tabulating-Recording Company. In 1924 it became International Business Machines.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Punch cards certainly had a huge influence on businesses of all sorts, including financial ones. Indeed, they did not become obsolete until the 1960s, when digital computers took over. The long-time prevalence of cards had a profound effect on how financial firms used technology. In part thanks to their technical limitations, computing machines were seen almost entirely as a means of automating manual processes. There was little concept of data storage (memory was primitive and expensive until the digital era), and only limited ability to compile data in forms that could be analysed.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Early computing systems were usually designed to be more efficient "analogues" of existing physical business systems that relied on hand-written ledgers and paper chains. Punch cards also led to an approach which took it for granted that processing would be done in batch cycles: literally the batches of cards that could be fed into machines running a single program. So the computing infrastructure of financial services mirrored its physical infrastructure. Cheque-processing systems, credit-accounting systems, even banks' general ledgers, were reproduced first in card and then in digital form. This analogue tendency persisted in the 1960s and 1970s when big firms installed mainframes.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The race was now for efficiencies in processing. A new generation of managers, exemplified by John Reed of America's Citibank, extolled the virtues of process engineering and tried to import technologies from manufacturing into finance. Paper was anathema. Machines replaced clerks. But the nature of the underlying jobs was unchanged. As one senior banker explains, the first mistake that everybody made was to suppose that their existing model was the right one and that computers could be used in some way to make it more efficient.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In retrospect this is somewhat ironic. Managers knew that information was the essence of finance. Yet they built huge, expensive systems that simply dealt with processes and transactions, with no effect on how their firms captured and monitored information. Although this meant greater speed and fewer errors, it profoundly limited the impact of technology on the managers' business.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is largely because they were concentrating on aspects of finance which could confer few if any competitive advantages. Activities such as cheque processing are now rather like utilities. Reflecting that, they are fertile ground for "outsourcing" to low-cost specialist firms. Another consequence was that competitors that were slow to adopt technology were not fundamentally disadvantaged. If they stuck with manual processes, their competitive handicap was marginal rather than profound.<br><b><p>The competitive advantage of banks<br></b>Where, then, does competitive advantage in financial services lie&#063; Not in the transaction itself, perhaps; but certainly in the information typically embedded within it. What is a customer doing; how might this be different from his normal behaviour; does it expose either customer or financier to any risks which could or should be hedged&#063; These are questions that hint at where value resides. And, as we shall see, they are precisely the kinds of questions that financial managers are now, thanks to information technology, better able to answer.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Information of this type has, to be sure, always existed in finance. Firms created repositories for it intuitively and trusted that they could be used to make decisions. The repositories were not big central databases; they were people. Think of a broker's intimate knowledge of customers' investment goals and trading preferences. Or of insurance agents' grasp of the lifetime coverage needs of families. Perhaps most obvious of all, remember the local bank branch manager, whose social standing reflected his implicit lending power as well as his explicit knowledge of local connections.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By scattering these human repositories as widely as they could, banks and other financial firms built what were in effect information networks. In some cases, however, regulation forbade far-flung networks--American banks were until recently banned from branching across state lines. That made the banks more vulnerable to cyclical swings in profitability. In any case, there was seldom much of an attempt at useful aggregation of information. True, insurers built detailed models of mortality rates or theft claims. But they had little sense of whether their relationship with particular customers were profitable, or of whether the customers had bought an appropriate array of policies.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lack of specific knowledge about customers combined with high distribution costs to shape financial services in another way. Financial products tended to be uniform, regardless of who bought them. Only the super-rich could afford, say, insurance that was tailored to their needs. Most people bought standard products, often paying for elements they did not need or, perhaps worse, forgoing elements they might have found useful.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Extracting specific customer information from firms' process-driven systems was technically difficult and financially prohibitive--at least until recently. A big technological breakthrough came in the mid-1980s when faster and cheaper computer chips made possible the development of "middleware", or sophisticated systems that sit between mainframes and desk-top terminals and facilitate both data extraction and analysis.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The development of big relational databases also conferred an advantage on firms dealing with huge amounts of data. Falling communication costs removed another barrier to the creation of sophisticated computer networks, permitting the linking of previously disparate systems. These systems are now central to financial firms' ability to derive useful knowledge from their otherwise dumb data. Indeed, it has become <i>de rigueur </i>in some financial circles to have a "data warehouse": a somewhat misleading term for large systems for data storage and analysis.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peter Carroll, a consultant with Oliver, Wyman & Company, observes that in the past banks often purged data that had been temporarily entered into their processing systems. These days they seek to "mine" it for useful nuggets. Instead of rejecting a credit-card applicant because he has no credit history, a bank might now note that he has $250,000 on deposit and issue a card after all. Rather than lose the account of a prominent local entrepreneur, a bank might choose to waive charges on his son's bouncing cheques.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In some ways, this is merely an effort to replace human repositories of knowledge by machines. At another level, however, it is a huge shift in how financial firms go about their business. They are seeking to turn data into information; and then to use that information to make more profitable business decisions. These decisions could be big strategic steps, such as disposing of a business line or agreeing to a merger; or they might be tactical decisions, to re-price a product or close a branch, say.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Yet, as Mr Carroll argues, the really profound impact of the shift from dumb data to usable information comes in the unglamorous area of daily operational decisions. There are three main types of operational decision (see <a href="tf3.gif">table</a>). In the past these were dictated by firm rules--people who lack a credit history make bad credit-card customers, say. But now such decisions can be informed by a richer array of knowledge. A bank can differentiate its decisions: instead of applying one iron rule to all similar customers, it can say "yes" to one customer, "no" to another, and "yes but only if" to a third.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not easy to appreciate the  For each individual decision, the financial effect may be small or even trivial. But extended to an entire customer base, the impact of such techniques could be enormous. Even without gaining a single new customer, a bank could transform its revenues by becoming better at evaluating its existing relationships. And if it could also ensure that new customers would be more likely to be profitable, the bank could cement its advantage.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such techniques are not pipedreams. Several banks and insurers have experienced such improvements in limited areas of their business and are now trying broader applications. Other financial firms are also making the transition from dumb data to useful information. All of this, note, with no mention of the Internet or other high-tech frontiers. The bigger impact often comes from people using existing technology to run their businesses better--so long as their customers are prepared to go along.<br><p><Footnote>&#042;From "Computer: a History of the Information Machine". By Martin Campbell-Kelly and William Aspray. HarperCollins, 1996<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf3.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
