<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>It's consumer banking, Ed</H1><P><I>But not as we know it</I><p ><br>ASHEVILLE, North Carolina: an unlikely spot, you might think, for a grand experiment in banking. But this quiet town was chosen for a trial launched on August 26th by one of the region's leading banks. First Union, America's sixth-largest bank with $140 billion in assets, was once a typical process-driven user of technology, according to Ed Crutchfield, the bank's boss. "But about five years ago," he says, "we switched from an inward-looking perspective to asking how all this technology was affecting our customers, and what we could do to make them like it." Now the bank is trying to change its customers' behaviour. If it succeeds, it will extend the trial to all its 2,000 branches.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Customers entering the branch in Arden, a blue collar suburb of Asheville, are greeted by a new look. The space has been redesigned, walls knocked out to create open areas and desks repositioned to seem less intimidating. Telephones link to First Union's service centre outside Charlotte, the bank's base. The branch's automated teller machines (<font size=-1>ATM</font>s) have been enhanced to offer such services as instant cheque-cashing, mini-statements of recent transactions, split deposits (the ability to send, say, $100 to one account and $50 to another while making a single deposit) and coin facilities. Customers get another dose of novelty when they are approached by a "customer relationship manager" (<font size=-1>CRM</font>), who asks what they want to do. If the transaction can be done electronically or remotely, the <font size=-1>CRM</font> politely shows the customer a faster alternative to standing in a queue for a human teller.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The results are impressive. One man is waiting to deposit a cheque for $200, $50 of which he wants to transfer into his money-market account. Although he has an <font size=-1>ATM</font> card, he queues up to see a teller. Step forward the <font size=-1>CRM</font>, who telephones the First Union service centre and remotely adds the money-market account to the customer's <font size=-1>ATM</font> card. He can then do what he wants with a single visit to an <font size=-1>ATM</font>, avoiding the human teller. At one test branch, <font size=-1>ATM</font> deposits have quickly doubled their previous rates. Queues have dwindled. As Don Harrison, First Union's area manager in Asheville, jokes, he will need more <font size=-1>ATM</font>s if customers are not to be frustrated by a new kind of wait. Old ladies who had never before used an <font size=-1>ATM</font> card are suddenly enthusiastic about their technical prowess.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It may sound trivial; but that is because First Union is seeking merely to improve its use of technology that it already has. Most banks, having built their <font size=-1>ATM</font> networks, made little effort to ensure that customers actually use the machines. First Union is among a few that are trying to undo such negligence. Customers are surprised to find that they can do things faster and more conveniently. The benefit to the banks is obvious. Electronic transactions are much cheaper than people or paper-based ones; allowing for systems and personnel costs, an <font size=-1>ATM</font> transaction costs 25-30 cents, compared with $1.75 for a teller transaction.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  It is not that straightforward, however. Banks have learnt that what ultimately drives their costs is how customers behave. Instead of making a single teller withdrawal of $200, <font size=-1>ATM</font>-happy customers might make five visits to the machine, withdrawing smaller amounts each time and, oh, checking their balance for good measure. Thus, the correct cost comparison may be $1.40 against $1.75; still a saving to the bank, but a far less dramatic one.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Predicting how customers will use enhanced <font size=-1>ATM</font>s is no easy matter, either. The machines are expensive, at around $30,000 each; and their extra functions are seductive. In the Asheville trial, for instance, cheque-cashing has already proved popular, particularly among workers who are paid weekly and who formerly had to wait for their pay cheques to clear into their accounts.<p><b>Root and branch</b><br></b>First Union's Asheville trial is unusual in its scope and potential. Its encouragement to customers is part of an ambitious plan to shift 280m transactions that would have been branch-based to electronic channels by the end of the decade. That represents one-fifth of all transactions forecast by First Union over that period for the southern states of its retail-banking franchise. The bank's aim is simple: if a transaction can be done by <font size=-1>ATM</font> or telephone, that is how it should be done.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, First Union is treading cautiously. Staff in Asheville have been told that their jobs are safe, even as dwindling customer queues reduce the need for them. Yet a big chunk of the bank's assumed long-term cost savings must presumably come from lower personnel costs&#063; Not so, asserts Mr Crutchfield. "This isn't about eliminating jobs through automation; it's about using technology to generate revenue." At worst that means some branch workers being retrained as investment advisers or mortgage specialists, or as telephonists in the bank's fast-growing call service centre. "We need marketing skills far more than we need operations skills," says Mr Crutchfield.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Note that, a few enhancements aside, there is little new technology at work in Asheville. A video kiosk that provides links with specialists for complicated queries is a rare exception. The biggest benefits to the bank will accrue from getting customers to use already existing electronic channels rather than people.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other banks have gone beyond First Union's policy of gentle encouragement, by resorting to the price mechanism. KeyCorp, a Florida bank,  pays 25 cents to customers who make deposits at <font size=-1>ATM</font>s rather than use a teller. Last year First Chicago pioneered an alternative approach when it began to charge for some types of teller transactions. Earlier this year Citibank introduced a bank account that is free provided the customer does not use a teller. There is more to First Union's technology efforts than mere tinkering in branches. Mr Crutchfield has committed the bank to investing in any technology that can be expected to help customers to contact the bank without using a branch. Whether that is a home computer, a smart telephone, an <font size=-1>ATM</font> or a merchant's debit terminal, he wants First Union to have a presence. To that end Mr Crutchfield engineered a huge merger last year with First Fidelity, a New Jersey bank, arguing that First Union needed a bigger capital base if it were to afford the growing bill for technology investment. (See <a href="tf4.gif">chart</a>)<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The business logic is persuasive. If banks that use technology more widely and intelligently than their rivals can both realise more value from existing customers and make them happier, they will worry less about losing them--and they may even attract new ones. To take an example, First Union has used the power of new technology to develop what seems a peculiar line of business for a bank: relocation services. (See <a href="tf5.gif">chart</a>)<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Around 15% of America's households move house each year, routinely closing bank accounts and laboriously opening new ones at a different bank in their new town. First Union used to lose the business of more than 80% of customers who were moving. Then, in 1991, the bank started a small business which had two main goals: to keep the business of more customers who were moving, and to win a large share of the business of people moving into the bank's own region. Using government statistics, First Union creates computer models of patterns of migration. It has also built a network of information suppliers who provide leads on households that might be about to move.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Retention efforts were concentrated on trying to predict which customers are about to move, and offering help with their relocation. Many can be directed towards a First Union branch in their new area or to its own telephone banking service. The bank now loses many fewer customers than it did. Its pitch to newcomers to its area is even more striking. As well as opening a bank account and preprinting cheques for them, the bank liaises with local utility companies to ensure that services are connected before the new customers arrive in their homes. Last year, First Union helped to relocate 40,000 households. This year, by the end of September it had already helped another 70,000 to move. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The financial impact of such techniques is significant. In addition to its relocation business, the bank now has a direct sales force that uses information about customers to predict their likely needs. Letters (1.2m of them last year) are generated from individual sales agents offering customers a product or service. First Union estimates that in 1995 it acquired new business worth $1.2 billion this way.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These efforts are part of a broader trend to tailor products and services to individuals rather than to mass markets. Smart banks (and insurers) no longer roll out a new product and try to sell it to every customer. Rather, they assess each customer and ask what he or she might need. Over time, they create a picture of each customer that allows them to market their services more effectively.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In early September, for instance, Hurricane Edouard veered ominously towards some of First Union's biggest markets in the Carolinas. If the winds hit home, there would be massive disruption, followed by the chaos of insurance claims. First Union knew that many customers might face temporary financial difficulties. Thanks to its data system, the bank was able to send every account holder living in the hurricane's path a letter reassuring them that it would be understanding. "The only limits to this technology are our imaginations," says one enthusiastic First Union manager. It is a message that is also beginning to affect banks' biggest business of all: lending money.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf4.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
