</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>Learning how to lend</H1><P><I>Technology is helping institutions to codify what they know about their business</I><p ><br>THREE years ago Barclays Bank cut its dividend and wrote off almost &163;2.6 billion ($4.1 billion) of bad debts, wiping out its profits for 1992. It was a humiliating experience, brought about by years of ill-disciplined lending. "There were three things wrong with our corporate-loan portfolio," says Martin Taylor, who joined the bank in 1993 as its chief executive. "We grew it too fast, so we lost quality; we priced our lending wrongly; and we allowed huge industry concentrations."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even before its nadir, Barclays was taking steps to improve its lending methods. In 1991 it started to build a computer system to support its lending staff by providing them with information and analytics. The project was motivated less by awareness of the gaping holes in the bank's portfolio (that was to dawn only a year or so later) than by frustration that some lenders were obviously much better at the job than others. Barclays had tried extensive training programmes, but wanted to capture more of the best practice of its loan officers.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; "We wanted a system which would allow us to do a structured financial analysis of our customers," says Brian Fowler, head of credit in Barclays' business-banking operation. The result was Lending Adviser, a software system which the bank had purchased and then extensively customised. It was tested in two branches before being installed throughout Barclays' business banking network during 1994. The system became fully operational in June 1995. Mr Fowler, who was the senior project manager for Lending Adviser, admits that he had initial doubts. "There was a real danger that we did not fully understand the technology we were implementing," he says. "At the very least I felt that it would require cultural changes in the bank if it were to succeed."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the old Barclays lending paradigm, individual lenders acted at local level, triggering referrals up the hierarchy only if they wanted to make loans that would exceed their pre-set limits. So-called "exceptions" were passed first to regional offices and then to head office, where they were dealt with by specialist credit staff. By the time a proposal reached the specialists, it had implicitly been approved further down the hierarchy, encouraging the credit specialists to look for reasons not to make the loan. The bank had no uniform view of a potential loan's riskiness. Indeed, because lenders were trying to "sell" proposals to the institution, that riskiness was greater than anyone realised.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This had several effects. First, individual lenders assumed what Mr Taylor calls a "binary" mindset. Each decision was formulated along the hard lines of whether a given individual would repay or not. "That's fine if you make only one loan in your life," says Mr Taylor. "But if you are a bank and you are making hundreds and thousands of loans, then the right question to ask is 'what is the chance that this loan will be repaid&#063;'--a crucial difference."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nowadays, every potential loan is, with the help of Lending Adviser, marked with a grade that assigns the proposal to one of ten categories separated by perceived riskiness and the likelihood of default. Adding lots of those chances together (that is, making a portfolio) gives the bank a statistical basis for evaluating both individual lending decisions and its overall loan book.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another effect of the old lending system was to make it hugely vulnerable to the attitudes of its central credit specialists. Barclays hit trouble partly because in the late 1980s its lending was growing at an annual compound rate of 25-30%, whereas Britain's <font size=-1>GDP</font> in money terms was not even growing half as fast. This happened largely because the bank's board had signalled an era of growth in an effort to reclaim Barclays' position as Britain's biggest bank. The credit specialists got the message--and switched off their risk antennae. The furious lending that followed, much of it to property companies, led directly to the bank's subsequent write-offs.<br><b><p>Co-operation, not conflict<br></b>Lending Adviser was a conscious break with established procedures. Significantly, it did away with the laborious paper process by which loan proposals reached head office. Moreover, it was incompatible with the bank's old command-and-control management hierarchy. Exceptions are now sent electronically from their point of origin to the bank's credit managers. So-called loan sanctioners at the centre now view the same information as the would-be lender in the field, co-operating with the lender to come to a decision about a proposal.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The system was not an instant hit with all of Barclays' lenders. Despite some fancy software, Lending Adviser remains somewhat clunky. It takes time to load a business's details on to the system so that its financial prospects can be analysed. At the outset, staff complained about the long wait before they could achieve anything useful. But this complaint proved short-lived, says Mr Fowler. Once information has been entered into Lending Adviser, it can be manipulated with remarkable speed. Financial ratios are calculated in an instant; "what if" scenarios model a firm's financial condition under varying assumptions, so as to probe for possible weaknesses. "The system", says Mr Fowler, "highlights the risks of each business, which is helpful to our customers as well as to us."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each time a customer is visited, the new information goes into a central file, so Barclays as an institution has a much clearer idea of the state of its loan portfolio than it did in the past. For instance, the bank can monitor how many of its borrowers might slip to a riskier grade. That knowledge can help it to plan its provisions against bad debts with greater accuracy. It can also price its lending to reflect its view of borrowers' riskiness. And the bank can use the information consciously to direct its lending away from particular risk grades. Because Barclays' loan book represents some 90,000 companies, it is a reasonable proxy for the state of the British economy. If its borrowers' finances are slipping, the chances are that the economy is slowing-- which would certainly shape lending policies.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for the industry concentrations that so bedevilled the bank, these too can be avoided with Lending Adviser. Each borrower is classified by industry type, so it is a simple matter to calculate the bank's exposure in particular sectors. The bank can also be more selective and responsive in its lending. In time it might even be able to identify some of the things that distinguish its best lenders from the rest. It could then tweak its culture yet again to reinforce what it thinks are sound habits.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of this would have been impossible a few years ago. The bank had massive amounts of credit information, but only primitive mechanisms for pooling and collating it. True, Lending Adviser cannot do everything: it does not tell a lender that a particular loan should be sanctioned, nor does it tell managers precisely where the British economy stands in the economic cycle. But it does offer a tool for making better judgments based upon information the bank already has.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Barclays is not the only, or even the first, bank to have tried to codify the best elements of its lending culture by using information technology. But it is a striking example of how the introduction of technology into a previously established system can lead to significant, and often unexpected, cultural and operational changes. Whether the technology has also laid the ground for sounder lending policies will become clearer over the coming years.<p><b>Automatic pilot</B><br></b>One important change can already be noted. Aided by Lending Adviser, Barclays has fundamentally changed its business model for lending. Its central aim is no longer to lend as much as possible on the basis of its capital; but rather to lend only as it should according to its risk-pricing disciplines-- and to let that determine how much capital the bank needs. This new approach explains, for instance, the recent trend of share buy-backs among banks who realise they need less capital to make loans. Its significance, to banking and to the financing of industry, can hardly be overstated.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another example of how technology has penetrated to the heart of banks' lending business can be found in America. In recent years there has been much talk of disintermediation, under which competitive and technological changes do away with the need for established intermediaries. Banks have seen much of their business slip away, whether lending to companies that now tap capital markets direct, or gathering retail deposits that now pour into mutual and money-market funds.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet there was one area of banking that was supposed to be immune from such change: lending to small businesses. The reason was that the information required to make a success of such lending could be gathered only locally. Banks' branch networks apparently gave them an unassailable advantage over distant would-be lenders, while the customers were intrinsically too small to have direct access to the capital markets.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But now a new surge of small-business banking is changing this. With banks such as Wells Fargo and Bank of America in the vanguard, new techniques are breaking down barriers erected by geography. They are based upon lessons learnt from running huge portfolios of consumer loans, whether in credit-card operations or in more straightforward financings. The trick is to focus on volume and canny pricing rather than specific information. A small-business bank has a portfolio of loans, some of which can be expected to default. Instead of gathering detailed local information and hoping to exclude a good proportion of likely defaulters, why not use new technology to price a portfolio of national loans so that the bank can be indifferent to which particular borrowers will default&#063;<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea is powerfully seductive to customers. Rather than go through lengthy and detailed loan applications locally, they can respond to solicitations for pre-approved lines of credit and have the finance in a matter of hours. They may pay a bit more in interest charges. But they gain a precious commodity for any harried small employer: time.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for the lenders, they incur none of the costs of a national presence--direct mail is a fine way to reach potential borrowers--and only a fraction of the costs of processing more detailed loan applications. Last year, for instance, Wells Fargo mailed some 5m loan solicitations in America. The forms asked only a few key questions designed to elicit relevant facts about the borrower: for example, a history of poor personal credit usually signals an undesirable business customer. The simplicity cuts processing costs to a minimum. So long as the bank gets its credit assessment and pricing right, then it should make money. In 1995 Wells Fargo earned a 32% return on equity on its small-business lending.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf5.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
