<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>Looking forward</H1><P><I>The impact of technology on finance is cause for optimism</I><p ><br>IN A plush office in mid-town Manhattan is the Financial Ideas Exchange. As well as a talking shop, it is a laboratory, devised by Andersen Consulting, that offers an evolving display of new financial technologies. Visiting managers can thrill at a futuristic Internet shopping mall, gawp at a smart phone on the back of an airline seat, watch a high tech call-centre being put through its paces. Gathered in one place, the technology is impressive. So is the message it conveys. Where once each new box of financial technology tricks was a stand-alone marvel, the emphasis now is on how things fit together. Customers are a constant presence. How will this instrument be used&#063; By how many&#063; How can this tool improve what our business offers&#063;<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As this survey has shown, the scope of technology in finance is immense. And looking beyond its extensive and fast-growing use by finance, technology is now fundamentally changing the way that business is run. Suddenly and at different rates, geographies are breaking down, business models are eroding, and customers are acquiring new power. Firms that have embraced technology are seeing their businesses shift in unpredicted directions as benefits accrue in unexpected ways. How machines are used is generally far more important than the technical niceties of this model or manufacturer versus that one.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some common themes stand out. The ability to store and manipulate data has become a key competitive weapon, putting dumb data-processing in the shade. Capital, which used to define banks' ability to lend, now limits only their ability to invest in ways to lend more intelligently. Firms such as Citibank fret more about whether their credit-card data systems are up to scratch than about the size of their balance sheets. Physical networks, which used to define insurers' and brokers' reach, have been thrown into turmoil by virtual alternatives that can be delivered down telephone and modem lines. Established financial brands are under threat from unlikely rivals, such as supermarkets and consumer goods firms, as well as from technologically savvier newcomers. Mathematics has moved from being an eccentric companion to being an essential helpmate of modern finance.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, the implications of oMoreover, the implications of one industry's changes go far beyond its boundaries. As financial firms discover and improve new ways of conducting commerce, their efforts will spread across entire economies. Money in all its forms is capitalism's essential lubricant. More efficient uses and transmissions of money are not ends in themselves. Banks that can lend better may alter the behaviour of customers who can borrow better. Clamour from small investors who want venture-capital returns will alter how companies fund themselves, and perhaps alter the nature of ownership. Better risk management will strengthen firms' defences, but might also allow them to use capital more efficiently, producing inflation-free economic benefits. Developing countries that can buy off-the-shelf electronic stock exchanges might unleash social changes far faster than anyone predicts. Cheap electronic channels and the automation of benefit and health-care systems may allow poor people a chance to bank and The convergence of powerful information and communications technologies is the enabling force for all of this. But it is how people behave that will ultimately be the decisive force shaping how the finance industry changes. As finance is digitised, each and every one of its products will be expressed in binary code, including money itself. Customers should benefit from that change. The business battle for the future will then be how to turn all those digits into dollars.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
