<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<H1>The Thatcher revolution </H1>

<P><I>The Tories' greatest achievements were to crush the unions and sell
the nationalised industries</I> <BR>
</P>

<P>BRITAIN'S greatest post-war economic problem, to which many other failures
can be traced, was its system of organised labour. The results of this
system were the symptoms of what by 1979 was known worldwide as the &quot;British
disease&quot;: industrial disruption on an epic scale, a persistent tendency
to wage inflation, chronic backwardness in production and management, low
investment, arthritic rigidity in the face of economic change, demarcation
disputes raised to an art form, stone-clad resistance to new ideas, managers
who did not manage and workers who, it seemed, seldom worked. You might
argue that against this background Britain's productivity record between
1950 and 1979 was actually quite impressive. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As Nicholas Oulton of the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research points out, the defects in Britain's system of labour relations
were both entrenched and unusual--a compound of three distinct elements.
First, union membership was high: in 1979, more than half of all employees
were in a union. Second, Britain's unions had developed a dual system of
bargaining, with negotiations over pay and conditions conducted not only
at plant level by local shop stewards but also nationally by the union's
central officers. Third, unions were organised not by company or industry,
but by &quot;craft&quot; (ie, occupation). Often, any given negotiation
in any given company would therefore involve many different unions. In
1980 nearly 40% of large firms (that is, firms with more than 2,000 workers)
had to deal with six or more manual workers' unions. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To this complicated and strife-prone structure was added a range of
legal immunities that were extremely generous by international standards
(and which, by the way, seriously infringed individual liberties). For
instance, secondary picketing-- when a union disrupts work at firms not
directly connected with its dispute in order to put further pressure, sometimes
through political channels, on employers--is subject to civil and even
criminal penalties in many countries. Britain's law protected it, and the
unions resorted to it routinely. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Until 1979 no British government had dared to face down the unions,
though most (old Labour and Tory alike) had known it needed to be done.
Margaret Thatcher's government took up the challenge, and how. With the
brutal clarity Mrs Thatcher brought to such matters, the unions were no
longer seen as a partner to be coaxed or even arm-twisted into greater
co-operation, but as an enemy to be smashed. And smashed they were, to
an extent that would have seemed incredible in the 1970s. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Successive rounds of industrial-relations laws severely restricted the
unions' immunities. Their right to recognition was curbed, the closed shop
and secondary picketing were outlawed, the freedom of unions to call strikes
was narrowed (for instance, by a requirement that a secret ballot of the
members be called first). In all cases, infringement exposed the unions
to severe civil penalties. In 1984, in an event of enormous symbolic importance,
the government took on the union that had paralysed the country and broken
Edward Heath's administration in 1974--the National Union of Mineworkers--and,
thanks partly to the incompetence of the union's leadership, crushed it. <BR>


&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Union membership fell from more than half of the workforce in 1979 to
less than a third in 1995. The number of firms recognising unions fell
sharply too, from about two-thirds to less than half. More important, the
relationship between employers and those unions that continued to be recognised
changed radically. By and large the unions became more co-operative, and
began to regard strikes as a last rather than first resort..

<P><B>Back to work <BR>
</B>Other factors, of course, aside from the Tories' new laws, also helped
to change the industrial-relations climate. Some were inadvertent and in
themselves extremely undesirable--such as the sharp rise in unemployment
and the unintentionally rapid contraction of the economy during the disinflation
of the early 1980s. Others were the deliberate consequence of policy, and
in themselves a good thing. For instance, the adoption of competitive tendering
(&quot;contracting out&quot;) in much of the public sector greatly weakened
the power of many public-sector unions. Privatisation is another example:
it was probably as important for helping to change the overall character
of industrial relations as for directly improving the performance of the
privatised companies. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;By pushing &quot;lame ducks&quot; such as
British Leyland (now Rover) and overmanned public enterprises such as British
Telecom into private ownership, the Thatcher government lent new credibility
to its promise to let failing companies fail--a vow that many previous
governments had made and then broken. Privatisation sent a clear message:
taxpayers would no longer give refuge to firms that were unable to make
their way in the world. This set an example to the rest of the economy,
encouraging managers, among other things, to adopt a less indulgent attitude
towards dealing with their own unionised workforces. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To say that privatisation helped to change
Britain's culture of labour relations, however, is not to deny that the
direct results of the policy mattered in their own right. They did. When
the Tories came to power, the nationalised industries were making heavy
losses. The cost in state support was equivalent to &pound;300 a year for
every taxpayer. The privatised companies now make profits of roughly &pound;2.5
billion a year--and pay taxes on those profits which amount to a rebate
of &pound;100 a year for every taxpayer. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Most of the nationalised or formerly nationalised
industries raised their productivity a lot faster in the 1980s than in
the 1970s (see <a href="chart4.gif">chart 4</a>). Some, such as British Telecom and British Steel,
became global standard-setters for their respective industries, another
achievement that few would have bet on before 1979. British Steel succeeded
in becoming much more efficient after 1979 while still in the public sector
(it was privatised in 1988); this has led some to question whether privatisation
was really necessary for better management. It may not have been strictly
necessary: better management under public control was evidently possible.
But privatisation was most likely very helpful. Even where efficiency improved
a lot before the firm was sold, as it did at British Steel, the prospect
of private ownership almost certainly acted as a spur. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sceptics also point out, again rightly, that
the government did too little to promote competition in the privatised
industries. Maximising proceeds from the sales mattered to the Treasury,
and monopolies (albeit heavily regulated ones) fetch a better price than
companies that must compete to survive. But this is only to say that the
benefits of privatisation might have been even greater than they were--not,
on the face of it, a good argument against privatisation. Disappointing
or otherwise, the improvement in performance (the result of a too-small
increase in competition and a big increase in profit-seeking) cannot be
denied. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But who has benefited from this better performance?
What of the view, the sceptics' last resort, that the industries' new shareholders
(and overpaid bosses) have gained at the expense of citizens at large? Opponents
of privatisation tend to complain when shareholders have done very well
(grasping investors were sold the companies too cheaply) and when they
have not (poor, unsuspecting shareholders, including many old-age pensioners,
were deliberately misled). <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This is all very silly. Investors in privatisation
shares have done well, but not outrageously so. Taxpayers have gained a
lot, as already noted. And consumers have profited as well. Thanks to better
productivity and a regulatory framework that, for all its faults, divides
the gains of greater efficiency between shareholders and customers, prices
charged by the privatised utilities have mostly risen far less rapidly
than prices in general. For one reason or another, privatisation may have
been unpopular with voters--but in every other way the policy was an unambiguous
success. </P>

<P><B>It ain't broke <BR>
</B>New Labour is at its weakest when it tries to deny that the underlying
performance of the British economy has improved since 1979. Even though
it has no plans to reverse the main policies that have brought this about--the
Tories' anti-union laws and privatisation--it accepts these measures grudgingly.
It says, in effect, that it would not have done these ill-advised things,
but it is too late now to undo them. You can't turn back the clock. New
Labour must make the best of the wreckage the Tories will leave behind.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If this position were entirely a matter of
political spin, one might have few grounds for complaint or anxiety. Judging
Labour by what it firmly promises to do (almost nothing), you would conclude
that the Tories' structural repairs of Britain's economy are secure. Why
not then allow New Labour its ritual denunciations of the government? But
the question is whether, and how, this grudging acceptance of the Tory
revolutions in industrial relations and the state-owned enterprises will
express itself in government. It is false reassurance to suppose that the
reforms cannot now be undone. Some could be explicitly reversed, others
implicitly rendered null. Clocks can, in fact, be turned back. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;New Labour is keen, for instance, on the
idea of a &quot;stakeholder economy&quot;. Again, measured by what Labour
promises to do in office, the idea appears to have virtually no content--which
is fine. But what does it mean to the voters whose support it is intended
to attract?  What might it come to mean? </P>

<P><B>Partners in progress <BR>
</B>At a minimum, it implies a bigger role for workers (organised or otherwise)
in the running of companies. The very term &quot;stakeholder&quot; is intended
to be contrasted with &quot;shareholder&quot;--meaning that companies should
be run with interests other than the &quot;short-termist&quot; demands
of shareholders in mind. The principal stakeholders in any company, after
its owners, are its employees. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Undoubtedly, Britain's unions hope to recapture
ground they have lost under the Tories if Labour wins the election; undoubtedly,
on the key things, Mr Blair is determined to disappoint them. But &quot;stakeholding&quot;
gives them grounds for hope. It is a commodious term, intended to bring
coherence to Labour's various non-pledges on corporate governance, the
minimum wage and the European social chapter (of which more later). That
makes it a big stick with which to beat the new prime minister after the
election. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Advocates of stakeholding and scourges of
City short-termism are in a paradoxical position. Under the Tories, these
critics of the government would agree, shareholder capitalism has made
great strides. Companies are no longer anything like as constrained as
they used to be by powerful unions; enterprises once owned and run by the
government are now owned by shareholders and run by their agents. Yet,
as the productivity figures make plain, these changes have gone hand in
hand with a marked improvement in the performance of British companies.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Admittedly, productivity is only one way
to judge industrial efficiency. Critics of British post Thatcher capitalism
emphasise, as you would expect, other measures. Gordon Brown, the shadow
chancellor, often draws attention to Britain's relatively poor record on
investment, calling this the &quot;root cause&quot; of Britain's relative
economic decline. Put to one side the point that Britain has not, in fact,
been in relative economic decline since 1979. Wouldn't its performance
(good, bad or indifferent) have been be a lot better if investment had
been higher? <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Britain does invest less than similarly prosperous
countries. Since 1960, Britain has spent a smaller share of its national
income on investment than almost any other rich economy: its rate of roughly
18% of <FONT SIZE=-1>GDP</FONT> over the past 35 years was fractionally
less than America's, substantially less than that of France and Germany
(about 22%) and barely three fifths that of Japan (roughly 30%). In this
respect, the record since 1979 shows no improvement. The government, sensitive
to this line of criticism, challenges the numbers and the usual interpretation
of them. It points out that Britain has invested less in housing than similar
countries; its rate of business investment (which excludes housing) has
been second only to Japan's since 1979. Other studies have served mainly
to deepen the confusion: much depends on exactly how business investment
is defined, and the definition varies in large and small ways from country
to country. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Almost by definition, more of the right sort
of investment would improve Britain's economic performance. It would be
fairly easy for the government to arrange a mere increase in capital spending:
that would require only generous subsidies and/or tax allowances of the
kind that Labour often appears to favour (but has not yet spelled out).
The cost would be higher taxes and, at least for a time, lower living standards,
for what is spent on investment cannot also be spent on consumption; but
a mere expansion of investment is certainly achievable. More investment
of the right sort, however, is another thing. No government is competent
to judge which industries, or which firms, or which activities within firms,
deserve to be subsidised. If a greater quantity of investment is achieved
at the expense of quality, nothing has been gained. If New Labour believes
anything, it surely ought to believe that investment decisions should be
made in the marketplace, not in Whitehall. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Some of New Labour's intellectual allies
would deny that. In attacking Britain's short-termist corporate culture,
they call frankly for the government to override the pull of market forces
on investment (and other things), and not merely with a bit of subsidy
here or there. The &quot;stakeholder economy&quot;, that splendidly elastic
term, encompasses demands not only for greater participation by workers
in the running of their firms but also for a tempering of shareholders'
power to demand high short-term profits of their managers. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Here too Mr Blair has adopted the label but
flinches at the substance. Unlike its forebears and very many of its supporters,
when New Labour speaks on the record it proposes no grand new &quot;industrial
strategy&quot;. That is just as well. Britain doesn't need one. More investment,
especially if it resulted from greater confidence among Britain's businessmen
in the prospects for the economy, would be welcome; better macroeconomic
policy, of which more in a moment, would be the best and simplest way to
foster such confidence. In the meantime, however, talk of Britain's continuing
economic crisis does not deserve to be taken seriously. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Even some proponents of &quot;stakeholding&quot;
would go along with that. John Kay, a professor at the London Business
School, is one. In &quot;The Foundations of Corporate Success&quot;, published
in 1993, he explains how best to judge the success of a company. He favours
a measure based on &quot;value added&quot; by the business; mere profit,
beloved of shareholders, can be a misleading gauge. Then he examines a
database of all big European companies to discover which were the most
successful in the 1980s according to this definition. Of Europe's ten most
successful firms, seven were British (see <a href="chart5.gif">chart 5</a>). Not bad for a basket-case.
</P>

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur ">Search</a>
