<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1> The outsiders </h1>

<i>Surging unemployment has been the Tories' greatest failure. What can be done about it?</i><p>

NEW LABOUR'S attack on the Conservatives' record at last hits the target when it comes to unemployment. Mr Blair cannot plausibly deny that British companies are better run than they used to be or that, for the majority, this has put higher living standards within reach. What he can plausibly deny, however, is that the fruits of this achievement have been spread to all parts of society. A substantial minority, Labour argues, have been excluded from the broader trend of growing prosperity. The most conspicuous mark of exclusion is joblessness. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;High unemployment has lots of different consequences, all of them bad. Those directly affected, the unemployed and their families, obviously suffer most, not just because their income disappears but also through loss of self-respect and ever-diminishing employability as time spent without work extends. The costs also extend far beyond the principal victims. High unemployment promotes crime; it increases the burden of the welfare state on taxpayers; the greater threat of joblessness spreads anxiety far and wide. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the economy at large, high unemployment represents an outrageous waste of resources. Although a certain amount of unemployment is unavoidable in any economy, high rates can become self-perpetuating. Unemployment is subject to a kind of inertia that economists call "hysteresis": there is a tendency for the long-term unemployed to increase as a proportion of the total. Not only does this concentrate the misery, it also inhibits the dampening effect on inflation that unemployment would otherwise have. The result is that the unavoidable minimum rate of unemployment--the rate consistent with a low and stable rate of inflation-- drifts higher. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Joblessness also lies behind most of the deterioration in the various socio-economic indicators that Labour cites so effectively against the Tories: growing poverty, rising inequality, the number of households receiving means-tested benefits, and so on. It accounts for much of the rise in public borrowing witnessed in the early 1990s, which New Labour is also at pains to deplore. (The public-sector borrowing requirement reached &pound;45 billion, or 7% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, in 1993-94; it has since fallen to &pound;32 billion.) Ordinarily, the government might find this close connection between unemployment and other economic ills consoling: as unemployment continues to fall (by the end of next year, it should be about 1.75m), those other measures of economic failure are bound to improve as well. Given the electoral timing, however, such progress is likely to be too little and too late. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Causing a needlessly high rate of unemployment is one of the worst mistakes a government can make. Why did unemployment rise so quickly in the early 1980s and early 1990s? What if anything can be done now to reduce it faster?<p>
<b>If it's Tuesday, it must be £M3</b >
<br>Often during the 1980s, the government's critics accused it of using high unemployment as an instrument of economic policy. Millions were shunted on to the dole, it was said, in a cynical effort to curb inflation and quell the unions. Actually, the government was dismayed at the rise in unemployment of the early 1980s. The prevailing orthodoxy had been that a programme to cut inflation, announced in advance and described in detail, could succeed without much, if any, rise in unemployment. The trick was to make sure that everybody believed the government's promise that inflation would fall. If they did, wage demands would moderate and fewer workers would find themselves priced out of work. Accordingly, the government devoted much effort to developing and defending its "medium term financial strategy", a multi-year framework that set the context for each year's budget.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a variety of reasons, the policy went wrong. The Tories succeeded in lowering inflation only at an enormous cost in unemployment. Evidently, however, little was learned from the experience. Unemployment soared again in the recession of the early 1990s. And the cause of that recession was essentially the same as before: inflation had risen sharply, so the government was obliged to contract the economy. This time, though, fewer people argued that so patent and embarrassing a failure had been a deliberate act of policy. (Sterling's ejection from the European exchange-rate mechanism made it far harder than before to put a brave face on defeat.) Henceforth, in macroeconomic policy, it was more plausible to mock the Tories for their incompetence than to deplore them for their wickedness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The lesson of the past two recessions is that--in a limited sense, and unpalatable as it seems--unemployment is after all an instrument of economic policy. But the lesson would apply as much to a socialist or New Labour government as to a Tory one. Once inflation is rising, curbing it requires higher unemployment, at least for a time. The choices surrounding this short-term trade-off are essentially second-order decisions: should the government curb inflation quickly (implying a more rapid, but perhaps more short-lived, rise in unemployment) or more slowly (implying a gentler, but perhaps longer-lived, recession)? When Margaret Thatcher justified the first Tory recession by saying "There is no alternative", she was almost right: once inflation is up, there are no likeable alternatives.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It follows that the best anti-unemployment policy is a successful anti-inflation policy. This is well worth remembering at times like now. Inflation is low; wages are increasing at a relatively modest pace; unemployment is falling; the economy is growing at a steady if unspectacular pace. For some commentators, this is not enough: the government should cut interest rates further and "allow" the economy to grow faster. These are the commentators (from both left and right) who have applauded Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, for cutting interest rates against the advice of the Bank of England in recent months, and who regret only that he has not gone further to stimulate the economy. It is safe to predict that they will be the very commentators who will criticise Mr Clarke most bitterly when inflation rises in due course, making higher interest rates (and rising unemployment) necessary once more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments everywhere find it difficult to keep inflation securely in check. No particular technique of monetary policy holds the secret--if it did, Britain, which has tried almost every regime you can think of, would have found it by now. What seems to matter most is not the nuts and bolts of monetary management but a popular demand for, or at least acceptance of, stable prices. This is why a successful anti-inflation policy is especially difficult in Britain, and helps to explain why the record of every British government since the 1960s in this respect has been so dismal. To put it mildly, Britain has a high tolerance of inflation. Recent signs of brisker business in the housing market--often a precursor of a more general rise in prices--were widely regarded as good news.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In several ways, in fact, Britain's inflation problem is linked to housing. Most people in Britain finance their homes with (subsidised) floating-rate debt. This makes them unusually sensitive to changes in interest rates. Fraction-of-a-point rises that would pass almost unnoticed elsewhere are front-page news in Britain, and hailed as a great political setback. Even more than in other countries, therefore, British governments love to cut interest rates and hate to put them up. Tolerance of inflation (to put it at its mildest) together with this great resistance to "safety-first" adjustments in interest rates have given Britain a persistent tendency to high inflation--a persistent tendency, in other words, to spells of high unemployment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Changing this settled pro-inflation culture would be a job of many years. The best hope is to keep inflation down for so long that the economy's institutions begin to adapt to, and then demand, stable prices. The catch of course is that, until then, keeping inflation down is going to be difficult. A step in the right direction would be to make the Bank of England responsible for monetary policy, and to let it discharge its duties independently of the Treasury. This is no cure-all, as some appear to think. Monetary policy would not become apolitical merely because the government said so--as the Bank would quickly discover. The most that can be said is that, with luck, the distance between politics and anti-inflation policy would be somewhat increased. It would be a start.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government had appeared to be adopting this approach. Over the past few years the Bank has been given a bigger say in the operational aspects of monetary policy (eg, in deciding precisely when to change interest rates in the amount and direction chosen by the chancellor), and it has been allowed to say more in public about what it thinks (notably through its own independently produced <i>Inflation Report</i>, and through publication of the minutes of its monthly monetary-policy meeting with the chancellor). As these changes were announced, it was speculated that they might constitute de facto independence for the Bank. Hardly. Mr Clarke has shown his followers how to operate the system: hear the Bank's views, ignore them, and collect extra credit on that account when interest rates are cut.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a time it also seemed that New Labour might embrace the idea of an independent Bank of England. But its proto-manifesto is careful to stop short of that. It says only that "We will reform the Bank of England to ensure that decision-making on monetary policy is more effective, open, accountable and free from short-term political manipulation." In other words, "We will make things better but we aren't saying how." Perhaps it was naive to suppose that if Labour gained office, having been denied power for nearly 20 years, it would promptly surrender the most powerful tool of economic policy into another's hands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In most other respects, New Labour spares no effort to reassure voters and the City that its macroeconomic policy will be non-inflationary. Indeed, to most of its supporters, the party's position is cautious to a fault. No talk of the traditional "dash for growth" (the idea is explicitly repudiated). And, as already noted, virtually no firm promises on new public spending. Judged by what Labour's leaders have said, rather than by what their supporters wish they would say, there is little to choose between the two main parties on macroeconomic policy. Both promise to do the right thing: curb the budget deficit, keep inflation low. Neither offers any new reasons for supposing its promise will be kept. 
<p><b>Skills and standards</b >
<br>Though it is true that the best way to keep unemployment low is to keep inflation low, thereby avoiding the need to throttle the economy every few years, curbing unemployment is not just a matter of macroeconomic policy. Much of Britain's unemployment is "structural", meaning that it will take more than a business-cycle recovery to eliminate it. In principle, any of a number of factors may cause this kind of unemployment. For instance, the unemployed may lack the skills that an expanding economy will need; the welfare system may be designed in such a way that some people are better off collecting the dole than they would be going out to work; there may be regulatory barriers of one sort or another preventing would-be workers from finding jobs; and so on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since 1979 the government's assorted interventions in the labour market have avowedly been designed to promote "flexibility"--that is, to improve skills and incentives, and to clear away the barriers that keep the unemployed out of work. It is difficult to judge the success of these measures, overshadowed as they have been by two severe recessions. But the government's various initiatives have undeniably increased the proportion of 16-18-year-olds in formal training. They have substantially reduced the number of people caught in the worst forms of the unemployment-benefit trap. (This was achieved partly by reducing benefits for some recipients and partly by tightening the rules on eligibility; the result is that fewer people are now better off on the dole than in work.) They have weakened the power of trade unions, and ended the power of Wages Councils, to set pay at levels that reduce the demand for labour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this, it seems, has improved the ability of the labour market to match willing employers with would-be workers. The evidence for this is that in the recovery from the second recession, unemployment started falling sooner than in the recovery from the first (see <a href="chart7.gif">chart 7</a>). In other words, employment now seems to respond more sensitively to the state of the economy than before. Many other things changed between the 1980s and the 1990s, of course, but it seems likely that a more flexible market for labour is one of the reasons for that faster growth of jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New Labour's proposals on employment are a peculiar mixture. As in other areas, they reflect the party's ambivalence over the respective roles of state and market. The goal of "flexibility" is embraced, as you would expect. Old Labour would have denounced the term, with some justice, as a euphemism for screwing the workers; to New Labour, flexibility in all things is both modern and necessary. Needless to say, however, flexibility must be combined with certain "minimum standards".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour therefore intends to introduce a national minimum wage (its level to be determined by a new Low Pay Commission). It also says it will adopt the European social chapter, which would extend workers' entitlements in matters such as consultation by managers and unpaid parental leave. Less contentiously, the party proposes to expand the existing provision of vocational training, both to increase the proportion of 16-18-year-olds receiving a good standard of formal training and to ensure that the long-term unemployed are given a variety of training choices as a route back to work.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On benefits, Labour's policy appears to be more niggardly than the government's. That is, any young unemployed people turning down these improved options for work or training (which include, presumably as a last resort, a job on Labour's "environment taskforce") will have their benefit cut: "There will be no option of remaining permanently on full benefit." Though it bemoans the rise in poverty of the past two decades, New Labour does not propose to restore the real value of benefits. To judge by its proto manifesto, it is more concerned to curb fraudulent claims.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour, haunted by the memory of its election campaign of 1992, is nearly as vague on taxes. The interaction of benefits and taxes for those on low incomes continues, despite the Tories' changes, to be an important obstacle to higher employment. Radical solutions to the tax-and-benefits trap--especially an integrated system in the form of a negative income tax--have a lot to be said for them and should commend themselves to a left-of-centre party. But schemes of this sort would be very expensive. Rather than proposing any such reform, Labour talks blithely about reducing the starting-rate of income tax from 20% to 10% when conditions allow.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the meantime, its purported remedies for Britain's most pressing economic and social problem are a mixture of good and bad. Labour's ideas on training are promising. It is a pity they do not go further. One of the most outrageous anomalies in British public policy is that university education for bright 18-21-year-olds is hugely subsidised by the taxpayer, whereas vocational training for academically unsuccessful 16-19-year-olds is often undertaken at private expense. There is a very strong case on the grounds of equity and efficiency for correcting, and indeed reversing, this bias.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;University students, who will be the most prosperous members of society, and who will themselves capture almost all of the benefit of their higher education, should receive much less subsidy. In contrast, society has a large interest in helping its least gifted people into gainful employment, as opposed to idleness or crime. Many of these rejects are failing to receive training under the government's expanded schemes; Labour's plans would be an improvement, but are still not intended to reach everyone. Here is an opportunity for a left-of-centre party to be both radical and intelligent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No such luck. Labour's proposals on welfare-to work are limited in scope. This is partly, one imagines, so that financing them can be said to require not a fundamental change of priorities, still less an ongoing rise in general taxation, but merely a "windfall levy" on the privatised utilities. This daft way of presenting the policy mars an otherwise worthwhile idea. A "windfall" tax cannot finance a recurring expense; it will probably fail to raise enough money to pay for even one year of Labour's new regime; and it pretends that a tax on the privatised utilities is not somehow a tax on the public at large (which, ultimately, it is). What this stratagem shows is that Labour is unwilling to present even its best ideas as plans that voters might actually be willing to pay for.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's other main ideas on employment are not flawed so much as plain awful. The minimum wage, unless set cynically at so low a rate that it would not raise anybody's wages, is a job destroyer. The <font size=-1>EU</font>'s social chapter is constitutionally objectionable (subsidiarity should apply here if anywhere) and threatens to become another heavy tax on jobs. Anything that raises the cost of hiring an extra worker makes it less likely that a worker will be taken on. If reducing unemployment were Labour's top priority, as it should be, it would have no truck with nonsense of this sort. Labour's feeble reply is: "Everybody else in Europe does it." It only remains to add that Britain's unemployment rate, however dire, is one of the lowest in the Union.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur ">Search</a>
