<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1>Cradle to grave </h1>

<i>What should become of the welfare state?</i><P>

REPORTS of the death of Britain's welfare state have been exaggerated. Since 1979, welfare spending--broadly defined to include pensions, social security, education, the National Health Service and public housing--has increased by half in real terms. Even as a proportion of <font size=-1>GDP</font> it has increased, from 23% to 26% (see <a href="chart9.gif">chart 9</a>). 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On unchanged policies, it is true, the recessions of the 1980s and 1990s would have driven welfare spending a good deal higher under the Tories. And until 1979 the share of welfare spending in national income had been on a steadily rising trend. In merely halting that growth, at a time when demands on the system were rising for both business cycle and demographic reasons, the Tories had to squeeze hard in some areas. They did it by cutting capital spending and extending means-testing where they could. Housing and education came to receive smaller shares of the total, health care and social-security benefits bigger ones. But the broad goals of the system, and the resulting cost to taxpayers, have changed much less than most of the governments' critics allow--and less than some of its critics would have wished. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among the various exceptions to that, one is important. It caused surprisingly little fuss, perhaps because its effects will take years to become conspicuous. This was the decision to link future increases in pensions and some other benefits to inflation rather than to average earnings (which rise faster than prices). The implication is that the basic state pension will provide an ever-diminishing standard of living, measured relative to the incomes of those in work. To avoid poverty in old age, people will increasingly need to provide for themselves, by saving more during their working years. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This decision, in other words, announced the beginning of what could become a long, slow retreat in a central component of the welfare state as it was once envisaged. Whether tomorrow's pensioners fully understand the difference this will make to them is doubtful. Labour opposed the change, as you would expect; as you would expect, it has no plans to reverse it. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That aside, Tory efforts to reform the welfare state have mainly concentrated not on the scale of provision, but on the method of delivery. Here, their thinking has been radical by any standards. A turning-point came in 1988. Up to then, most of the Tories' changes to the welfare state had been mere tinkering, forced upon them by the need to contain costs. But then came the Education Reform Act, which introduced the national curriculum, open school enrolment and provision for schools to opt out of local-authority control. State schools would still be free to their users, but the reforms would begin to change the system from one that allocated resources according to the plans of central and (especially) local authorities into one that worked more like a market--a "quasi-market"--for educational services. The idea was simple enough: schools would compete with each other, and standards would rise. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1988 the government also set up a review into the future of the National Health Service. This yielded a shake-up that was even more radical than the one that had just begun in education. Again, the principle of free provision was not questioned. Instead, another "internal market" was to be established. Hospitals could opt out of health-authority control, and many general-practitioner practices would be given their own budgets to buy services from hospitals or health authorities as they chose. Again, competition was intended to raise standards, by exposing inefficiency, weighing the costs of treatment more explicitly and causing resources to be better employed. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The quasi-market idea was also extended to other areas. In public housing, for instance, landlords were allowed to bid for control of local-authority housing, with rents shifted closer to market levels (and housing benefits raised to reflect that). The government's policy on "community care" also intended that public providers would play a smaller role and private providers a bigger one, all at taxpayers' expense. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taken together, these different initiatives suggested the beginning of a deep transformation of the welfare state. Henceforth, even though public services could continue to be paid for out of general taxation, they might be almost entirely provided by a variety of competing private suppliers. According to the purest form of the quasi-market model, most (if not all) schools, hospitals, residential homes, providers of "social housing", and so on would one day be private, as opposed to state-owned and state-run, institutions. The role of government would be confined to injecting money, regulating, promoting competition and monitoring the results. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The model could be extended even further, into the saving-for-retirement and insurance functions of the benefits system. For instance, the government might develop a funded replacement for the state pension system, paying a minimum contribution for each taxpayer into an individual pension account held at any of a multitude of competing providers. The delinking of pensions from earnings might then be seen as a first step in this direction. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In principle, then, there are two questions to ask about the future of the welfare state. The first, and more familiar, is: how big should it be? The other is: should it be organised along traditional public-service lines, or as a series of quasi-markets? It is a politically important fact, however, that these questions are by no means independent. The Tories' reforms of the welfare state are easy to portray as a strategy of dismantling by stealth. This has been Labour's charge throughout.
<p><b>Outsourcing the welfare state</b>
<br>The charge has substance. Once quasi-markets are in place, and the government no longer acts as a monopoly supplier of the service in question, it is natural to ask how far its role as provider of cash should be supplemented, or replaced, by the private sector. Suppose the government pursued the logic of its reforms in education, for instance, and issued parents with vouchers enabling them to buy a place at the school of their choice. It would be in the spirit of such a scheme, some would argue, to let "state schools" (as they once were) invite parents to top up their vouchers with cash. With time, the state's contribution could be allowed to fall, leading by degrees to the privatisation of education.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Higher spending notwithstanding, the Tories' reforms of the supply-side of the welfare state have always been bedevilled by the popular suspicion that this is where they are really heading. New Labour, if it chose, could explore the quasi-market method of delivery with less political difficulty: its assurances that the aim was merely to improve the quality of services would be more readily believed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But does the quasi-market approach, judged solely as a method of delivery, actually give better value for money? It is too early to expect clear answers. Such dramatic changes involve heavy starting costs and great initial disruption; the gains, if any, will take time to come through. Accordingly, the evidence so far is mixed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Audit Commission recently published a report on the economics of <font size=-1>GP</font><b> </b>fundholding. It estimated that up to the end of 1994, practices had received &pound;232m to cover the costs of the extra staff, equipment and computers they needed to make the new regime work. Against that, they had achieved only &pound;206m in efficiency savings within their budgets. The question is whether improvements in the service provided to patients were sufficient to offset that financial deficit of &pound;26m. The commission found many improvements (such as better communication with hospitals, shorter waiting times, greater use of day surgery); but it found also that only the best-managed practices had succeeded in making a big difference in these respects. The best practices showed that the new system offered great potential for improvement, but few as yet were realising that potential.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In principle, competition ought to make sense: in most fields of endeavour, it works miracles. But in its application to the welfare state, there are difficulties. For a start, no doubt recognising the political obstacles, the government has stopped well short of the maximum dose of market forces. The Tories' quasi-markets are even further removed from proper markets than they might be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In primary and secondary education, for instance, the government has not adopted the voucher model. One result is that parents do not act as purchasers within the system, exerting all the pressure they might on schools to raise standards. Similarly, in health care, the power to shop around rests not with patients but with fundholding <font size=-1>GP</font>s. Any health system offering free services needs a "gatekeeper" of some kind if it is not to be overwhelmed. Even so, in a system which continues to discourage patients from switching among <font size=-1>GP</font>s, the question arises whether the reforms have really improved matters for the people the <font size=-1>NHS</font> is intended to serve.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A problem that seems pervasive in quasi-market systems is "cream-skimming". Any scheme that pays a standard fee for each user or group of users gives providers an incentive to search for customers who will be cheap to service. <font size=-1>GP</font>s would prefer to have the young and fit on their rolls; the old and infirm are financially less appealing. Schools would prefer to recruit the brightest pupils, because that improves their record in examination results; if possible, they will avoid accepting backward pupils, or those with particular learning difficulties, because such children do badly in exams and require a bigger investment of teaching effort.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Formulas can be devised to reward doctors and schools for taking on more needy or troublesome users, but unless this is seen to, the quasi-market approach is dangerously flawed. Competition among providers may be counted on, in the end, to raise average performance; but the quality of service provided to those at the bottom (which will often mean those in greatest need) may well decline.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if "weighted vouchers" were introduced to correct the bias in quasi-market systems against demanding users, there is a broader point here of some political moment. Even in its present half hearted applications, it is clear that the quasi-market method both decentralises and depoliticises. More decisions are taken by <font size=-1>GP</font>s, fewer by health authority planners; more by parents and school governors, fewer by local-authority bureaucrats.<b>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</b> Put that way, perhaps, it all seems fine. But decentralisation also means diversity. That is something that the welfare state's beneficiaries are unused to. People are accustomed to thinking of their rights within the system as uniform entitlements, measured not by the cost of providing the service (which has been no concern of theirs) but by the outcome. Suppose a patient with a good <font size=-1>GP</font> gets a hip replacement within weeks whereas a patient with a bad one must wait months. In the traditional regime, that is an anomaly: you either hush it up or call for action from the centre. The quasi-market system works in the first place by making such differences more obvious, which is awkward enough. Then it proposes no external remedy: within limits, the market is intended to heal itself. From a politician's point of view, this is to go from bad to worse. His role has shrunk. There is little or no place, if the model is fully developed, for a grand, politically accountable, harmoniser of services.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A welfare state that relied more on markets would probably deliver better standards and better value for money. But one wonders whether that would be a welfare state that Britain will ever want.
<p><bold>Alternative futures</bold>
<br>For now, it appears that nobody is about to offer Britain the choice; not in those terms, at any rate. The first big question about the future of the welfare state was, how much should it cost? New Labour's answer seems to be: about the same, measured as a share of national income, as now. That is the only answer consistent with the party's professed reluctance to raise taxes in the aggregate. Labour's provisional manifesto rightly says that as unemployment falls (which it is likely to, initially, under either sort of government), there will be room within the total for more spending on health and education. One supposes that the Tories, in contrast, would prefer to translate any such fiscal benefits into lower taxes. In the short-term, at least, the difference between these competing visions of the welfare state is puny.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More important, arguably, are the views the parties take on the second question about welfare: how are the services to be delivered? Again, however, the differences are slender. The Tories seem stuck half way between the traditional welfare state and a properly market-driven system. They lack the conviction to proceed, as though the radicalism that seized them in the late 1980s took them by surprise. New Labour seems equally confused. It denounces the <font size=-1>NHS</font> internal market in sternly moralising tones: "the corrosive ethics of the marketplace", and all that. It explicitly opposes vouchers in education, again as though competition taints what it touches. "We favour greater devolution for schools--but within a local, accountable service that ensures fairness and partnership between all schools 
<br>c." Make of that what you will.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What a pity that New Labour cannot seize its opportunity to marry a willingness to maintain spending on welfare with a vigorous commitment to use market systems of delivery. That would be a genuinely intriguing prospect. Labour would find it far easier to present the policy in the proper light--not an attempt to shave pennies, but an effort to improve services. Labour, one supposes, would also take greater care to weight the system in such as way as to limit cream-skimming, and preferably to go further, providing additional incentives to improve services to those most in need. There would be a real possibility of better services not merely for most people, but from top to bottom. Unfortunately, all the signs are that Labour's instinctive revulsion at market forces, though pretty well controlled when discussing the economy, is unquellable when it comes to the welfare state.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur ">Search</a>
