</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1> The reluctant European </h1>

<i>No less than its partners, Britain needs a clearer view of what the European Union is for </i>

<p>IN ONE way, the charge that the Tories bring nothing but a dull complacency to the debate on constitutional reform is unfair (quite apart from the fact that their record as constitutional revolutionaries belies their soothing words). Europe, after all, is a constitutional matter. You might argue, in fact, that the constitutional issues it raises are more important and more difficult than any others currently facing Britain. It would be too kind to say that the Tories are thinking hard about this subject; they are too busy shouting at each other to be giving the matter much thought. But you can hardly accuse them of ignoring it. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain's next government will have to confront two big questions about the country's future within the European Union. The first and more immediate is what part, if any, Britain should play in the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s plans to create a single European currency. The other, less urgent but in the end more important, concerns integration in the broader political sense: how far, if at all, should Britain join others in pursuing the idea, enshrined in the Treaty of Rome, of an "ever closer union"?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The questions are obviously connected--but not so inextricably as is generally supposed. With no significant exceptions, people who want closer political integration in the <font size=-1>EU</font> also favour the euro (which is what the single currency will be called). Indeed, they want the euro less for its economic benefits, such as they may be, than because it would be in their view a big step towards that grander political goal. In the same way, again with no large exceptions, those who oppose the euro do so less for its supposed economic costs than because it would, they say, advance the cause of political integration. Nearly everyone with a strong view about the euro, for or against, agrees that the issue is inseparable from the question of political union. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a pity. There is a respectable economic case for creating a single currency in Europe. Respectable, and unexciting. Judged in economic terms, no plausible estimate of the balance of costs and benefits could be big enough, one way or the other, to arouse passions like those excited by political union. This may explain why the question is rarely examined except in that larger context. The fact remains, it would be entirely possible to have the euro without further political integration. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The classical (ie, pre-1914) gold standard was just such a system. It worked well for decades, without it even occurring to anyone that irretrievably fixed exchange rates might require the pooling of political sovereignty, harmonised fiscal policy or harmonised anything else. All that was required was the shared conviction that the value of money was not something which governments were free to manipulate. Plainly, that conviction has vanished, a fact that certainly alters the prospects for any new monetary union. For this and other reasons, the classical gold standard does not make a compelling case for the single currency--but it should at least disturb the certainty of those who say that political and monetary union are inseparable.
<p><b>A close-run thing</b>
<br>The single currency has two main economic advantages. The first is the range of gains that may be grouped under the heading of "transactions costs". This is not just a matter of avoiding the traveller's commission costs of switching from one money to another at the border: in the bigger scheme of things, these are trivial. Far more important are the risks that fluctuations in exchange rates add to the cost of doing business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is true that some kinds of currency-risk can be hedged in the financial markets, at a cost. But a long-term investment in Germany, say, remains riskier for a British or Italian company than it is for a German one. The single currency would remove this impediment to the operation of the single market. Those who say that costs of this kind are small enough to ignore are saying, in effect, that the American economy would lose little if each of its states had its own currency--an improbable claim.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The euro's other main benefit would be conditional: as long as the new monetary institutions were well designed and did their job properly, the benefits of low inflation would be spread more widely in Europe than before. The blueprint for the institutions is still vague on some important matters; in any case, it will be impossible to judge the competence of the central bank until it has been tested in practice. Nonetheless, the potential to improve on the record of domestic, politically driven monetary policy is there, and should commend the euro particularly to countries with a proven record of incompetence in the field. If that category has any members, Britain (the leading euro-sceptic) is certainly one. By the same token, Germany (a leading euro-enthusiast) has less to gain than most of its partners. That goes to show how much political factors have driven what could and should have been a mainly economic debate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Against these substantial advantages must be weighed one big cost: the single currency would deny its members the independent use of monetary policy. Clearly, even a country that has been bad at monetary policy loses something valuable when it gives up the right to set its own interest rates. If a recession struck that country but not the rest of the <font size=-1>EU</font>, its interest rates (set by the single central bank) would be too high, and its slowdown would be worse than it needed to be. This is an important point, but against it note that most recessions (the Tories' two are examples) are caused by earlier mistakes in domestic monetary policy. You need to ask whether national monetary policy would be better for Britain than the euro over the whole course of the economic cycle, rather than saying "Assume a recession: what happens then?" It is a poor case for national monetary policy that you need it to mitigate the recession it created in the first place.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many other arguments often made against the euro are simply wrong. The most common fallacy is that a single currency would "lock in" differences in living standards across the community. By condemning the poorer countries to stay poor, it is further argued, the euro would add to demands for centralised fiscal policy aimed at narrowing the differences. Here lies the main supposed link between monetary union and political union. But the economic premise of this argument--that devaluing your currency shifts real resources into your country, thereby helping you to grow faster--is patently false. Devaluation does no such thing. At its theoretical best, it is a way to ease adjustment pains through the course of the economic cycle, not a way to raise long-term living standards. In practice, it would be harder to think of an idea that has been more conclusively refuted by the facts than the claim that devaluation makes you richer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, one other argument, which for some reason euro-sceptics mention much less often than the devaluationist fallacy, does call for greater caution in Britain's case than in most other countries. As noted earlier, Britain's economy responds far more sensitively to changes in interest rates than most others do. More than elsewhere, people in Britain own the houses they live in and finance the purchase by borrowing at floating rates. This is the legacy of chronic inflation. In the past, buying a house was the best hedge against inflation that most people could find (after tax, no other form of saving preserved its value so well); lenders, for their part, demanded floating rates because the monetary future was so uncertain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever the causes, the result is that even a modest change in interest rates in Britain is a big political event with a perceptible financial effect (for good or ill) on very many households. As a result, the political context for monetary policy is different from that in Germany or France. The Maastricht treaty's criteria for membership of the euro system require "convergence" in various ways: some of these criteria are beside the point, others harmful. The one thing above all on which convergence is advisable is sensitivity to changes in interest rates. The treaty doesn't mention it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Britain, then, the economic pros and cons of the single currency are finely balanced. But the decisive point, for now, is that the idea is widely unpopular: no such undertaking should go ahead (anywhere in Europe, not just in Britain) without strong popular support based on an understanding of the risks and why they may be worth taking. But since that test could one day be met, and since the euro has the potential to be a good thing, Britain should not oppose it on principle, still less rule out membership for all time and under any circumstances-- the hysterical demand of the Tory sceptics. Britain has its opt-out; it can wait and see what happens. That is John Major's policy and Tony Blair's as well. There can be no sensible objection to it.
<p><b>Wider still and deeper</b>
<br>The trouble is, a policy of "watchful waiting" can be difficult to distinguish from one of "we don't know what we think, and never will." However sensible it may be for Britain to bide its time on the euro, the country and its politicians ought surely by now to have worked out what Britain's broader place in Europe should be. The bitterness of the Tory party's split over Europe, and the signs that similar (if less intense) divisions are latent in the Labour Party, show how far that is from being true.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Collectively, Britain remains emotionally at arm's length from Europe: the very word still means "them" more often than it means "us". The comic aspects of this posture--as when the Tory government sought to blame "Europe" for Britain's mad cow scare--should not disguise the harm it may do. A discussion about Europe's future is going on. Britain should be fully engaged in that discussion, not jeering uselessly from the sidelines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Scepticism about the course set for Europe by the Maastricht treaty is fully warranted. History may judge that the European Community (as it then was) took a wrong turn when, in response to the collapse of communism in Eastern Europe, it sought to integrate more deeply rather than, as a higher priority, prepare itself to accept new members. Moreover, this decision came not in response to the demands of citizens, but was the expression of a grand political strategy. Public opinion was expected to catch up in due course.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difficulties that many governments encountered in ratifying the Maastricht treaty--not least, the wafer-thin support for it in the French referendum--showed how ill-advised this top-down approach had been. The lesson from that period for leaders intent on deeper integration ought to have been: go slower, build support first. Judging by the renewed promises in France and Germany to secure monetary union within the Maastricht timetable, despite lukewarm backing at best from their electorates, the lesson has not yet been learned.
<p><b>A place for Britain</b>
<br>So in the debate about the future of the <font size=-1>EU</font>, it is well that Britain's voice should be heard. Its traditional pragmatism, its scepticism about grand designs, and (post-Thatcher) its more liberal instincts on economic policy have much to commend them. Britain should be arguing vigorously, in others' interests as well as its own, for several things.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most urgently, the <font size=-1>EU</font> needs to produce a working definition of "subsidiarity". Following the Maastricht-ratification trauma, various attempts were made to lend substance to the idea, to appease those who feared that the treaty moved too much power to Europe's centre. But the thinking remains vague, albeit much wordier than before, and it continues to emphasise the "effectiveness" of policy as a criterion for deciding where power should reside. A better formula would define subsidiarity in terms that would take powers to the centre only when that was absolutely necessary, not merely when it was "more effective".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A definition along these lines, once developed, should be written into a simple new constitution for the <font size=-1>EU</font>. That would have other merits. The doctrine of "ever closer union" for all the members served its purpose during the years when the European Community was under construction. But a point must come, and probably now has, when such an idea costs more in destabilising existing arrangements than it gains in improving them. In other words, a point must come when Europe's union is close enough. A constitution would be obliged to define that point, and would require governments to build a consensus around it. As part of that exercise, defects of the present regime could be addressed--in particular, the widening of the "democratic deficit", as powers have moved to the centre without adequate accountability to citizens. Beyond that, the implications of "variable geometry"--the idea that in future some countries will integrate more closely than others--also need to be thought through.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On constitutional matters like these, Britain should be arguing its corner. Similarly on matters of policy--the future of the common agricultural policy (<font size=-1>CAP</font>), the Union's external trade relations, co-operation on defence, enlargement, you name it--Britain's voice should be heard. But Britain cannot expect its sceptical-liberal instincts or the merits of its particular arguments to be warmly recognised by its partners unless the country regards itself as a settled member of the club. After all these years, it still isn't. Britain's prevailing attitude often seems one of sneering contempt for all things continental. Lately, national politics has stirred such ideas even more to the surface. Much of the commentary on Europe offered by Tory Euro-sceptics and their supporters in the media is outright xenophobia. In the country's discussion of Europe since the government's humiliation in the <font size=-1>EMS</font> crisis of 1992, a puerile and insufferable smugness about Britain has once again become not merely respectable but fashionable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such sentiments are damaging as well as ugly. Warranted scepticism about further ambitions for European integration needs to be balanced by an understanding of the gains Britain has had from the European project. The greatest of these--long neglected only because the European Community allowed one to take it for granted--is security. A region riven this century by two appalling wars is now one of the safest parts of the world. Beside that immense prize the economic achievements of European integration are bound to seem small, but by any other yardstick they too are impressive. Trade in Europe has grown enormously since the 1970s, expanding opportunities for businesses and consumers alike. Britain has fared especially well lately, because its position within the <font size=-1>EU</font>, together with its friendly business climate, has attracted a lot of inward investment (see <a href="chart10.gif">chart 10</a>).
<p><b>By jingo</b>
<br>That many in Britain welcome these achievements so grudgingly, if at all, doubtless says more about post-imperial chagrin than it does about the defects of the <font size=-1>EU</font>. As a medium-sized economic and military power, Britain still has some growing up to do. But what a dilemma this poses at the next election. A substantial minority of Tories is intellectually paralysed by its hatred of "Europe". It is hard to imagine a Tory government advancing with any success a sensible agenda for reform of Europe's policies and institutions--simply because the good faith of any Tory government is bound to be questioned, and rightly, by other Europeans.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, New Labour seems a much better bet. Its proto-manifesto says: "If we can build alliances with those in Europe who share our views we can achieve a Europe that is open, outward-looking and anti-protectionist." Gosh, marvellous. Labour also wants reform of the <font size=-1>CAP</font>, greater openness in Europe's institutions and "a far more vigorous approach to the single market". Better and better. But then it goes and spoils everything. At the top of Europe's agenda for reform, says New Labour, should be "action on unemployment".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What? This is not a reference to the need for a Europe-wide monetary policy (reasonably enough, Labour reserves its position on the single currency). So it can only mean that Labour seeks Europe-wide initiatives on labour-market measures aimed to promote employment. This is arrant nonsense. Such measures as may be advisable are either national initiatives (changes in taxes, benefits, education and training) or local (subsidies or other forms of special assistance, say, tailored to meet the needs of a particular area). Europe-wide policy is singularly ill-fitted to play any useful role. Indeed, in so far as the <font size=-1>EU</font> has a Europe-wide policy on labour markets--the social chapter--it is actually a destroyer of jobs; and Labour has said that Britain should surrender its opt-out from it. This implies not merely that Labour fails to understand unemployment but also that it regards a wider range of action for European policy as a good thing in itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A fine choice, then. The Tories have, for the most part, sound anti-statist prejudices and broadly the right economic ideas, but they carry an intellectually and diplomatically debilitating strain of jingoism. Labour seems to have a clearer view of Britain's place in the modern world, but favours damaging interventionist remedies in areas of policy where the <font size=-1>EU</font> has no useful role.



