<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1> An <i>Economist</i> manifesto </h1>

<i>A few ideas </i>

<p>FOR the moment, <i>The Economist</i> has no plans to run for office. But you never know. If we were to seek a mandate for government, what might our manifesto say? To begin with, of course, it would deplore the intellectual incoherence and weak leadership of the present government. Tradition demands as much and, on this occasion, the charges are fair. No doubt we would also deplore the intellectual incoherence and dishonest leadership of the main opposition party. Again, one could do no less. As to our own policies, the highlights of our programme would be as follows. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On macroeconomic policy, we would emphasise the folly of risking a rise in inflation for a temporary surge in growth: that way lies higher unemployment. Recognising the bias for inflation that is built into Britain's political culture, we would grant the Bank of England independence to determine interest rates, and give it a statutory duty to keep inflation below 3% a year. (A vote in Parliament could change that target in extraordinary circumstances.) The tradition of levying taxes sufficient to cover spending over the medium term would be revived, not as an end in itself but because it is the best way to keep interest rates down and investment up at any given level of economic activity. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On industrial policy, we could be brief: there wouldn't be one. Our view is that companies themselves are better equipped to make decisions on investment, staffing, location, working practices and the rest than the government. The goal of industrial policy, such as it is, should be to get out of their way. There would be but two small exceptions. We would aim to promote competition more vigorously than the Tories have done. (This would mean, among other things, changing the remit of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission so that its task was defined more narrowly in terms of promoting competition rather than, as at present, balancing that goal against the "public interest".) And we would take further steps to increase (not reduce, as Labour seems to favour) the accountability of managers to shareholders. Beyond that, we would privatise the postal service, the <font size=-1>BBC</font>, and any other enterprises we found remaining in public ownership and/or control. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Our priorities in employment policy would be to lower taxes on the working poor, and to institute a marked shift in education spending away from universities (where students would be obliged to pay their own way) and towards vocational training for 16-18-year-olds. No minimum wage, no social chapter, no other initiatives calculated to put people out of work. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We would aim to increase public spending on primary and secondary education. Here, and across the welfare state, "internal markets" would be developed with greater determination, using vouchers and other methods to improve providers' accountability to users. The Tories' policy of squeezing the state pension (which Labour is not pledged to change) would be explicitly embraced as a long term policy of abolition. Personal taxes would be reformed to encourage people to save for their own retirement. In due course, we would introduce a mandatory, state-subsidised, saving-for-retirement scheme, using competing private pension funds. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Overall, and in the long term, we would aim to keep the taxpayer-cost of the welfare state on a gently falling trend as a proportion of national income--an extremely demanding goal that allows for very little growth of spending in real terms. Except in the priority areas of education and training, therefore, pressures of the sort applied since 1979 would need to be maintained or increased. Even then, the scope for lower taxes would be limited. We would concentrate the savings on tax cuts for the low paid, aiming to take gradually increasing numbers out of income tax altogether. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We are constitutional reformers. Unlike Labour, and supposing the Scots vote for it in a referendum, we would give Scotland a parliament with matching control over taxes and domestic spending; the rights of Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s to sit and vote at Westminster would be correspondingly curtailed. (Wales would be offered the same arrangement, in the confident expectation that it would not want it.) On Northern Ireland, the constitutional settlement indicated in the government's framework document would be more resolutely pursued. The strategy of allowing the province's political parties to reach such an accord in their own good time would be abandoned: a settlement would be put directly to the people of Northern Ireland in a referendum. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We are sceptical about a bigger role for local government in Britain: many of the traditional tasks of this tier (notably education) can be brought more closely under users', rather than local bureaucrats', control. Elsewhere, it is doubtful that local communities have strong enough identities to support a healthy local politics. But we recognise that it is desirable to foster stronger local communities and would support local initiatives aimed at developing them, provided they were locally financed. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We would introduce a bill of rights and a freedom of information act. We would reform the Commons to increase the power of <font size=-1>MP</font>s, and especially committees of <font size=-1>MP</font>s, in relation to ministers. We regard other proposals for constitutional reform as much less important than measures such as these. Nonetheless, we favour denying hereditary peers the right to sit or vote in the House of Lords; further reform of the Lords would be considered. We will reveal our plans on electoral reform when we see how big our majority is. Labour says: "We have no plans to replace the monarchy." We do. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On Europe, our policy would be one of constructive engagement. We are in the European Union, glad to be there, and have strong views about how it should develop from now on. We regard the single market as a remarkable and valuable achievement, and we wish to see its benefits spread more widely (by including new members in Eastern Europe). Scrapping the common agricultural policy is a top priority. So is liberalising the union's external trade policy. Further political integration is undesirable. Subject to that, we have an open mind on <font size=-1>EMU</font>: even if Britain chooses not to join soon, or ever, we recognise the potential of the project to do good and want it to succeed.
<p><b>Send your contributions to&#160;. &#160;. &#160;.</b>
<br>How such a manifesto might fare in a general election must remain (fortunately) a matter for speculation. With apologies to Liberal Democrats, Scottish Nationalists, Plaid Cymru, Greens and what have you, the big choice that Britain will shortly make will be between another term for the Tories and a new start with New Labour. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>The Economist</i> doesn't have a vote either, but if it did how would we cast it? We disagree with the Tories about many things, but our biggest quarrel with them is over constitutional reform. Their complacency on the subject is deplorable. We also disagree with many of Labour's plans, but especially over industry and employment. In these areas, Labour's policies are much less dangerous than they used to be, but the desire to meddle harmfully (the minimum wage, the social chapter, managers' responsibilities to "stakeholders") has not entirely gone away. For different reasons, we regard both parties as hopelessly unsound on Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that is to speak only of the parties' expressed goals. The choice between the Tories and New Labour is a confusing one because, although the parties affect to despise each other, their policies sound pretty similar. If New Labour's conversion is to be believed, the forthcoming election does not matter much after all. But is it to be believed? By and large, this survey has judged the Tories according to what they have done up to now, and Labour by what they say they will do. Yet ballots are cast on the basis not of what the parties say, but of what people expect them actually to do. In Labour's case, this credibility gap is already large, and may well grow larger.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of those who believe that Mr Blair will yield to the left in office, at least as many will vote Labour on that account as will vote Tory. Labour's traditional supporters, the millions who voted for the party when its policies were crazy, will support it next time in the hope that, once in power, it will drop the modish new talk about enterprise and initiative and get down to its rightful business of soaking the rich. If Labour wins, it will be because those voters act in concert with others, courted so assiduously by Mr Blair, who believe that the party will not relapse. To hold such a curious coalition together until polling-day would be a political masterstroke: to maintain it much beyond then would require a political genius.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But perhaps Mr Blair <i>is</i> a political genius. Without a doubt, what appeals most about New Labour is that the party is superbly led. Mr Blair is forceful and passionate. His manner, if not his manifesto, radiates purpose and conviction. John Major may have broadly the right policies (as New Labour seems to agree), but as a leader he is a sorry sight. The harder he tries to project a big idea--and he has had so many--the more ridiculous he becomes. The country is sick of him and so, frankly, are we. Who gets our vote? We're still thinking about it, but we will be sure to let you know in good time.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur ">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
