<html><head><title>The tyranny of success&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<img src="soft5.gif"  alt="Software"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>The tyranny of success&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.</h1>


<i>.&#160;.&#160;. and the success of tyranny.
Microsoft knows both


</i><p>THE <font size=-1>PC</font> Forum, an annual conference that attracts some of the biggest names in the computer industry, is a hard place to get noticed, especially if you are a relatively obscure economist. It is a place for networking and deal-making, where the industry's big wheels get together to schmooze. Yet when Brian Arthur reached the podium to give his speech last year he had to utter only one word to freeze a hundred conversations in mid-sentence: "Microsoft". Bill Gates and his empire command fear, respect and curiosity in the world he helped create. Microsoft dominates the software world like no other company in a major consumer industry. More than three-quarters of <font size=-1>PC</font> "productivity applications"--the largest packaged-software category, including word processors, spreadsheets and databases--sold today comes from its campus in Redmond, Washington. Even Coca-Cola only has half-of the soft-drinks market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Microsoft announces that it is entering a new software category, it causes panic among the incumbents. WordPerfect and Lotus once had seemingly unassailable domination of word processing and spreadsheets, their respective categories. But when Microsoft released its own Windows products, it cleverly bundled them into Office, a "suite" that cost less than half as much together as its stand-alone competitors apart. Today Microsoft has 90% of that market, and both Lotus and WordPerfect have been bought by other firms. Over the years Microsoft has expanded the definition of an operating system to include dozens of functions, from back-up utilities to e-mail software, that were once the profitable domain of independent companies, some of which have now gone bust.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No wonder some of Microsoft's competitors look on it as a force of evil in the industry. They claim that it unfairly exploits its ownership of the <font size=-1>PC</font> operating system in a hundred little ways (for example, by including secret parts of Windows that help its own applications). Never mind that these charges usually evaporate under scrutiny: much of the software world is convinced that Microsoft simply does not play fair. For most of the 1990s, companies have been badgering America's antitrust authorities with complaints about Microsoft's alleged monopolistic abuses. Yet a series of investigations by the Justice Department (and later the competition authorities of the European Union) have turned up little of substance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of the complaints are sour grapes from lesser companies. But Microsoft does play rough, and some of its technology decisions do look suspicious (installing Windows 95 and The Microsoft Network, for example, can disable rival on-line services). The battles have left a cloud over Redmond. Much of the enthusiasm for Netscape, network computers and Java is generated by the fact that they are simply Not Microsoft.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even Microsoft's customers, who have seen their computing headaches diminish with the company's ascendancy, think of Microsoft as the firm they "hate to love, not love to hate", in the words of Forrester Research, a consultancy. A <font size=-1>PC</font> that runs nothing but Office, Windows 95 and other Microsoft software is easy to set up and will probably work well. But if such convenience comes at the cost of squeezing competitors out of business, thus stifling innovation, only Microsoft wins in the long run. Customers know that choice, even if it comes with complexity, is worth preserving.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may explain why so many industry pundits claim, perhaps wishfully, that the day in August 1995 when Windows 95 was released marked Microsoft's peak: not, perhaps, in absolute terms (the firm continues to grow at an extraordinary rate) but in sheer industry dominance. The arguments to support the claim come in two parts. First, the pundits say, Microsoft has conquered all the easy ground already: as its traditional markets become saturated, growth will become slower and less profitable. Second, they continue, the Internet changes everything. It will turn Microsoft's operating-system advantages into so much surplus baggage, slowing it as nimble newcomers sprint ahead.
</p><p><b>Thinking the unthinkable</b>
<br>To consider the decline of Microsoft today seems almost perverse. After all, the company has never done better: it is on track for net profits of over $2 billion, a rise of more than 40%, on sales of over $8 billion this year. It has some of the cleverest programmers in the industry, and still seems able to attract the best talent. Its products, although in most categories not the best, come a very close second. Some of its smaller bets have failed, such as its backing for interactive <font size=-1>TV</font> software, a version of Windows for telephones and fax machines, and a cartoon-like interface called "Bob". But the big bets usually pay off. Windows 95 may not have matched its hype, but it is undeniably a success.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet <font size=-1>IBM</font> also looked good when the <font size=-1>PC</font> was born in 1981. The Internet amounts to another such revolution, which Microsoft must face at the same time as its traditional businesses are starting to slow. Just as <font size=-1>IBM</font> is still a huge and profitable company today, so Microsoft is likely to continue to prosper. But over the next decade its domination of the industry will become increasingly hard to maintain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For most of Microsoft's history it has grown between 30% and 40% a year, almost always faster than the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry as a whole, itself one of the world's fastest-growing markets. Wall Street is counting on more of the same. Were Microsoft to slow to, say, the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry's expected growth rate of 18% this year (great for most companies, but half Microsoft's usual rate), the share price might slide. Yet stock options are one of the carrots that Microsoft uses to attract the brightest software engineers and get them to give up all semblance of a life. More than 2,000 Microsoft employees have become millionaires that way. If the share price were to stop rising, let alone fall, the 14-hour days might seem a lot less bearable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a sense, the company has been too successful. It is approaching saturation in its core markets, and no new markets as lucrative as the Office suite (which now generates more than a third of the company's revenues) have emerged (see <a href="csu396.gif">chart</a>). Virtually all new <font size=-1>PC</font>s are already sold with Microsoft's operating systems. There is no market in suites left to take from other firms, and most of the biggest corporate customers already have all the word processors and spreadsheets they need (more than half of new <font size=-1>PC</font>s sold to companies are now replacements).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the past few years, Microsoft's main growth plan has been to encroach further on the "client-server" turf: the industrial-strength software (such as large databases and internal communications software) that runs big companies. When earlier this year Microsoft put the finishing touches to its "BackOffice" package of database and communications software, there was none of the Windows 95 razzmatazz; the corporate world is a conservative place. But Windows <font size=-1>NT</font>, Microsoft's operating system for servers--computers that hold data and programs to be shared across a company--is starting to take off; sales have doubled over the past year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, rich though the client-server market may be, it is harder going than the <font size=-1>PC</font> productivity applications were. The competition in this big-business market is tougher (from <font size=-1>IBM</font> to Oracle), the buyers more cautious and demanding, and the growth slower. Microsoft is already winning market share, but not without a large investment of time and effort, at a time when it can least afford to take its eyes off the Internet.
</p><p><b>The beam in Microsoft's eye</b></b>
<br>As Microsoft marshalled its troops for this assault on the corporate ramparts, it almost missed what was happening on the public networks under its nose. Not until the winter of 1993, when a Microsoft employee sent back a memo from Cornell University reporting that ordinary students there were more wired than Microsoft's own engineers, did Mr Gates consider the possibility that the Internet, though not invented on his own campus, might have to be taken seriously. Even so, it took Microsoft another two years to grasp what the Internet might do to its business unless it embraced radical change.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For example, the company introduced the Microsoft Network with great fanfare in August last year, even though both the network and its content were based on proprietary standards, closed to others on the Internet. It was a curious mistake, especially since established on-line services had already acknowledged that such proprietary networks had no future in a world opened up by the Web.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last December, Microsoft admitted defeat by moving the Microsoft Network and its much-touted publishing tools for developers to the Web, infuriating those companies that had invested their time and money developing content for the network. It licensed Java, and announced that it would be adapting all of its main products, from its word processors to the Windows <font size=-1>NT</font> operating system, to work on the Internet. It has largely delivered on its promise, releasing dozens of new Internet products in an extraordinarily rapid turnaround for such a large firm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft seems at last to have become serious ("hardcore", as Mr Gates puts it) about the Internet. Cynics say this is not so much because of the clarity of its vision but because it is terrified that Netscape and Sun might be right: the Internet really could be a new platform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The very combination of the words "platform" and "Internet" is a red flag to the Microsoft faithful. From Mr Gates downwards, they rubbish the idea that a simple ("trivial", in Mr Gates's language) browser and yet another programming language (and a slow one at that) can seriously be considered a platform. It is easy to see why they find it threatening: Microsoft rose with the <font size=-1>PC</font>, and might fall with it. If the Internet were to become the dominant computing platform, then the <font size=-1>PC</font> would be just one of many machines that can access the Internet. Its relative importance--and sales--would decline, and so would Microsoft's operating-system revenues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So it makes sense for Microsoft to preserve the <font size=-1>PC</font>'s--and hence its own--dominance at all costs. It sees little Netscape as one of its most serious threats. When Netscape won the browser market by initially giving away its software, Microsoft developed its own browser and promised to give it away indefinitely. In response to Netscape's success in selling Web server software, Microsoft gave away a Web server with its Windows <font size=-1>NT</font> operating system. And after Netscape licensed Java and built it into its browser, Microsoft went one better by announcing that it would not only build Java into its own browser but that it would integrate it with its own Java-like programming standard for Windows, a package of technologies known collectively as ActiveX. This April it went the full way, agreeing to incorporate Java into Windows itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Microsoft is successful, it will preserve the <font size=-1>PC</font> as the favoured Internet access device, and therefore protect its place on the desktop. But that will not stop the software market from increasingly shifting to the Internet itself. The battle for this market is very different from that in the early days of the <font size=-1>PC</font>. Then, it was winner take all. On the Internet, there may be no single winner at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Mr Andreessen puts it, the <font size=-1>PC</font> had two "control points"--the microprocessor and the operating system. The companies that took the lead there--Intel and Microsoft--have been able to control the pace and direction of the machine's development, usually to their own benefit. Depending on how you look at it, the Internet has either infinitely more such points or none at all. Dozens of companies are trying to set their own standards for everything from telephony to security and electronic commerce. Yet so far the only true standards, from the underlying technology of the network to the basic language of the Web, have been open--developed by committees or academics or otherwise in the public domain. This may not last: the financial rewards for standard-setters are as great on the Internet as anywhere else. But seeing how far the Internet has come without such ownership, it will be hard for anyone, even Bill Gates, to gain as much control of the Internet as Microsoft has of the <font size=-1>PC</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft, as it happens, agrees. But it does not think it needs such an advantage to extend its success to the Internet. It rejects the idea that its gains in word processors or spreadsheets had anything to do with its domination of the operating system: it simply sold better products at a better price than its competitors. This is a bit of revisionist history--it discounts, among other things, the cross-subsidies possible when you are assured $50 from the price of virtually every new <font size=-1>PC</font>--but it is more true than the operating-system-as-manifest-destiny version that is painted by its competitors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year, the betting in Silicon Valley was that Netscape was too far ahead and too nimble for Microsoft to catch. Now the geeks have recovered their respect for Mr Gates. Microsoft could still lose: although it has come a long way, it is still about six months behind Netscape. That is a big lead on the Internet, said to move in "dog years" (one for seven). But at least nobody could accuse Microsoft of failing to understand how these markets work.


