<html><head><title>Microsoft's media mania</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Microsoft's media mania</h1>


<p>ON MICROSOFT's sprawling campus, one of the many glass-and-chrome buildings yields an unexpected sight: a big room that looks to all the world like a television newsroom on full alert. It is the morning of April 3rd, and the aeroplane carrying the American secretary of commerce has just crashed. A news director shouts out instructions as reporters hang on the phones and producers hunch over banks of computers to get the story on the air. As it unfolds, a wall full of television monitors shows a live press conference, news channels and satellite feeds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is the newsroom of the Microsoft Network (<font size=-1>MSN</font>), and it offers a hint of how serious Microsoft is about moving beyond the software business. Bill Gates may have started his career as a programmer, but he seems to want to end it as a media mogul. If money can buy that, he is well on his way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beyond <font size=-1>MSN</font>, Microsoft has a $400m partnership with <font size=-1>NBC</font>, the television network, to produce <font size=-1>MSNBC</font>, which will include a cable <font size=-1>TV</font> news channel and an Internet news service. It has invested $30m in Dreamworks, Hollywood's newest studio, and is collaborating with Tele-Communications Inc, a cable <font size=-1>TV</font> giant. Last year it hired Michael Kinsley, a former editor of the <i>New Republic</i> (who has also worked on <i>The Economist</i>) to start a political magazine on the Internet. It is planning on-line magazines in several big cities, covering arts and entertainment, and setting up a host of other Internet services, from a car<i>-</i>shopping bazaar to a childcare information centre.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gates exchanges deal-making gossip with such entertainment industry giants as David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg, and greatly admires Disney's brand. "Content is king," he writes in his syndicated newspaper column<i>. </i>He studies the economics of the newspaper business and watches the rise of on-line advertising dollars. "We are in essence trying to figure out how to be an interactive media company," explains Peter Neupert, who negotiates Microsoft's content deals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gates's media obsession goes deep, from his voracious reading habits to his admiration for the broadcasting industry. But his confidence in Microsoft's potential in this market comes straight from "Encarta". Microsoft's foray into multimedia encyclopedias has been indisputably successful. Within two years of its release in 1993, Encarta had become the best-selling encyclopedia of any sort, whether on paper or <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, its success seemed almost effortless. Microsoft licensed most of the content from a second-tier encyclopedia maker, then wrote the software to make it easy and fun to use. As sales took off, the lesson seemed clear: traditional firms in this business did not have the understanding or the technical skills to succeed in the computer world. Microsoft did, and beat the experts at their own game. Perhaps the rest of the media world would succumb to the same strategy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Or perhaps not. Encarta may simply have been a fluke. Microsoft makes dozens of other education and entertainment <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, from Microsoft "Dogs" to a wine guide, and none of them is anywhere near as successful. Analysts reckon that, but for Encarta, the division would be losing money. Indeed, the shine even on Encarta may be wearing off: most copies are included free with new <font size=-1>PC</font>s, not bought in stores, and the rest of the encyclopedia industry, jolted by Microsoft's success, has taken a crash course in going digital. Encyclopaedia Britannica, which was hurt most, is now on the Internet. The site may have none of Encarta's multimedia fun, but it does have deep and rich information on any subject--something Microsoft had to scrimp on to make room for the videos on the <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>. In the end, consumers may remember why they wanted an encyclopedia in the first place.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft acknowledges that it knows little about the news business or, for that matter, any other media business. But it does know about software, and it reckons that in tomorrow's interactive world the successful media companies will be those who master both content and technology. And it is betting that it can buy and nurture talent and creativity more easily than traditional media giants can master interactivity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the medium really is the message. But it is early days yet in the Internet revolution, and the media giants have plenty of time to catch on. Meanwhile, in the <font size=-1>MSN</font> newsroom, Mark Pawlowsky, a harried ex-newspaperman, is trying to teach youngsters wearing baseball caps the wrong way round how to be reporters. "We're not a racehorse yet," he says. Microsoft has a lot of money to bet on this experiment, but the odds do not look enticing.


</td></tr></table>
