<html><head><title>The importance of being American</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="soft7.gif"  alt="Software">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1>The importance of being American</h1>


<i>Can the rest of the world catch up?

</i><p>IF EVERYTHING is going software, most of the world is in trouble and America is laughing. It makes an estimated three-quarters of the packaged software sold worldwide, worth $100 billion now and growing as the <font size=-1>PC</font> becomes a global standard. The next largest, Britain and Germany, have less than 10% of the market between them. Most of the world's rich countries, and now increasingly some of the poor ones too, have domestic software industries, often with hundreds of companies (see <a href="csu342.gif">chart</a>). But none has even come close to challenging America on the world market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first reason for this imbalance is that software simply follows hardware: America is where computing started and where it has grown fastest. Nearly half the world's computing power is in America, seven times more than in Japan, its closest competitor. America offers software companies a single market of more than 60m <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Germany's <font size=-1>PC</font> market, the second biggest, is no more than a quarter of that.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same factors that spawned Silicon Valley's hardware industry are at work in software. America has the largest venture-capital market in the world. It has a stockmarket, Nasdaq, made for small, fast-growing firms. Its various technology meccas have attracted a critical mass of other firms in the computer industry that serve both as suppliers and customers, and provide a source of inspiration and ideas for each other. And on both coasts it has world-class university computer departments and research centres.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's software strength has created its own positive feedback cycle. The international language of computing is English. Non-American software companies with international ambitions have tended to incorporate themselves as American firms simply to be taken seriously (a habit that makes it difficult to get accurate figures of other countries' software strength). Bill Gates has become an American hero. Geeks are cool.
</p><p><b>The new internationalists</b></b>
<br>The Internet, too, is largely an American phenomenon, but it has helped software firms everywhere. By creating a single global market for software, the Internet cuts through many of the distribution and marketing barriers that have kept foreign software firms from making headway in America. And since a company's Web presence often provides no clue to its physical location, firms that market and sell their software on-line no longer have to set up shop in America to be taken seriously.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;VocalTec, <font size=-1>VDO</font>net and CheckPoint are three of the hotter Internet companies, making, respectively, an Internet telephone, video software and security software. Many of their customers may not know that all three of them are Israeli firms. NeuronData, a French programming tools company, and Micromuse, a British network software firm, are able to keep quiet about their national origins in the same way. On the Web, companies appear to reside in the here and now, open for business round the clock somewhere on your screen. It may be the middle of the night in Herzlia, Israel, but VocalTec's Web site gets busiest when America takes a lunch break.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet cannot eliminate all of the disadvantages non-American firms face. There are still the problems of financing, language and such intangibles as the number of people at the local coffee bar whose idea of a gripping conversation is an analysis of the latest Java compilers. But it does help their prospects. Here are a few of the countries that are already a force in software, and stand to benefit most from the Internet's global market:
<ul>

<font size=-1><li></font>Germany owes its relative software strength mostly to the meteoric rise of a newcomer, <font size=-1>SAP</font>, and the continued growth of a giant from the mainframe days, Software <font size=-1>AG</font>. Both now specialise in client-server software, having developed their skills by writing custom accounting and database software for large German companies. With a sophisticated package of products already in hand when it entered the American market, <font size=-1>SAP</font> became one of the fastest-growing software firms in the industry, and now ranks fifth in the world. But popular though its software is, it is also big, complicated and expensive to install. Analysts reckon this will soon slow <font size=-1>SAP</font>'s climb; so far no other German software rocket has emerged to take its place.

<p><font size=-1><li></font>Britain, it seems, has always been just on the verge of a software boom. It has most of the right ingredients: world-class computer research institutions, hundreds of small software companies, and proportionately more <font size=-1>PC</font>s and Internet connections than most other European countries. It even speaks the right language. Until Germany's <font size=-1>SAP</font> took off, Britain had the strongest software industry outside America, with three companies--Misys, <font size=-1>JBA</font> International and the Micro Focus Group--in the world's top 50. But none of its software firms has become a billion-dollar world-beater. Why not? The answer seems familiar: the big firms are mostly in slow-growth mainframe markets, and the newer <font size=-1>PC</font> software firms have been hampered by the lack, until recently, of a small-company stockmarket and enough venture capital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Too often promising British firms have put technology ahead of marketing, and have been beaten by louder American competitors. And most of the consumer-software companies that sprouted up in the 1980s developed programs for the Acorn computer, a proprietary design that has been largely buried under the <font size=-1>PC</font> avalanche. Britain's software future may lie in its cottage industry of small computer-games makers, which have developed some of the best 3-D graphics technologies.

<p><font size=-1><li></font>France loves technology, and its computer researchers are some of the best in the world. Perhaps they are just too good: French firms are best known for state-of-the-art programming tools; they are less successful at using those tools to create mass-market applications software. Business Objects, NeuronData, <font size=-1>ILOG</font>--all have grown quickly with the industry's move to "object-oriented" programming, a French speciality. But making software for other programmers is by definition a niche market, something Philippe Kahn, often described as France's most successful software export, learned to his cost when Borland, his programming-tools company in Boston, imploded after trying to challenge Microsoft.

<p><font size=-1><li></font>Israel has long had a stronger technology industry than the country's size would suggest, and is doing especially well in Internet software. Like most of the country's technology industries, this one has been helped by military funding. Like the Internet itself (which was designed to resist atomic attack), many of the technologies of warfare--such as signal processing and encryption--have found new applications on-line. Signal processing lies at the core of video and audio compression, and encryption is the key to the tough problem of Internet security. Israel's traditionally close ties with American business and financial markets are likely to ensure that its software firms will prosper over the next few years.

<p><font size=-1><li></font>India is pushing hard to become a force in the software industry, with some success. It reckons its domestic firms will sell $1 billion-worth of software and services next year. But most of this is work being done for others: India biggest software firms are contractors who offer cheap programming services, mostly for American firms. With an average Indian programmer's salary less than a third of his American counterpart's, Indian firms reckon they can undercut American firms by 40% or more, even after allowing for telecoms and other costs of such long-distance work. The Indian government, having failed in the 1970s to coax a domestic computer industry into life by imposing high tariffs on American computer technology, is investing in satellite links to bypass the country's appalling telecoms networks, and most software firms have power generators to weather the frequent brown-outs. But although India has become the world's favourite software jobshop, it has yet prove that it can come up with software products of its own.

<p><font size=-1><li></font>Japan is a software cipher. Even though it has the second-largest number of programmers in the world, it cannot claim a single success abroad in packaged software (other than in video games). The explanations for this baffling failure include language, the dominance in Japan until recently of various proprietary and incompatible <font size=-1>PC</font> standards, and the preference of Japanese firms for commissioning software unique to their company. In a 1994 study on Japan's software problems, Edward Feigenbaum, a Stanford computer scientist, calculated that such custom software accounts for about 90% of the Japanese industry's output. In the past year, sales of standard <font size=-1>PC</font>s have rocketed in Japan, as have Internet connections. But with software engineering still considered a less respectable occupation than hardware engineering, where the country has traditionally been strong, a Japanese Bill Gates seems a long way off.
</ul>


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,sur">Search</a>
