<html><head><title>The new world&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="soft8.gif"  alt="Software">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<h1>The new world&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.</h1>


<i>.&#160;.&#160;. &#160;looks a bit like the old world, but with a difference: software every where, but never a program in sight.

</i><p>SOFTWARE is so abstract and ephemeral--just ones and zeros, recorded in tiny magnetic fluctuations or microscopic pockmarks--that its true economic significance is not always recognised. Computer hardware is much easier to quantify by the usual measures of the industrial age: chips, boxes, lorryloads. To use the language of Nicholas Negroponte, the <font size=-1>MIT</font> Media Lab's digital guru, computers are atoms. Software is bits. Atoms can be weighed, seen and felt. Bits, like genetic code, are inanimate--until they are placed into the right vessel. Then they use that vessel's machinery to create life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The beauty of the computer--indeed, the basis of its world-changing success--is that it is totally unspecialised. A toaster has just one job: it toasts. A <font size=-1>PC</font>, on the other hand, is more like a blank sheet of paper: it is a generic device that serves as a carrier and a repository for ideas of any sort, from "Rebel Assault II" to "Richard III". Partly for this reason, the hardware and software worlds have grown up very differently. Hardware exists to do the bidding of software, not the other way around. Both can be good businesses to be in, but on balance software has the economic edge. Microsoft enjoys gross margins of 85% while Compaq, the leading <font size=-1>PC</font>-hardware maker, makes do with 23%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the early 1980s, all the fun and games in the computer industry was in the battle between hardware companies. Would <font size=-1>IBM</font> lose its lead to clone makers? Would Apple's Macintosh beat the <font size=-1>PC</font>? Would the <font size=-1>PC</font> beat the mainframe? Today all those questions have been answered; the <font size=-1>PC</font> won, but unlike in software, no single company won with it. The <font size=-1>PC</font> industry is now becoming a rather dull and conventional consumer-electronics market, with most of the competition focused on brand, price and quality. The excitement in the industry has shifted to the bits, and those bits are now starting to move away from the <font size=-1>PC</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This move from the desktop to the network has become a kind of Rorschach test for the giant software companies. Each of them sees in the Internet only what it wants to see. Every one of them believes that, either by good luck or good management, the network plays right to their strengths.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>IBM</font> points out that the shift away from desktop computers and back towards servers is a vindication of its dogged loyalty to the mainframe, which it now calls a "superserver". Oracle argues that servers are really only machines running big, specialised databases, of just the sort it has been making all these years. Computer Associates thinks that the gaping security holes exposed by the Internet-driven boom in servers of all sorts will open up a great market for security specialists--such as itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sun never tires of reminding punters that it coined the then-baffling slogan, "The Network is the Computer", back in 1988. Microsoft notes that the Internet is in large part an expansion of the client-server strategy it has been building up for years. <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s Lotus subsidiary explains that the Internet is all about collaboration and communications, just like its Notes groupware. Novell claims that the Internet is built on a foundation of office networks, where it happens to dominate, and believes that the Internet will extend Novell's software all the way to appliances in the home. When Adobe looks at the Web, it sees a booming publishing industry, much like the paper-based desktop publishing market it has already claimed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They could all be right: the Internet is a broad church. But history suggests that when industries shift direction, most existing companies are left behind. "Some companies will make the transition," says James Breyer, a venture capitalist, "but the vast majority of the software leaders today will lose their leadership over the next two years."
</p><p><b>Changing places</b></b>
<br>This is a clash of the old world and the new. But they are not mutually exclusive. Just as the <font size=-1>PC</font> did not replace the mainframe, the Internet will not somehow replace the <font size=-1>PC</font> (nor will Java, nor the $500 Network Computer, nor even the mainframe reinvented as a server). It is worth noting that today, 15 years after the <font size=-1>PC</font> revolution began, <font size=-1>IBM</font> is by far the largest software company in the world, with software revenues of nearly $13 billion last year--getting on for twice those of Microsoft.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the roles have been switched, in a strange sort of way. Microsoft is now in the position formerly occupied by <font size=-1>IBM</font>, deeply committed to the status quo and in danger of missing the new opportunities if it tries too hard to protect its existing business. <font size=-1>IBM</font> is in the curious position of oversized underdog. Having fumbled the <font size=-1>PC</font>, it talks about leapfrogging straight from the mainframe to the Internet. With its share price near a five-year high, it runs taunting advertisements insisting that its stubborn vision was right all along. "Correction," reads one full-page <font size=-1>IBM</font> display. "Over the past few years, several publications have predicted the demise of the mainframe. This was a typographical error. What they meant was the 'rise' of the mainframe, not the 'demise'..."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Irving Wladawsky-Berger, who heads <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s Internet division, argues that once companies move from internal networks supporting a few hundred people to sophisticated Web sites supporting thousands, they will rediscover the charms of Big Iron's security and reliability.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet seems to have a magical ability to make the old new again. One of the hottest services on the Web is a search site at Digital Equipment, a minicomputers-to-workstations maker that almost went under a few years ago. Larry Ellison at Oracle has a vision of a cheap Network Computer (<font size=-1>NC</font>) that sounds a lot like an <font size=-1>X</font>-terminal, a technology that has been struggling for acceptance for nearly a decade. The <font size=-1>NC</font> itself goes back to a design by Britain's Acorn, one of the many proprietary home-computer makers to fall under the wheels of the <font size=-1>PC</font> train in the mid-1980s. And even Java is based on a language originally designed for interactive television "set-top boxes" before that market imploded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For software, the Internet requires an entirely new model. Today most packaged software is sold in a big and mostly empty box for somewhere between $50 and $300. Tomorrow it will be sold on-line for much less, perhaps a few pennies per use. It may take the form of Java applets, downloaded on demand, or run remotely as a paid-for service.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape's Mr Andreessen thinks software, as a stand-alone product, will simply fade away. "Software application, content and services used to be three separate things. They just merged." After all, he argues, most users do not want to run a program, they want to do their work, find information, or be entertained. Software will be hidden in content, like closed-captioned information in a television signal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much of today's software will probably remain largely as it is. There is no need to reinvent the word processors and spreadsheets we use now. But the overall software pie will grow immeasurably, as specially tailored software finds its way into everything from the morning on-line newspaper to a downloaded tax form.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It may also open the industry to a multitude of newcomers who have not been able to surmount the barriers to entry of today's <font size=-1>PC</font> software distribution channels and monolithic applications. "Software will look more like publishing," says Paul Cubbage, a former analyst with Dataquest, a consultancy. "There's a huge well-spring of people who are willing to develop software--they just don't want to get into marketing and starting a company. The Internet will be like cable <font size=-1>TV</font>: a huge monster that eats up interactive content."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an Internet computing world, prices will drop but (remember Doomonomics) volume will rise spectacularly (see <a href="csu340.gif">chart</a>). "What's been propping up the price of software is the perceived value of the big box and the manuals," says Mr Cubbage. "Would you pay $299 for a bare <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> or an Internet download?" Sun, having released Java into the world without an obvious way of cashing in on it, now hopes to make its money as a broker, keeping track of the micro-payments each time a user downloads a Java applet. In a volume business, a few cents here and a few cents there can add up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These network programs, then, are the new species of software's next epoch. They will populate the thousands of new niches that will open as the Internet's combination of global reach, infinite capacity and near-zero marginal costs infiltrates the traditional economy. At first some of them will seem as strange as the armoured tankfish or the mammoth when they first appeared on earth, but they will be better suited to their new wired world than their predecessors were. Software, like life itself, adapts wonderfully to change.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
