<html><head><title>System failure</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib2.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<h1>System failure</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Collapse is less likely than it used to be, but the possibility is no less frightening</i>


<p>IN THE City of London and on Wall Street, this may seem an odd time to talk about financial problems. After all, for the past three years many banks on both sides of the Atlantic have been enjoying an unusually long run of record profits and soaring share prices. Yet this is no cause for complacency, if only because experience shows that banks' bad-debt problems tend to surface only once an economy begins to slow. Besides, it is not so long ago that British and American banks were also in trouble. During the dark days of the early 1990s, even some of the biggest looked decidedly shaky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On balance, however, banking is probably a sounder business today than it was in the past. For a start, banks now have fatter capital cushions than they used to, which should help them to cope with unexpected shocks. As part of the Basle capital-adequacy agreement, which came into effect fully in 1992 and set minimum standards for international banks' capital levels, these banks are supposed to hold capital equal to at least 8% of their risk-weighted assets. In addition, they must also have "tier-one" capital (mostly equity) equal to at least 4% of their risk-weighted assets. Most countries' big international banks are now comfortably above that minimum figure (see <a href="images/csu254.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As another form of self-defence, banks have also developed their own sophisticated risk-management systems. These have enabled them to identify more clearly the risks that they are running in both their lending and trading business, and to hedge, or insure themselves, against those that do not offset one another; and they have made senior managers focus more sharply on the profitability (or lack of it) of different businesses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some big banks, such as America's J.P. Morgan, have even touted part of their risk-management packages to rivals. They have several motives. One is that there is money to be made from advising statistically-challenged bankers, who have not developed sophisticated systems of their own. Another, more public-spirited one, is that the more sophisticated the banking system's component parts can be made, the safer it will be as a whole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Deregulation has also strengthened banks in several ways. In America, it has allowed them to begin diversifying geographically. This should reduce some banks' dependence on the economies of single states and, with luck, make a re-run of the Texas and New England banking collapses of the 1980s less likely. At the same time, banks have continued to diversify beyond their bread-and-butter lending business. This makes sense because their role as middlemen is being undermined by the securities markets, which match borrowers and lenders directly. That is why many American and Japanese institutions have set up their own underwriting and trading operations in legally distinct subsidiaries, thus partially getting round the legal restrictions that separate commercial and investment banking in both countries.

</p><p><b>Fatter ratios, fitter banks</b>
<br>In Europe, where banks have long had a foot in both camps, the trading one is getting bigger: witness the unseemly rush by Swiss and German bankers to lay their hands on medium-sized British merchant banks with large trading outfits. Another form of diversification, <i>bancassurance</i>--tie-ups between banks and insurance companies--is still all the rage in Europe too. American bankers would love to sell more insurance, but have met stiff resistance from the country's insurance agents. They have, however, built up their fund-management operations and other fee-earning activities. Income from these and from trading has helped to offset what they have lost in their traditional lending business. According to a recent study* for New York's Federal Reserve Bank by two economists, Franklin Edwards and Frederic Mishkin, non-interest income from fees and trading as a proportion of American commercial banks' total income rose from an average of 19% in 1960-80 to 35% in 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Fatter capital ratios, fancy risk-management systems and faster diversification: all of these things are undoubtedly creating a fitter banking system. At the same time, they are probably reducing the threat of a systemic crisis. To see why, consider what makes a banking system vulnerable to disruption if a bank fails. Although in some way every case is unique, there are some common themes. According to Philip Bartholomew and Gary Whalen, two economists at the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, which oversees America's nationally chartered banks, these can be summed up in a few words: concentration, homogeneity, information and connections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The greater the <b>concentration</b> of a bank's loan portfolio in a single company, industry or country, the greater the chance that it will collapse if a single borrower, or group of borrowers, defaults. The same principle holds true for its trading business. Concentration is not necessarily a bad thing: it may simply reflect the bank's competitive advantage in a particular area. Moreover, by focusing on a narrow set of borrowers or counterparties, a bank may get to know them well and therefore become a better judge of their creditworthiness. But, in general, the less diversified its relationships, the more vulnerable it is to a shock.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If it does fail, others are likely to follow only if depositors at these banks think that there is a great deal of <b>homogeneity</b> between the casualty and the rest. If they conclude that there is, the result may be a bank panic. They may of course have got it wrong. But they can tell only if plenty of good <b>information</b> about banks' finances is widely available. The more there is, the easier it will be for depositors, creditors and counterparties to distinguish between good and bad banks. Sometimes word of mouth will suffice. For example, many institutions knew at an early stage that the Bank of Credit and Commerce International (<font size=-1>BCCI</font>) was crooked, and therefore avoided dealing with it, which explains why its closure in 1991 had no knock-on effect.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other factor that determines the gravity of a systemic threat is the extent of the <b>connections</b> between different financial institutions. If a bank that collapses is a lone wolf that has had little to do with other banks (as in <font size=-1>BCCI</font>'s case), regulators can wash their hands of it. But if it is a big player in a particular market, a sizeable lender to other banks or an important link in payments and settlements systems, then they may think twice before allowing it to fail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In two respects, matters have improved somewhat. First, lenders claim to have become savvier about assessing credit risk, or the chance that a borrower will default. Some banks, such as Britain's Barclays and Australia's Westpac, are trying to measure this risk more accurately and put a price on it. Barclays even sets aside a specific provision for credit risk when it makes loans. Such calculations rely on the risk-reducing benefits of diversification.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, more information is now available about banks' finances. Much of this is provided by private credit-rating agencies such as Moody's, Standard &amp; Poor's and <font size=-1>IBCA</font>, which rate various types of debt issued by banks. Their job has been made easier because banks have been securitising more of their loans--packaging them into bundles that can be traded in a marketplace. Among the most common debts that have been sold in this way are banks' mortgage repayments, credit-card receivables and sovereign loans. By establishing a market price for these and other debts, such as loans to small businesses, securitisation allows outsiders to estimate the value of some of a bank's assets with greater accuracy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Welcome though these trends are, they have not banished systemic risk for good. For a start, it seems that not all bankers may have cottoned on to risk management in lending. Over the past year or so, regulators have repeatedly given warning that margins have become dangerously thin in the syndicated-loan business, in which banks club together to lend collectively to large firms (see <a href="images/csu216.gif">chart</a>). And last month Michael Foot, the Bank of England's new head of supervision, said that stiff competition for mortgage business between banks and building societies (thrifts) could cause lenders problems if loans later turn sour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The process of securitisation is also a double-edged sword. Many of the loans that banks have disposed of in this way are top-quality, low-risk credits that appeal to a broad range of investors. Those left on their balance sheets are poorer-quality ones, which are more likely to cause problems.
</p><p><b>Cock-ups will happen</b>
<br>Even if banks have decent risk-management systems, they are not immune from what they like to call "operations risk"--a polite word for management cock-ups. At Barings, Nick Leeson, the bank's nemesis, was able to disguise huge losses because the bank committed a cardinal sin at its futures operation in Singapore: it let him keep his own books. Such lax internal controls are not as rare as they should be. Toshihide Iguchi, a bond trader in the New York branch of Japan's Daiwa Bank, somehow managed to hide his mounting losses over a period of 11 years. When he finally owned up to them in October 1995, they had reached an astonishing $1.1 billion. This blew a hole in Daiwa's balance sheet, but luckily it was not fatal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another caveat is that the financial figures available from banks often do not give an accurate picture of their true net worth. Most of their accounts are still drawn up on the basis of historic-cost accounting, so they inevitably fail to capture rapid changes in the risks being run. This gap between financial reporting and reality has grown as banks have taken on more fast-changing market risk--the risk that the price of their holdings of securities or derivatives may fall--via their proprietary trading operations, which bet the banks' own capital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the threat of a systemic crisis has probably diminished, the damage that one could do if it did happen has increased exponentially. This is because financial liberalisation and the growth of global trade have brought about changes in national and international financial systems that have reinforced links between banks, as well as their ties with the financial markets. The following figures are only a snapshot of a few of these connections, but they tell a startling story.
</p><p><b>Doomsday scenario</b>
<br>In 1980 the size of America's interbank loan market was $74 billion; by 1995, it had almost doubled, to $170 billion. The international interbank lending market has grown rapidly too, reaching $5.8 trillion in June 1995.
<ul><font size=-1><li></font> According to the Bank for International Settlements (<font size=-1>BIS</font>), a sort of central bank for central banks, turnover in the foreign-exchange market, in which banks are the principal players, has reached an estimated $1.2 trillion a day, almost double the figure in 1989.
<p><font size=-1><li></font> Commercial banks are also heavily engaged in over-the-counter (<font size=-1>OTC</font>) derivatives (ie, those that are not traded on a recognised exchange). A survey of the market published under the auspices of the <font size=-1>BIS</font> showed that at the end of March 1995 the total amount of outstanding <font size=-1>OTC</font> contracts had reached an eye-popping $41 trillion.
</ul><p>In short, banks are doing more business with one another. This proliferation of relationships, together with the large amounts of money that are riding on them, has made it even more important for banks to manage the risks involved. Fortunately, the very things that have created this state of affairs--faster computers, improved communications, innovative financial instruments--have also made it easier for them to do so. This is often overlooked in the debate on whether banks' role in the <font size=-1>OTC</font> derivatives business is a bomb waiting to go off (see <a href="ibsu3.html">page</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more worrying source of systemic risk, but one that gets much less public attention, are the world's payments and settlements systems. These are often taken for granted; yet banks put unimaginably large amounts of money at risk in them, albeit for short periods. If one of the big systems were to break down, it is not just banks that would be in serious trouble, but entire economies.
<br><hr><br>
<font size=-1>* "The Decline of Traditional Banking: Implications for Financial Stability and Regulatory Policy", by Franklin Edwards and Frederic Mishkin. <i>Economic Policy Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank of New York, July 1995.

</font><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
