</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Can't pay, won't pay</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib3.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<h1>Can't pay, won't pay</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Watch out for blockages in the financial plumbing</i>

<p>IT IS the stuff of which nightmares and movies are made. The scene is New York, late one Friday the 13th. Wall Street is in turmoil. The stockmarket is plunging. Suddenly a big bank announces that it needs help because trading losses have wiped out its capital. It refuses to settle up with the banks to which it has sent $10 billion-worth of payment instructions earlier in the day. This spells serious trouble for those banks, which have already paid the cash to their customers. So they, in turn, renege on settlements with other banks. Eventually, the entire banking system grinds to a halt. Chaos quickly spreads to the rest of the economy as companies discover they cannot make or receive payments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mercifully, this is fiction. But the threat is real because many of the world's wholesale payments and settlements systems--networks that allow banks to send large amounts of money to one another and settle foreign-exchange or securities deals--operate on the basis of "netting". This works as follows. In the course of a day, two banks, <font size=-1>A</font> and <font size=-1>B</font>, send thousands of payments instructions to each other, but no cash. The bank receiving an instruction simply credits its customers' accounts while the system keeps track of the two banks' net position. At the end of the day, if <font size=-1>A</font> owes <font size=-1>B</font> money, it settles by transferring the amount owing from its account at the central bank (if the payments system is a public one) or the clearing house (if it is privately run) to <font size=-1>B</font>'s account. If that payment cannot be made, then it may affect <font size=-1>B</font>'s ability to meet its settlement commitments to other banks, creating chaos and, just possibly, a string of defaults.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thanks to the growth in payments systems, netting now operates on a multilateral basis, involving many different banks. Tom Labrecque, the president of Chase Manhattan, an American bank that recently merged with Chemical Bank, reckons that the money passing through the world's payments and settlements networks each day now adds up to $6 trillion. The sheer size of the amounts at stake was also highlighted by recent figures from the <font size=-1>BIS</font>, which showed that in some countries the annual value just of interbank payments had more than doubled as a proportion of <font size=-1>GDP</font> since 1985 (see <a href="images/csu125.gif">chart</a>). Payments systems as a whole in America, Germany and Japan now turn over the equivalent of their annual <font size=-1>GDP</font> every few days.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time, the amounts that banks owe one another during the day has rocketed. The chart found <a href="images/csu131.gif">here</a> shows a combined figure for America's privately run Clearing House Interbank Payments System (<font size=-1>CHIPS</font>) and Fedwire, a system run by the Federal Reserve. These "daylight overdrafts" are sometimes larger than banks' capital bases. Trying to work out exactly who owes what to whom is tricky. At a recent conference on payments systems hosted by Goldman Sachs, an American investment bank, Gerald Corrigan, the chairman of the bank's international advisory council and a former president of New York's Fed, said that these systems "constitute an extraordinarily complex chain of financial flows and resulting credit interdependencies that I dare say nobody fully understands."
</p><p><b>Clear as mud</b>
<br>It is this opacity, coupled with the size of the credit exposures involved, that creates a potential systemic risk. Mr Corrigan fears that banks have become more defensive, and may refuse to meet their settlement commitments at the first sign of trouble. A senior executive of one big European bank agrees. As he delicately puts it, if an important link in a payments system were to break, "it would be every man for himself and screw the rest of you." But what if a troubled bank simply delayed settlement for, say, a day rather than refusing to pay outright? That way the other banks would eventually get their money. But they would still have to raise money to bridge the gap, perhaps by selling assets. If they could not do so fast enough, they might need help.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To start tackling these risks, some central banks have assumed a more active role in payments systems. In Fedwire's case, the Federal Reserve guarantees payment "finality", meaning that transactions will not be unwound if a bank fails to settle. The central bank will pick up the tab if a bank defaults. Private-sector systems, such as <font size=-1>CHIPS</font> and Britain's Clearing House Automated Payments System, have imposed limits on their members' overall indebtedness to one another. <font size=-1>CHIPS</font> and Japan's private-sector payments system have also introduced loss-sharing arrangements, so that one bank's failure will not stop others from settling.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A number of countries, mostly in Europe, have gone for another approach: real-time gross settlement (<font size=-1>RTGS</font>). This involves banks settling their large payments with one another immediately, assuming their accounts with the central bank have enough money in them. This should dramatically reduce systemic risk because if a bank fails, it will owe little to others. The difficulty with <font size=-1>RTGS</font> is to ensure that enough credit is available to smooth payment flows, but without making it so cheap that it encourages banks to take big risks. Some <font size=-1>RTGS</font> systems, such as the Bank of Japan's, forbid daylight overdrafts; instead, banks have to raise loans from an interbank market. Others, such as those in Britain and the Netherlands, require banks to provide liquid assets as collateral before their settlement accounts can be overdrawn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Progress has also been made in reducing systemic risk in other areas. One is securities settlement, where there is often a lag of several days between, say, the delivery of a share and payment for it. This is gradually being reduced (for equities in America, from five business days to three last year) and may eventually disappear. <font size=-1>RTGS</font> also helps here by ensuring that, once it has been made, a payment for a security is irrevocable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for derivatives, those traded on exchanges pose less of a problem because multilateral netting keeps settlement flows small, members are required to put up collateral ("margin") against their positions and these positions are subject to limits. Some <font size=-1>OTC</font> contracts also include margin arrangements, though it is difficult to say how widespread this practice is. This has prompted some people to recommend that the clearing-house concept should be extended to the <font size=-1>OTC</font> market, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some regulators fear that the international links that derivatives create could complicate settlement problems if a bank defaults. But again, this risk is not new. And because netting arrangements mean that the amounts involved are small, a glitch here is less worrying than in some other areas. Indeed, by far the biggest settlement threat looms in the foreign-exchange market, where bankers still quake in their boots at the mention of "Herstatt risk"--the danger that a bank, having fulfilled its side of a foreign-exchange trade by delivering currency, suddenly discovers that its counterparty has not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1974 Bankhaus Herstatt, a medium-sized German bank, was closed down by the German authorities. Herstatt had been in the middle of over $620m-worth of foreign-exchange trades, and had received <font size=-1>D</font>-marks from a number of American and other banks. But it was shut before New York's settlements system had opened, and so did not transfer dollars in return. This caused a panic in America, where banks that had sent money to Herstatt refused to make other payments on their, or their customers', behalf. <font size=-1>CHIPS</font> wobbled, but fortunately did not go down.
</p><p><b>Keep going round the clock</b></b>
<br>Since then, Herstatt risk has been reduced by measures such as extending the opening hours of national settlements systems to reduce the troublesome gap (next year, for example, Fedwire will stay open an extra six hours). But more needs to be done. Last month, a hard-hitting report from a <font size=-1>BIS</font> committee headed by William McDonough, the New York Fed's boss, said that settlement risk in foreign exchange can sometimes stretch out over more than three days, and berated banks for failing to measure and manage their exposures properly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bankers finally seem to be getting the message that something needs to be done to tackle this problem. Shortly before the <font size=-1>BIS</font> report appeared, a group of the world's biggest banks, dubbed the <font size=-1>G-20</font> (even though there are only 17 members; who said bankers could count?), announced plans to create a 24-hour organisation for foreign-exchange settlements within the next few years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fact that the world's payments and settlements systems have proved reasonably solid over the past 20 years partly reflects improved risk management. But there have been several close shaves. In November 1985, for instance, the New York Fed lent $23 billion to the Bank of New York--more than 20 times the bank's capital--after a computer glitch caused it accidentally to run up a daylight overdraft of almost $30 billion. The Fed also had to step in after the 1987 stockmarket crash to encourage commercial banks to keep lending to securities houses which were supporting troubled customers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Small wonder, then, that central banks take a great interest in the design and development of payments systems. They are worried that, left to their own devices, banks might not develop real-time systems, which are safer than netting but more expensive. But should central banks run as well as oversee payments and settlements systems? After all, there is no shortage of initiatives from the private sector, such as <font size=-1>CHIPS</font> and the proposed global clearing house for foreign-exchange deals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Central bankers argue that close involvement on their part creates confidence and therefore reduces the chance of a systemic crisis. But it also creates a significant moral hazard. Safe in the knowledge that the central bank will provide finality and a safety net, banks could become slapdash about managing credit and liquidity risks, thus making daylight overdrafts soar and increasing the likely cost of bailouts. This has already happened on Fedwire. To tackle the problem, the New York Fed has recently begun to charge fees for daylight overdrafts and to require collateral from banks that regularly run up large credit positions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tougher rules are probably justified, but the Fed is worried that these may cause banks to decamp to rival systems. This is just one example of how government action can inadvertently increase systemic risk. A much more worrying case of this kind of regulatory failure is the perverse effect of deposit insurance and banking bailouts.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ibsu5.html">Next article</a>
</p>
