<html><head><title>Trouble in Tokyo</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib5.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Trouble in Tokyo</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Moral hazard has played a part in Japan's banking disaster, too</i>

<p>WHEN, in December 1995, America wound up its Resolution Trust Corporation, the body set up to dispose of the bad assets of savings and loan associations, it closed the book at last on an awkward episode in its financial history. Most European countries have also put their banking crises behind them. But Japan's refuses to go away. Among the culprits being blamed for the mess are hapless bankers, greedy property developers and even the <i>yakuza</i> (Japanese gangsters), who apparently built up property businesses with cheap credit from banks. But, in some ways, the real villains of the piece are bank regulators.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japanese banks' problems are especially worrying because bank finance plays a crucial role in the country's economy. At the end of 1995, total bank credit as a proportion of nominal <font size=-1>GNP</font> in Japan was 105% compared with just 37% in America, where domestic capital markets are much bigger. So if several of Japan's big banks were to collapse, the resulting credit crunch might devastate Japan's economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japanese officials have been hard at work trying to prevent anything of the sort. When the depositors of Cosmo, the country's fifth-largest credit union, began a run on it last July, the Bank of Japan stepped in with emergency loans--the first time it had done so since 1965, when it bailed out Yamaichi, a stockbroker. More recently, the government has been trying to push a &#165;685 billion ($6.3 billion) rescue package for seven all-but-bankrupt <i>jusen</i>, or mortgage lenders, through parliament against bitter political opposition. Even if the package gets through, the <i>jusen </i>are the tip of the iceberg. On some estimates, their bad debts are no more than a tenth of the banking system's as a whole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japan got into a mess in much the same way as did several European countries that suffered banking crises in the early 1990s. Like European banks, Japanese ones faced a profit squeeze in the 1980s as interest rates on deposits were progressively deregulated. By 1990 the proportion of deposits paying market rates of interest at Japan's city (or commercial) banks had risen to 70%, from only 22% in 1985. To compensate, banks lent aggressively to the property sector, either directly or indirectly via non-banks, many of which were big property lenders too (see <a href="images/csu149.gif">chart</a>). When the property market crashed, they were left with huge bad debts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What made Japan's headache even worse was that its big banks had invested especially heavily in equities during the stockmarket bubble. This created what Andrew Smithers, an economic consultant, calls "a doomsday machine". Under the Basle capital-adequacy rules, Japan's banks are allowed to count up to 45% of the unrealised gains on their equity holdings towards "tier-two" capital. That is fine if the market is rising, but dangerous if it is falling sharply. Last year some analysts predicted that if the Nikkei stockmarket average slipped below 13,000, the aggregate Basle ratio for the country's biggest banks would fall below the 8% minimum. Thanks to various official efforts to prop up the Japanese stockmarket, the Nikkei only fell to 14,485 before it began climbing again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; How did Japanese banks get into such trouble? Not because of deposit insurance, which in America has generally been blamed for encouraging banks' follies. The Deposit Insurance Corporation (<font size=-1>DIC</font>), Japan's version of America's Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, is puny by comparison. It covers deposits up to a limit of &#165;10m, but exhausted its meagre resources by helping to arrange the mergers of a few small troubled banks last year.
</p><p><b>Blame the bureaucrats</b>
<br>One important culprit is the country's finance ministry, which supervises the banking industry. Until the 1970s, it ran what became known as the "convoy system", under which banks were all expected to steam in the same direction and at the same rate of knots. The ministry's officials more or less took the helm, telling banks what they should and should not do. No wonder bankers did not bother assessing risk. When some banks ran into trouble, officials persuaded healthier ones to bail them out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But now the ministry is finding it increasingly hard to persuade Japanese banks to come to one another's aid. Rei Masunaga, the deputy president of the Japan Centre for International Finance, a research institute, says that even relatively healthy banks have some bad debts, so they are less keen to stump up cash for others. This harder-nosed attitude has been obvious in the debate over who pays for rescuing the <i>jusen</i>. These were originally founded by the big banks, which have refused to foot almost all of the bill for a rescue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the mandarins have been guilty of forbearance, it may be partly because they have had difficulty in finding buyers for troubled institutions. A preliminary report by an advisory committee, appointed by the finance ministry to look into the causes of the crisis, concluded last September that some financial institutions had been allowed to stay in business "even though [their] financial condition had worsened practically to the point of failure... Consequently, disposal costs tended to be larger." A good example of this is Kizu, an Osaka credit union. In 1994 regulators found a &#165;600 billion hole in its balance sheet, but still allowed it to stay open. When it eventually closed in August 1995, the loss had risen to &#165;960 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The regulators were also slow to tackle the problems at many of the <i>jusen</i>. Cynics ask whether this might have had something to do with the large number of former finance-ministry officials who hold senior jobs at these institutions. Whatever the truth, the common practice (known as <i>amakudari</i>, or "descent from heaven") of bureaucrats moving to posts at banks they used to supervise has created the impression, as one foreign consultant puts it, that these people are simply "regulating their pre-retirement income".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The finance ministry has also been reluctant to force the banks to own up to the full extent of their bad loans. Better information matters because if creditors and depositors cannot distinguish between good and bad banks, in the event of a failure they are more likely to cause a run on all of them. Indeed, the ministry's own uncertainty about the true size of the banks' bad-debt problem--put at &#165;40 trillion in June 1995 and &#165;50 trillion only a month later--helped unnerve the market last year. David Atkinson, an analyst at Goldman Sachs, an American investment bank, argues that until banks are forced to own up to and realise all of their bad loans, and then refinance borrowers, the country's property market is likely to remain moribund.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For now, though, the ministry seems to be hoping that a combination of low interest rates and tax breaks will be enough to tide most institutions over. Belatedly, it has also allowed some banks to go bust. Until last year, not a single Japanese bank had failed since the second world war. Since then, several small ones have gone under, including Taiheiyo Bank, which collapsed last month. But depositors should not have to worry. Officials have promised that they will not let any of Japan's 21 big banks fail, and that deposits at smaller ones will be protected until the end of the decade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And what then? The finance ministry says it intends to get tougher with its charges. At the end of last year it announced a series of reforms which included beefing up the deposit-insurance fund, hiring more examiners and creating an early-warning system to alert regulators to trouble. Bankers seem unworried by this prospect: there is still no formal commitment to banking burials, and the reforms do not include any proposals to improve financial disclosure. That is a pity, because regulators in other countries increasingly feel that the only effective way to supervise complicated beasts such as banks is to harness market forces to the task.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
