<html><head><title>A novel bank statement</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><!img src="../images/ibsu.gif"  alt="Sp Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>A novel bank statement</h1>


<br><p>WOULD a bigger role for market forces in disciplining banks make the system more stable? Many financial economists are convinced that the answer is yes, but they have no recent empirical evidence to support their view. That is about to change.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until the start of this year, New Zealand, which has no deposit-insurance scheme, relied on a system of bank examinations to ensure financial stability. That system has now been scrapped. Instead, every bank must produce a comprehensive quarterly financial statement for the country's central bank, listing items such as the quality of its assets, the sectors it has lent to and its ratings from private credit-rating agencies. A bank's statements must be audited twice yearly, and a two-page summary must be posted in all of its branches. The first statements, for the year to end-March, should appear soon.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is not all. Under the new regime, bank directors will have to validate these reports and state publicly that their bank's risk-management system is suitable for its business and that it is being properly implemented. If a bank subsequently goes bust because of a lapse of control, woe betide its directors: creditors can sue them and they may face unlimited liability.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The aim of the reform, says Don Brash, New Zealand's central-bank governor, is to improve banks' internal governance. It will also give investors and depositors more detailed and timely information on the banks' financial health. The banks, for their part, will escape the central bank's rules on internal control systems and its examination fees. They will, however, still have to meet the Basle capital-adequacy ratios, and will be promptly dealt with if they fail to do so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New Zealand's approach to disclosure is anathema to regulators almost everywhere else. Some argue that the country was able to choose this route only because around 90% of the assets in its banking system belong to subsidiaries of foreign banks, which are in effect supervised by their home countries' regulators. Mr Brash insists that the reason for the central bank's decision to switch arose purely from its conviction that the traditional approach to regulation was flawed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other central banks point out several problems with New Zealand's experiment. One is that unlimited liability might discourage good people from taking up directors' posts. Another is that, in some circumstances, too much information can be as dangerous as too little. For example, if a big investment made by a bank suddenly turns sour, the bank's depositors might panic when they see the red figures. Moreover, say the critics, banks will be more willing to own up to difficulties if they know the information will be kept private. The role of father confessor allows regulators to solve potentially serious problems behind closed doors. In short, the market's ignorance is sometimes bliss.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of these arguments is conclusive. If a bank knows that it will have to come clean about its finances every quarter, it is less likely to take a risk that could sink it. Besides, the new regime gives banks a big incentive to build up their financial strength to impress credit-rating agencies. "Banks will be competing for deposits not just on [interest] rates but on ratings," says Mr Brash. As for central banks' ability to keep information under wraps, this has no doubt helped all concerned out of some tight spots; but, as this survey has shown, it may also have led to costly forbearance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is another problem, too. The secrecy of bank examinations encourages the belief that the government is somehow in league with the industry, and is therefore to blame when it allows a bank to fail. This puts pressure on regulators to prop banks up. One reason for New Zealand's change of approach is that the central bank wants to dispel the notion that individual banks carry a public guarantee. Its experiment may not be perfect, but it is worth watching.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
