</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Private ideas for public policy</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib7.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Private ideas for public policy</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>A different insurance policy would produce a very different type of bank</i>

<p>IS THERE a better way of tackling moral hazard and reducing systemic risk than the insure-and-regulate approach to banking? A number of academics and consultants, mostly in America, have envisaged various ways of bringing about a largely unregulated and uninsured banking system, all of which share a common theme: to make explicit the cost of the subsidy that deposit insurance provides and to pass it on to banks and/or their customers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most extreme suggestion now being debated is to privatise deposit insurance and bank regulation altogether. This would force banks to pay a market rate for their insurance coverage and encourage insurance firms to stop the banks from taking excessive risks. But there is a snag: the thought of underwriting banks' deposits fills most insurers with horror. They prefer their risks to be predictable, a quality which bank runs by their nature do not possess. And when a run happens, the cost can be steep--so steep that it can bankrupt insurers, leaving governments to pick up the bill. America's experience has confirmed the worst fears. During the thrift crisis, the state authorities in Maryland and Ohio had to step in to help depositors left in limbo by bust quasi-private insurance funds covering the <font size=-1>S&L</font> industry.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Might another version of private insurance work? Bert Ely, a banking consultant in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>, has long championed an intriguing plan under which banks would in effect underwrite one another's risks via a system of "cross-guarantees". Before a bank could set up shop, it would have to persuade a syndicate of guarantors (largely other banks) to underwrite all of its liabilities. If the bank subsequently went bust, the guarantors would cover all liabilities left after its equity had been wiped out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition to charging a premium for the guarantee, the guarantors would also draw up a contract with the bank laying down operating guidelines; and they would appoint a specialised supervisor, or "syndicate agent", to enforce it. The result would be a complex web of interlocking contracts binding the industry together. A small government agency would ensure that all guarantors were themselves guaranteed and that their contracts met certain minimum standards (see <a href="images/csu088.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main attraction of this plan is that, by removing deposit insurance, it cures the moral-hazard problem. At the same time, it encourages banks to police one another and gives syndicate agents an incentive to watch them like hawks; an agent responsible for supervising a bank that goes bust is unlikely to get more business. Moreover, banks could tailor their contracts with guarantors to fit their strategy--a big advance on the present system of regulation, which tends to have one set of rules for everybody. Given the resources of big American and European banks, Mr Ely reckons that cross-guarantee systems in both regions would be able to withstand all but the most epic shocks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this sounds fine in theory. But in practice, switching to such a system would be a huge gamble. Some of the plan's critics argue that by connecting banks even more tightly together, it would increase systemic risk. Under the scheme's rules, banks are supposed to pay first and complain later if problems do crop up. But what if they refuse to cover a loss? And if the government was still involved in the system via the cross-guarantee agency, would it not have trouble convincing people that it had abandoned its role as a backstop altogether?
</p><p><b>Narrow-minded</b></b>
<br>According to another school of thought on banking reform, the state safety net should not be abolished altogether but merely shrunk. This would be done by splitting today's risk-loving, accident-prone banks into two disparate halves: a super-safe, government-insured "narrow bank" that sticks to traditional business and invests only in secure assets, and an uninsured institution--call it a "broad bank"--that could range more widely under a much lighter regulatory system. Savers who invested in the broad bank would get a much higher return because it could invest in riskier assets; but they would also lose their shirts if it went bust. Narrow banks could be owned by broad ones (or indeed any other kind of institution), but a series of legal barriers, or "firewalls", would prevent broad banks from dipping into narrow banks' coffers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All banking boffins agree that narrow banks could not get involved in risky activities such as property lending, securities underwriting and derivatives, but they differ on details. For instance, Lowell Bryan of McKinsey, a management consultancy, has proposed a system under which narrow banks (or "core" banks, as he likes to call them) could lend to individuals as well as to small and medium-sized businesses, on the ground that such loans are relatively safe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This bothers other narrow-bankers, who consider such illiquid loans too risky for an institution intended as a safe haven. Moreover, they say, the point of narrow banking is to isolate and insure only the unique and critical functions that banks perform. Lending does not qualify because many other kinds of institutions, such as insurers and credit-card companies, also make loans. So what does fit the bill? James Pierce, a professor at the University of California at Berkeley, has suggested that "monetary service companies"--his label for narrow banks--should provide only basic payments services and accept deposits, and that their investments should be limited to highly liquid assets, such as Treasury bills.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such narrowness appears to offer a neat solution to several of the problems identified earlier in this survey. It reduces systemic risk in the payments system by allowing only highly liquid banks access to it (others must channel payments through these banks). It tackles moral hazard by limiting deposit-insurance coverage. And it lightens the regulatory load on broad banks, making it easier for them to compete with loosely regulated non-bank rivals. A national commission looking into the effects of the thrifts crisis in America in 1993 was so impressed that it included narrow banking as one of its recommendations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics, however, point out that the system has costs as well as benefits. One is that it prevents broad banks getting information about depositors that would help guide their lending decisions. Another is that even a narrow bank will not be entirely safe because other institutions using it to make payments could run up daylight overdrafts and then go bust before settling them. To tackle the first problem, Frederick Carns, an economist at the <font size=-1>FDIC</font>, has suggested that rather than splitting banks in two, they should instead be allowed to offer savers a choice between "insured" and "uninsured" accounts. The second objection could be met by introducing real-time gross settlement for payments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more serious criticism of narrow banking is that, in certain circumstances, it could lead to more runs on banks. In good times, everyone would want to invest in broad banks; but during bad ones, cash would flood into safe narrow banks, perhaps forcing broad ones to call in some of their loans. Of course, money-laden narrow banks could help channel money back to solvent broad banks by buying their securities. But this might not be enough, and if governments then bailed out some broad banks to avoid a credit crunch, this would undermine the whole point of narrow banking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To avoid this problem, some economists have turned to another banking model, originally thought up in the 1930s by a group of Chicago economists as an alternative to deposit insurance. Instead of breaking banks up, this would force them to back any deposits they hold with an equivalent amount of Treasury bills and other safe assets. In a recent book*, Robert Merton and Zvi Bodie of Harvard University argue that this would not only produce a sound payments system and protect any synergies between deposit-taking and lending, but also force banks to fund their loans by, say, issuing securities rather than relying on deposits. But this approach, too, has its critics, who argue that the banks it would create would be unable to make a profit. Customers, they claim, might even have to pay to deposit their cash with them. The banking system would shrink dramatically.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Without a crystal ball, it is impossible to say for certain what economic and social impact narrow-banking models would have. However, there are good grounds for thinking that they would create more stable banking systems. Most regulators, however, remain sceptical about narrow banking's practicality. Instead, they are concentrating their efforts on creating common international standards of financial safety. That is easier said than done.


<br><hr><br>
<font size=-1>* "The Global Financial System". Harvard University Press, 1995.</font>


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ibsu10.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
