<html><head><title>Extinguishing banking's fires</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib9.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Extinguishing banking's fires</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Bad banks are usually the product of bad macroeconomic policy</i>


<p>EVEN Adam Smith fretted about systemic risk in banking. In his book, "The Wealth of Nations", he drew an analogy between the need of governments to violate the natural liberty of bankers by regulating them, and the need to make neighbours build party walls to stop fire from spreading through a community. Fortunately, since the Great Depression, the legal and other firewalls installed by governments throughout the world's banking systems have stopped all kinds of potential catastrophes from spreading. Somehow, though, that is less reassuring than it should be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a moment, put aside the methods used to tackle these financial conflagrations, and the side-effects that they have. The real point is this: whereas governments have managed to prevent systemic banking crises, they have singularly failed to tackle their underlying cause. This is not because of short-sightedness among bankers, but rather because of myopia among countries' economic policy-makers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This judgment may seem harsh. After all, there have been plenty of occasions--for example, after the 1987 stockmarket crash and during the recent property bust--when swift government action to pump liquidity into the financial system or to lower interest rates has helped to defuse a potential crisis. But in these and many other cases, governments have simply cleared up financial messes that were to a large extent of their own making. Much of the blame for this lies with the volatile monetary policies that caused the boom-and-bust cycles. It is no coincidence that the worst banking crises in recent years occurred in countries where interest rates rose sharply in the late 1980s. Nor is it a coincidence that banks in countries such as Germany and the Netherlands, both paragons of monetary stability, escaped the traumas of the early 1990s largely unscathed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, almost every financial catastrophe can be traced back to some failure or other of economic policy. There is a simple lesson in that. The greatest single contribution that any government can make to better banking is to create a stable macroeconomic environment in which banks can flourish. That means resisting the temptation to respond to sluggish growth by slashing interest rates and stimulating demand with all manner of tempting tax breaks. And it means ensuring that economies get richer gradually and boringly, rather than in a series of spectacular booms and busts.
</p><p><b>The $64 billion question</b></b>
<br>But do not pin too much hope on these things happening. The governments of rich countries may profess to have learnt the lessons of the most recent banking crisis, but a glance at the financial history books shows they have often made such claims in the past and failed to live up to them. Rather than concentrating on fire prevention, they will continue to reach for the extinguishers every time that banks go up in flames.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a strategy, as this survey has shown, simply stores up more costly problems for the future by aggravating moral hazard. Some economists have argued that even though safety nets may have led to excessive risk-taking and wasteful investments by banks, this is a small price to pay for preventing a systemic crisis. Perhaps. But unless the present system is changed, the cost of the safety net is likely to rise inexorably. For one thing, the wave of mega-mergers that is sweeping the industry--including those between Chase Manhattan and Chemical Bank in America and between Mitsubishi Bank and the Bank of Tokyo in Japan--is creating ever bigger banks that in the event of failure would cost more to rescue. Moreover, as banks' traditional franchise is invaded by competitors, they are rapidly moving into ever riskier businesses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What can be done to solve the problem of moral hazard? Trying to return banking to its original, heavily regulated state would be a mistake, even if it were possible, which is doubtful because the industry has changed so much. As well as destroying the economic benefits that liberalisation has brought, a <font size=-1>U</font>-turn would reinforce the impression that governments are there to ensure that banks do not go bust. A move to a system of private insurance also seems impractical, although some elements of this could complement government schemes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, what is needed is a mechanism which would make it possible for most, if not all, banks to fail without causing a systemic crisis, and which would inflict heavy penalties on those that are bailed out as a deterrent to others. Making bail-outs unpleasant is relatively easy. Even if central bankers break Bagehot's rules by lending to troubled banks at subsidised rates, they can still ensure that the banks' shareholders are wiped out and that their managers are replaced, no matter what the size of the institution. Even if some banks are too big to fail, none should be considered too big to suffer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Allowing bank failures without inviting systemic crisis is much more difficult. Domestic insured deposits are now only a tiny percentage of the liabilities of some of the world's biggest banks. In exchange for a lighter regulatory regime, some of them might be persuaded to relinquish their attachment to the safety net. But because they would still play a central role in payments systems, governments might feel duty-bound to support them if they got into trouble. Some form of narrow banking could resolve this dilemma by separating payments from the rest of a bank's activities. But it might take several more banking crises to convince governments that this is worth trying.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the meantime, they will continue to muddle along with the present insure-and-regulate system. This can certainly be improved by, among other things, more co-insurance, more disclosure, greater reliance on subordinated debt and a system of prompt corrective action that makes it harder for regulators to support ailing banks for no good reason. But even with all these improvements, the task of monitoring the far-flung activities of global banking giants seems beyond the wit of many supervisors--just as, it seems, it is beyond some of the managers of the banks themselves. The Barings and Daiwa cases hit the headlines, but many similar, though rather less costly, fiascos have been kept under wraps by embarrassed banks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One change is afoot, however, that is making it easier to let even big banks fail. As more and more countries' payments systems move towards real-time gross settlement, the chances of one collapse causing a domino effect is diminishing. With efforts now focused on exorcising the ghost of Bankhaus Herstatt in foreign exchange too, international banking is moving towards what one central banker has called "real-time everything". The vital but unglamorous job of fixing the world's financial plumbing will still take years to complete, but once it is done, many bankers who persist in leaping out of windows before looking will suddenly discover that there is nobody there to catch them.



