<html><head><title>Don't ban the bomb</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><h1 align=center>Don't ban the bomb</h1><CleverDrop>HAS the time come to get rid of nuclear weapons? For 50 years mankind has lived uncomfortably with the knowledge that Armageddon is no longer just a piece of biblical symbolism: the end of the world has been an achievable, man-made possibility. Moral outrage at this prospect lay at the heart of the old abolitionist cause, even if others exploited it for less noble ends. But the idea of the West giving up its nuclear arms never found majority support in the democracies as long as communists elsewhere were determined to hang on to theirs. Now the cold war is over, Soviet communism presents no threat, and the disarmers have been joined by some prominent ex-generals, statesmen and thinkers. No misty-eyed idealists or stooges they. They make serious arguments that deserve serious thought.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the new abolitionists see it, the risk that a nuclear weapon might go bang unexpectedly or fall into the wrong hands now outweighs whatever deterrent value these weapons may still possess. Moreover, as long as some countries have nuclear arms, others will want to acquire them. The solution is for the haves to join the have-nots: dump the bomb.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, the world has changed faster than government thinking about nuclear weapons. Attention is at last turning to getting rid of old weapons, rather than building new ones (see <a href="sf0805.html">page</a>), but the big powers still have enough bombs and missiles to make the post-Armageddon rubble bounce. America, Russia, Britain, France and China are frank about their nuclear arsenals. Israel, India and Pakistan are more coy. Plenty of other countries could go nuclear if they wanted to, and some would if they could.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of the ideas recently put forward by the Canberra Commission (an international body set up by the Australian government), and by a group of about 40 mostly American and Russian ex-military men, make sense: take all nuclear weapons off alert; store their warheads separately; make much deeper cuts than planned in nuclear arsenals; and include those of Britain, France and China in arms-cutting treaties. Along with an ever tighter clamp on nuclear skills and materials, such measures would reduce the dangers of accident, miscalculation and proliferation.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that would still be only a partial means to a different end: a less nuclear world, not a non-nuclear one. Though they recognise it would not be easy, both the Canberra group and the old soldiers want nuclear weapons abolished completely. But could it be done? And would a nuclear-free world be a safer place? If the answer to both questions is a pretty confident yes, then, with courage and foresight on the part of the nuclear powers, a non-nuclear era could indeed be in prospect. Unfortunately, the answer to neither question is as straightforward as the disarmers would like.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nuclear technology is old technology; it cannot be unlearned. The blueprint for a bomb could probably be discovered in any decent university library, or retrieved from the Internet. The engineering techniques can be tricky, though many countries could master them. The hardest part is producing enough of the right sort of uranium or plutonium to make the thing go bang. That is what prevented Saddam Hussein from adding nuclear weapons to his arsenal of nasties before he attacked Kuwait in 1990. North Korea's dabbling with plutonium alerted the world to its nuclear moonlighting. And Iran's attempts to get hold of uranium from Russia and others confirmed its nuclear ambitions.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if the world cannot unlearn the alchemy of the bomb, might it be persuaded to do without it? Such is the reasoning behind the Canberra Commission's case: that big-power disarmament could set off a beneficial chain reaction.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nuclear fission can be reversed by political will. Some countries that secretly had the bomb or were making one-- South Africa, Argentina, Brazil and others--have renounced nuclear weapons. Others that could have gone nuclear chose, or were persuaded, to forgo the pleasure (though usually in return for nuclear protection from America or Russia). The Canberra Commission argues that, in today's rather different world, if the big powers agreed to give up their nuclear status symbols, even Israel and others might agree to follow.<br><b><br></p><p><b>Man remains vile</b></b><br>Maybe. But probably not. Few countries have sought the bomb just because America and Russia had it. India, more status-conscious than most, exploded a nuclear device in 1974 mostly out of fear of a large, hostile, albeit by now also nuclear-armed, China right next door. Threatened already by India's superior strength in conventional weapons, Pakistan built the bomb because India did. Israel, its neighbours vowing to drive it into the sea, saw nuclear weapons as the great equaliser, should Doomsday dawn. To the governments concerned, nuclear bombs were simply the most ferocious weapon their technology could build. They still are.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, big-power disarmament would scarcely make the world a safer place. As North Korea and Iraq have shown, catching nuclear cheats is an uncertain business. Lining up enough international support to punish them is harder still, even when the would-be chastiser--usually America, for want of much help from China or Russia--is dealing from overwhelming nuclear strength. Had the big powers renounced nuclear weapons, would a Saddam with a bomb or two have been prepared to listen? America has plenty of other weapons with which to bomb Baghdad. But there is every reason to believe that it was America's nuclear arms that stopped Saddam using his chemical and biological ones (renounced, as it happens, by almost everyone else) in the Gulf war. America's nuclear support for South Korea would surely be an element in the calculations of North Korea should it ever in desperation turn on South Korea.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an imperfect world, nuclear weapons do still deter. Even without any more Saddams (a futile wish), there is still enough rivalry among the bigger powers--think of China's muscle-flexing in East Asia, or Russia's pushiness with its neighbours--to want some sort of mind-concentrating force, even if only a small one that is kept well in the background.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, however, the new abolitionists do raise an issue that should not be overlooked. Someday, possibly quite soon, the world will wake up to face a rogue regime or a bunch of terrorists with a nuclear bomb and the will to use it. Urgently needed are missile defences (ones that avoid setting off still greater nuclear rivalries--see <a href="sf0796.html">page</a>) to protect troops sent in to do the necessary dirty work. But needed most of all are the tightest possible controls over nuclear materials, earlier warning of cheating and then the will to do something about it. In a nuclear-knowing world, eternal vigilance, not a disarming gesture, is the best hope for keeping the peace.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?852339600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="sf0805.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
