<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>America feels good</h2>
<h5><a href="bw1.gif">(See chart)</a></h5>
<b>American consumer confidence</b> jumped in December, and for the year, paving the way for "a healthy economy during the first half of 1997", according to the Conference Board. That boost follows a spurt of 14.2% in sales of new homes in November, the fastest growth for four years. Consumers spent more, too, but not enough to raise worries about inflation.<p>
The <b>Dow Jones </b>industrial average fell back at the end of the year, leaving it 26% higher at the end of 1996 than at the start. But some European bourses made bigger gains: Frankfurt rose by 28%, Paris by 27% and London by 12%. For dollar investors, Hungary was the most profitable emerging market, rising by more than 130%.<p>
<h2>Sparking</h2>
The latest merger linked to the deregulation of America's electricity industry may end the woes of <b>Long Island Lighting Company. Brooklyn Union Gas</b> agreed to a $3 billion share swap with the larger utility. Lilco charges the country's highest electricity rates, largely because of a disastrous $5.3 billion investment in a nuclear-power plant that was never used. The combined firm will have revenues of $4.5 billion and 2.2m customers.<p>
The top managers at <b>CITIC Pacific</b>, China's investment conglomerate in Hong Kong, bought a 15.5% stake in their company from its state-owned parent for HK$10.9 billion ($1.4 billion), a handsome 24% discount. The chief beneficiary was Larry Yung, <font size=-1>CITIC</font> Pacific's chairman and the son of Rong Yiren, China's vice-president.<p>
<b>Apple Computer</b> won back its founder of 20 years ago, Steve Jobs, after announcing it was buying <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font> Software for $400m. Mr Jobs, who owns half of <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font>, says he will devote a smidgen of his time to his one-time baby. Apple's shares, though, continued to sag alarmingly as investors waited for word of what the computer firm proposed to do with <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font>.<p>
Both in value and in number, management <b>buy-outs and buy-ins </b>in Britain reached record levels in 1996, according to the Centre for Management Buy-Out Research. There were 619 deals, up a modest 7% from 1995, but the value of them, &#163;7.5 billion ($11.7 billion), was up a robust 39%, swollen by three big British Rail privatisations.<b>Mergers and acquisitions</b> in America rose to a record $658.8 billion in transactions announced in 1996, said Securities Data Co, up from $519 billion in 1995, itself a record. The most feverish activity was in telecoms, followed by utilities.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Marvel Entertainment Group</b>, a comic-book publisher, filed for chapter 11 protection from creditors. This is part of an elaborate battle for control of the company between two financiers: Ronald Perelman, who owns 80% of Marvel, and Carl Icahn, who heads a group of investors that owns some $900m of junk bonds issued by Mr Perelman that are secured against his Marvel shares. <p>
<b>Telmex</b> lost its half-century monopoly in Mexico as the government threw open the country's $7 billion telecoms market to competition. More than half a dozen competitors, including <font size=-1>AT&T</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font> and their local partners, are now poised to improve services, cut bills and increase long-distance traffic. <p>
Helped by "Twister", <b>Hollywood</b> had a record year. Box Office receipts in America increased by 8% to $5.86 billion as more people went to the cinema, reversing a recent decline. The biggest hit was Twentieth Century Fox's "Independence Day". It brought in gross box-office receipts of $733m at home and abroad, making it the third-biggest film ever (behind "Jurassic Park" and "The Lion King").<p>
<b>Circus Circus</b> is to build a 4,000-room resort casino in Las Vegas, its most ambitious, and most upmarket, endeavour so far. "Project Paradise" will have a tropical theme and will cost up to $1 billion to build.<p>
Shares in a big Dutch insurance group, <b>Aegon</b>, soared-- defying a fall in the rest of the Amsterdam market--after it announced plans to buy the insurance operations of America's <b>Providian</b> for $3.5 billion. The deal will allow Providian to concentrate on banking; Aegon will become a leading life assurer worldwide.<p>
<h2>(Not) in the air</h2>
 <p>
<b>Fokker</b>, a bankrupt Dutch aircraft maker, may have lost its last hope of rescue. The South Korean government confirmed that a consortium led by Samsung Aerospace would not be making a takeover bid.<p>
Some 1.35 billion people flew on domestic and international scheduled <b>flights </b>in 1996, a 4% rise on the previous year. The gain in 1995 had been 5%. The number of people flying internationally was particularly buoyant in 1996; up 8% for the second year running, to 404m. With 645 orders, Boeing had its best year since 1989. Airbus had 309 firm orders, its highest since 1990.<p>
China revealed proudly that some of its <b>prison labourers</b> are paid $31 a month--$6 more than the country's minimum wage. Separately, <b>Michael Ovitz</b> finally agreed his severance package from Disney: for 14 months work the former talent agent will receive $76m.<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
