<html><head><title>An adult affair</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="cybersex.gif"  alt=""><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><h1>An adult affair</h1><p><b>The main early use of many kinds of electronic communications is to let men watch and talk to naked women. It may, in the end, lead to better things</b></p><br>A CONFERENCE at London's plush Caf&eacute; Royal, last October. On the sixth floor, in two cavernous conference halls, a small but earnest collection of geared-up people discuss telecoms switching technology, billing systems and something called "international simple resale" before a small and scattered audience. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two floors down, the trade exhibition is humming. Pony-tailed young men demonstrate ground-breaking technology for reducing credit-card fraud on the Internet. Glamorous girls in skimpy skirts talk earnestly of turnover and call-minutes in booths emblazoned with the names of countries that nobody would readily associate with the leading edge of global communications: Sierra Leone, Moldova, Guyana. And Dan Guess, the burly chief executive of Virtual Dreams, presides happily over an admiring crowd experimenting with his videoconferencing equipment.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No ordinary videoconferencing. The young Dane who has taken over the keyboard at the computer is typing furiously. "Take off your . . . " He turns to a friend. "How you spell 'clothes'?" he asks. The friend obliges. On the computer screen, a lithe young woman with long brown hair begins, jerkily, to disrobe. "All the way from San Diego," says Mr Guess proudly. "And over an ordinary telephone line."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is an annual get-together of the world's audiotext industry. The transmission of information and entertainment on telephone lines and over the Internet is at the core of the communications revolution. A great deal of the material being communicated is what the trade describes as "adult entertainment": nobody, but nobody, calls it porn. (And, just for the record, all the companies named in this article insist they stay firmly within the bounds of what is legal.) Many of the main innovations in communications are tried out first--and, in a few cases, even developed--by the adult-entertainment business. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Videoconferencing on personal computers is merely the latest in a list of electronic technologies whose chief early colonisation is by the erotic. The cinema, the videocassette, France's Minitel system, the compact disc and pay-per-view television have all been used, in their early years, partly or mainly for adult entertainment. Some of them still are. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the late 1970s, when few American homes had videocassette players, more than 75% of all videocassettes sold were in this category. Since then, following a common trend, the percentage has fallen as the medium has acquired more conventional uses. Paul Fishbein, publisher of <i>Adult Video News</i>, a trade publication based in California, reckons that sales and rentals of adult video tapes through video stores were worth about $3.1 billion in 1995. Mail-order sales may have been worth another $1 billion or so. The business thus accounts for about 14% of rentals and sales by volume, he says. But, because adult tapes sell at a premium, the business probably accounts for rather under a quarter of the $16 billion revenues of the home video market. There is, Mr Fishbein complains, "a glut of products on the market. The profit margins are not what they once were."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Germany, too, adult fare accounts for the largest single chunk of the market for video rentals: 40% of a market worth about DM2.8 billion ($1.8 billion). The figures come from the trade association of erotic-video producers, which spends its time collecting royalties for its 190 or so specialist producers of adult films. <br></p><p><b><b>That's entertainment?</b></b><br>Adult entertainment is now a mainstay of pay-per-view television. In American hotels $150m-175m, or at least half of the revenues for pay-per-view films, usually comes from adult entertainment. Not surprisingly, as pay-per-view television in the United States has become available on cable and satellite channels, the two main companies in the business, Playboy and Spice Entertainment (which owns the Spice Networks), have rushed to take advantage of it. Between them, their four adult channels account for perhaps $200m of the $600m American market for pay-per-view television.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both have done well from the launch of direct-to-home digital satellite television in the United States two years ago. Now, both Playboy and Spice are bringing their television and film channels to more sex-starved parts of the globe: in late 1995 Playboy was launched into Latin America, and the Spice Networks have been moving into Asia. Within five to ten years, both of them think that at least half of their television revenues will come from abroad.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, both have big plans to make money from cybersex. At Spice, Roger Faherty, the chairman, believes that "if there is money in the on-line world, it will be in sex and sport." His company has launched Cyberspice, an "on-line peepshow". Tony Lynn, president of Playboy Entertainment, sees his company's Internet site, with 5m "hits" a day, as "potentially our most important revenue earner". The company is now experimenting with charging people to peek at a page.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Elsewhere, a cable channel is already using the Internet--legitimately--to avoid the irritations of regulation on television channels. In Britain, the Adam and Eve film channel has found it hard to win permission to broadcast throughout the day. Instead, the company is running its films of erotic cavorting around the clock on the Internet (at www.adamandevechannel.com, if you really must know). Ray Miller, the channel's chief executive, grumbles that it is hard to establish his tasteful offerings in the Internet's thickets of hardcore porn.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Larger companies, such as Spice and Playboy, face a similar dilemma. They aim to provide, as Mr Faherty of Spice puts it, "good taste within the genre". They are keen to offer value for money, because they recognise the need for repeat customers. "You can't throw garbage out there and expect people to pay for it," says Mr Faherty. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But they know good taste is not always the first concern of those who watch adult entertainment. Spice runs Eurotica, a more explicit cable service, in some European markets, and is exploring ways to launch a version in America. And on the Internet they will come head-to-head with competitors battle-hardened in an area where the ability to make good use of the latest electronic kit is the key to success. These are the veterans of the telephone sex industry.<br></p><p><b><b>A vision of the future</b></b><br>One such is Mr Guess of Virtual Dreams. "The two contents that drive technology are warfare and sex," he avers. "And sex generates the revenues." His company gets $700,000 a month in revenue from its "videoconferencing" service, which has been running for two and a half years. The service is, in fact, a one-way broadcast (the customer sees the girl, but not vice versa) with a two-way connection for typed messages or for a voice conversation. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The picture comes across an ordinary telephone line. The service hopes to show 12 frames a second to a viewer with a standard computer and a basic modem. That will be jerkier than a television broadcast, which shows 30 frames a second, but is still an astonishing testament to the powers of digital compression. "Like getting an elephant down a garden hose and reconstituting it at the other end," says Mr Guess--a little unkindly, considering that winsome figure in San Diego.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of the customers dialling Virtual Dreams' videoconferencing service, 75% are in the United States and the rest abroad. On January 1st the company launched an Internet-based service, which it expects will eventually be a far bigger business. It will be possible, for instance, to offer a broadcast with several hundred people watching the same live show. In time, the user will be able to control the camera from his home computer. It will also be possible to offer customers sites all over the world (eager viewers at morning sessions in the Caf&eacute; Royal had to wait for the girl in San Diego to finish her breakfast before she would perform). And customers outside the United States who use the telephone have to pay the high cost of an international telephone call. An Internet link cuts out that cost and opens the service to the world.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The service, in any case, does not come cheap. Customers pay $5.99 a minute, and stay on the line, on average, for 13 minutes, running up a bill of $78. The girl at the other end receives $25 an hour. At least some of the difference goes to finance the development of a technology that will ultimately change many activities apart from voyeurism. Medicine, education and a whole host of commercial and industrial transactions will eventually apply the technology now used almost exclusively for long-distance sex. <br></p><p><b><b>Hold the phone</b></b><br>"Telephone sex may be good for development." Who says? The International Telecommunication Union (<font size=-1>ITU</font>), the staid club of national telephone operators. While Virtual Dreams and its handful of competitors offer live colour video pictures of lightly dressed lasses (and lads, who are what one caller in five wants to watch), a larger and more established business sends live or recorded sex chat across an ordinary telephone line.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Customers may pay in one of two ways: through the cost of the call (in which case the bill appears on their ordinary telephone bill--or their employer's) or by credit card. To escape regulatory constraints, companies using the first method frequently run their services from faraway places with strange-sounding names, many of them penurious developing countries. Others use domestic premium-rate lines.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The industry reckons that 1.5% of all international traffic is telephone sex, with a global turnover of around $2 billion a year. The key to the business, explains the <font size=-1>ITU</font> (whose interest in it is purely academic), is a settlement system which ensures that the country in which an international call originates and the one in which it terminates share the revenue from the call.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This settlement system means that the public telephone operator (<font size=-1>PTO</font>) of a small developing country can benefit hugely if it can generate a large amount of incoming traffic. The <font size=-1>PTO</font> splits its share of settlement payments with the service provider, who drums up business and provides the girls. Often, the calls are routed back over a leased line (on which there are no settlement payments) to the country where the call began. The amorous fellow thus pays for an international call to talk to a woman who may be just a few miles away.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prize example is Guyana, a dirt-poor country in Latin America (<font size=-1>GDP</font> per head around $2,000 a year). Since the country's <font size=-1>PTO</font> was taken over in 1991 by <font size=-1>ANT</font>, an American company, it has increased its volume of incoming calls from 23.8m minutes to 139.7m in 1995, a compound annual growth rate of 56%. As a result, its yearly revenue from telecommunications services is now around $130m, or the equivalent of 40% of the country's 1993 <font size=-1>GDP</font>, or--to put it another way--$700 per household. Not all the revenue stays in the country, but with the money that does the <font size=-1>PTO</font> has been building one of the region's finest telephone networks. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ITU</font> points to a couple of even more extraordinary instances. Niue, a New Zealand protectorate in the South Pacific, handles many calls from Japan, one of the fastest growing markets for telephone sex. The island has more lines than inhabitants. Some of the lines are connected to answering machines rather than human operators. Others are routed back to a call centre in Toronto which is manned by operators who can speak English, French, Spanish, Greek, Italian and Swedish. Like many other countries in the business, one of Niue's selling points is that the tiny size of its population guarantees short telephone numbers. Dial the international access code of 683, and another four numbers will connect you to your heart's desire. It would be easy for the naive or ignorant to imagine they were making a local call.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dutch Antilles, in 1994, was receiving the equivalent of 2,600 incoming minutes of calls for every telephone subscriber in the country and generating at least $1,000 a head from settlement payments. Since Germany alone accounted for 47% of its incoming minutes in 1994, the tiny country will have been badly hit by Deutsche Telekom's decision in 1995 to clamp down on international sex calls--part of an effort to clean up before privatisation.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Germany is a big loss: all told, it accounted for about a third of the 60m minutes a month of the world's international sex calls. After the German clampdown, the United States is now the biggest caller. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even with Germany knocked out, more poor countries are crowding into the chat trade. Should <font size=-1>PTO</font>s be in this business at all? Those in the developing countries are, says Stuart Sharrock, editor of <i>Voice+</i>, one of the main trade magazines, "quite open about it. They are often in a tough commercial situation, and this allows them to invest in equipment that allows all sorts of facilities for their domestic customers. Many of them are well-run organisations with slick operations and published accounts." And, because they split their takings with the service providers, they make less from the business than the telephone companies in the rich countries where the calls originate, which pocket the other half of the settlement payment.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The international business is run by perhaps five to ten companies worldwide. More are based in the Netherlands than anywhere else, but all move easily between countries. Delegates at the Caf&eacute; Royal perked up when Sean Taylor, from Redwood Technologies, spoke of the work his company had put into developing telephone equipment that could work in any country, and be used equally for international and domestic calls. That sort of flexibility will be useful to many businesses, but is perfect for the adult market.<br></p><p><b><b>The puritan counter-attack</b></b><br>For it is, not surprisingly, a trade that has to keep one step ahead of the regulators. That is even more the case for the domestic premium-rate business. Premium-rate services allow telephone companies to charge callers a higher rate than the normal telephone tariff for dialling certain services. When premium-rate services were first introduced, in the 1980s, many of them were sex-chat lines.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gradually, national regulators have clamped down on many of them. Richard Cadman, author of a recent study of premium-rate services in Europe for Eurodata, a telecommunications consultancy based in London, reckons that adult services are 25% of the premium-rate market in Switzerland, 14% in Finland, but hard to measure anywhere else. A growing number of countries have banned or restricted the services or advertising for them. In Britain, where 70% to 80% of all premium-rate calls were to adult services when premium rates were launched in the late 1980s, the proportion is now down to less than 1%, according to the Independent Committee for the Supervision of Standards of Telephone Information Services. Why? British Telecom and Vodafone required would-be customers to register for a special identification number and prove that they are over 18. That, not surprisingly, scuppered the market.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1995 the industry in Britain sought a way to revive it: by setting up closed user groups, telephone networks used by businesses such as travel agents or hotels to link their branches together. Connected to such a network by clever software, a customer can take part in a live conference call. Today, the conference agenda may be smut. But here, too, there is potential consolation for the moralists. In future, such a network could link a family or a group of housebound disabled people.<br></p><p><b><b>The problem with getting paid</b></b><br>In the United States, premium-rate sex calls have suffered from a different handicap: the difficulty of extracting payments. Telephone companies are obliged by law to tell customers at regular intervals that as long as they pay for the transmission of a sex-chat call, they do not need to pay for the content. As a result, the industry suffers from huge bad debts--perhaps 30-40% of all the business in the United States, say some.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is one of the reasons adult services have increasingly moved to charging their customers by credit card. There are other advantages: once they have persuaded a customer to divulge a credit-card number, some services make it hard to cancel. And, in many countries, the range of premium rates that telephone companies will charge is limited and the top band is low: only 13 tariff bands are available in Britain, ranging up to $2.30 a minute, says Eurodata's Mr Cadman, compared with 28 in Finland, ranging up to $4.75. Above all, credit-card calls have been less regulated than premium-rate calls: regulators have accepted that, since only adults are eligible for credit cards, the system offers some automatic protection for children.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, as the adult business suffers so much fraud, credit-card billing is not necessarily a protection. Banks often refuse to accept such business. Two years ago Richard Gordon, a Californian businessman, developed a system for detecting and preventing fraudulent credit-card calls. When, in response to a request by a chat-line, a customer punches a credit-card number into the telephone, Mr Gordon's system checks it against an elaborate database. If the number is approved, his company processes and clears the payment. He claims to have almost eliminated bad debts.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, more than half the company's new credit-card business arises not from the telephone but from the Internet. That brings problems. Credit-card fraud rates are high. Moreover, while companies taking calls from telephone customers in the United States can see the telephone number from which they are calling--and thus spot whether the call is from a number with a history of attempted frauds--an Internet connection provides no such protection. So Mr Gordon's company is developing a system of electronic "finger-printing" to recognise a particular computer.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a system will, in time, be used not only for adult entertainment but for all the other services traded on the Internet. It is already being used by some companies selling software on-line. Software distributed that way, says Mr Gordon, shares a key characteristic with adult entertainment: there is no "deferred delivery". By the time the trader has found out that credit-card details are fraudulent, the customer has already received (and, in the case of porn, consumed) the product.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Guesses about what proportion of Internet trade is adult entertainment are bound to be vague. Forrester Research, a Boston-based consultancy that specialises in communications issues, reckons that adult services in 1996 accounted for about $50m-worth of business, or about 10% of all retailing on the Internet to customers in the United States (although that includes materials ordered on-line and then sent by post). That put adult business behind sales of computer products and travel. But the figure may well be too low. Mr Gordon reckons the market for telephone video-conferencing has been running at $1.5m a month recently; and that market is shifting rapidly to the Internet.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet has many advantages for the adult-entertainment trade. It is global; it is cheap to use over long distances; above all, it is hard to regulate. For a trader, though, it has drawbacks: customers are hard to trace, and intellectual piracy is rife. The adult-entertainment business, which has pioneered so many communications technologies, will find ways to solve these problems and will thus blaze a trail for more conventional businesses. To expect their gratitude, though, would be a mistake.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?852339600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="st4106.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
