<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Dec-1996 -->
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="polthisyear.gif" width="261" height="26" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>The great survivor</h2>
 <p>
<b>Boris Yeltsin</b> survived two challenges: a campaign for re-election and a heart-bypass operation. His security adviser, Alexander Lebed, made peace in Chechnya, and was then sacked.<p>
<b>NATO </b>agreed to start talks in 1997 about letting some East European countries join. Russia said it would discuss a charter to define its relations with the alliance. <font size=-1>NATO</font> troops kept the peace in <b>Bosnia</b>, and will remain until mid-1998.<p>
<b>Helmut Kohl </b>became Germany's longest-serving chancellor since Bismarck. Spain elected its first right-wing government since Franco; a left-leaning coalition won power in Italy. Both countries ran austerity budgets in preparation for a single currency, as did Germany and France, despite record unemployment. The European Union agreed on a <b>stability and growth pact</b> for countries that adopt a single currency in 1999.<p>
Necmettin Erbakan became Turkey's <b>first Islamist prime minister</b>.<p>
The European Union banned exports of <b>British beef</b> after scientists discovered a link between "mad-cow disease" and a new variant of <font size=-1>CJD</font>, a fatal human brain illness.<p>
Voters ousted <b>former communists</b> in Romania and Lithuania and elected reformist presidents in Bulgaria, Latvia and Estonia. Vaclav Klaus, the Czech Republic's pro-market prime minister, hung on to power. Alexander Lukashenka, Belarus's despotic president, tightened control.<p>
<h2>Peace broken?</h2>
<b>Binyamin Netanyahu</b>'s narrow win in Israel's election stopped the Arab-Israeli peace process. Before the election, bombs in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem killed 59 people. Israel attacked Hizbullah guerrillas in southern Lebanon, killing many civilians. Later in the year, over 70 people died in two days of Israeli-Palestinian clashes.<p>
<b>Carnage in Algeria </b>continued, as Islamist guerrillas battled the army, and both killed ordinary people. Voters approved a constitutional ban on parties based on religion.<p>
Iraq provoked <b>American missile strikes </b>by helping one group of Kurds against another. <p>
America moved 4,500 troops in <b>Saudi Arabia</b> to a new base after 19 servicemen were killed by a bomb in Dhahran. <p>
<b>Kofi Annan</b>, Ghanaian head of peacekeeping at the United Nations, will be the <font size=-1>UN</font>'s secretary-general after America vetoed another term for Boutros Boutros-Ghali.<p>
The civil wars in Rwanda and Burundi spilled over into <b>eastern Zaire</b>. Tutsi rebels established an enclave there, and 500,000 Hutu refugees went back to Rwanda.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
President Mandela inaugurated a new constitution for South Africa. Nigeria's General Sani Abacha permitted small steps towards a return to <b>democracy</b>. Somalia carried on fighting.<p>
<h2>A great comeback</h2>
<b>Bill Clinton</b> won a second term as president, the first Democrat to win two presidential elections since Franklin Roosevelt in 1936. Mr Clinton picked Madeleine Albright to replace Warren Christopher as secretary of state and William Cohen, a Republican, as defence secretary. The Whitewater investigations rumbled on.<p>
Mr Clinton ended the 61-year federal guarantee of <b>welfare payments</b>, replacing it with block grants to the states.<p>
The president signed the Helms-Burton law, allowing Americans to sue foreign investors in <b>Cuba</b>, but delayed its application, after protests from other countries. <p>
Latin America's move toward <b>market economics </b>stumbled on. Venezuela's ex-populist president bowed to the "Washington consensus". Ecuador's new populist president ate his campaign words even faster. Brazil saw some privatisations and congressional steps toward bigger ones. But in Mexico ruling-party activists rebelled against fresh sell-offs.<p>
Colombia endured an upsurge of killings by <b>guerrillas </b> and paramilitaries opposed to them. Peru's Shining Path and Tupac Amaru terrorists came vigorously to life again; Guatemala's agreed to peace. In Mexico a new left-wing armed movement emerged.<p>
<h2>Containing China</h2>
 <p>
East Asia saw its tensest <b>military confrontation</b> since the end of the cold war. China staged missile tests off Taiwan. America dispatched two aircraft carriers. Taiwan pressed on with its first democratic presidential election, which was won by Lee Teng-hui of the ruling Kuomintang. <p>
<b>Japan</b>'s Liberal Democratic Party staged a comeback. After three years ruling in coalition, the <font size=-1>LDP</font> did well enough in the election to form a government from its own ranks.<p>
An era ended in <b>South Korea</b> with the conviction of two of the country's former presidents on charges of corruption and treason.<p>
A corruption-tarnished Congress party lost power in <b>India</b>'s election. It was replaced by a United Front coalition of left-wing and regional parties, but Congress's economic reforms survived.<p>
For the second time, <b>Benazir Bhutto</b>, Pakistan's prime minister, was turned out of office by the president.<p>
China selected Tung Chee-hwa, a local businessman, to be<b> Hong Kong</b>'s first chief executive after it reverts to Chinese rule in July 1997.<p>
<b>Australians</b> elected a right-wing government. New Zealanders clipped their rightists' wings.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
