<html><head><title>Intuitively competitive</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The other technopolists</b></p>
<h1>Intuitively competitive</h1>

<p><b>Intuit owns most of the market for financial software. In the last of our series, we look at its prospects in the age of on-line financial services</b></p><br>
THE technopolists this series has covered so far have tended to concentrate on markets where the customers are all big, sophisticated firms. Consumer software is different. Products for home use tend to be cheap, consumers fickle and standards less important than in a networked office.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the home is exactly the market where Intuit rules. Thanks largely to a program called Quicken, the 13-year-old Californian firm has consistently held around 75% of the financial-software market, despite fierce competition from Microsoft. That dominance has helped its revenue grow fourfold in as many years, to $538m (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>) for the year that ended in July, although its aggressive acquisitions of other firms and investments in new business have often kept it in the red.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intuit's secret for winning, and keeping, its quasi-monopoly is simplicity itself. When Scott Cook founded Intuit and started selling Quicken in 1983, it faced 43 competing products, many of them highly sophisticated ones. Quicken, on the advice of Mr Cook's wife, distinguished itself by replicating on-screen a universally familiar device for paying bills: a plain chequebook. Since then the program has remained among the easiest to use, resolutely focused on the daily needs of ordinary people. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intuit is one of the few firms to have bested Microsoft. For more than five years the software giant has been pushing a competing program, Money, even giving it away at times, but has been unable to gain more than a quarter of the market. In April 1995 Microsoft even offered to buy Intuit in a generous $2 billion deal that included a promise to give away Money to another firm to maintain a semblance of competition in the market. But America's trustbusters were unconvinced. Faced with the prospect of a long and bruising court battle, Microsoft dropped the bid.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Having beaten off an all-out assault from Microsoft, Intuit has every right to walk tall, but its victory provides no guarantee of future success. The biggest challenge for the firm may not be its larger competitor but a changing marketplace. Over the next few years software of any sort will become less important than providing services on-line, such as letting people pay bills, manage their share portfolios and buy pension schemes over the Web.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Booz-Allen & Hamilton, a consultancy, reckons that nearly one in six American households will be banking over the Internet within four years. Most of these will be relatively well off, so between them they will make up nearly a third of bank profits by then. Such rich pickings have attracted many firms, including banks, to the emerging on-line financial-services market. In the face of this new competition, as well as that from Microsoft, can Intuit carry its dominance to this new market?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of Intuit's products connect to its Web-based Quicken Financial Network (<font size=-1>QFN</font>). Intuit acts as a middleman, offering information about mutual funds and insurance schemes, and introducing buyers and sellers. Some of these services are free, others require a monthly subscription. Intuit hopes to make its money from these subscriptions, as well as from advertisements on its site. And Intuit's Open Exchange, which connects Quicken users directly to their bank accounts, is used by 38 American banks, which pay the company a licence fee. Mr Cook reckons that within five years the Internet might account for as much as half of Intuit's revenues.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intuit's relations with the banking industry will be complicated. On the one hand it wants banks to use Open Exchange and support Quicken as part of their on-line banking services. On the other, it will be in head-to-head competition with them. More than 1,000 American banks will develop Web-based banking services within three years, according to Booz-Allen & Hamilton. These banks will find that <font size=-1>QFN</font>, rather than themselves, will rapidly become the point of contact between on-line customers and their financial institutions; and if the banks get their customers via <font size=-1>QFN</font>, they may have a hard time differentiating themselves from their rivals. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Intuit has two advantages over the banks. The first is that it can be seen to give impartial advice on current accounts, investments and pensions. The second is that its users are fiercely loyal. "People would change their bank rather than switch from Quicken," says Philippe Amouyal of the Boston Consulting Group.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile Microsoft has redoubled its efforts to promote Money, and linked it to a personal-finance Web site that is part of its Microsoft Network, the core of its ambitious push into media and other "content". Microsoft's Open Financial Connectivity, a direct rival to Intuit's Open Exchange (the word "open" means little, since both are proprietary networks), has brought in 61 institutional partners. Yet, ironically, Microsoft's attempt to buy Intuit boosted Open Exchange because it made the banks take the smaller firm more seriously. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Intuit, winning the battle for on-line financial services is a matter of survival, much more so than for either Microsoft or the banks, which have deep pockets to keep them going while they work out a new strategy. In a networked marketplace, standards count for more than they do in a home environment, and Intuit's standards are just one set of many. A commanding lead is a good place to start; but Intuit's greatest advantage may be that it is a lot hungrier than its rivals.<br>
<br>

