<html><head><title>Weird, perhaps, but quite wonderful too</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Dec-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="theearth.gif" alt="THE EARTH'S HIDDEN LIFE">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Weird, perhaps, but quite wonderful too</h1>

<p><b>Nothing left to discover on earth? Don't believe it. Wherever humans go, other creatures have beaten them to it; and pretty odd most of them are</b></p><br>
WHEREVER you look, life is there. Within the hair follicles of hamsters, and even of people, mites hatch, have sex and die. Inside the hearts and lungs of crocodiles, worms grow through adolescence and enter young adulthood, feasting on the rich blood of their hosts. Parasitic flies lay their eggs inside the bodies of fire ants; when the maggots hatch, they crawl into their host's head and devour the brains before they pupate. And this is just on the world's surface. Down in the bowels of the earth, curious bacteria flourish. Deep in the darkest oceans, fish with huge eyes and gigantic mouths patrol the gloom.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is nonsense to say that the Last Frontier has been crossed. Apart from the almost limitless expanses of space, where the physical cosmos may or may not blend into a non-physical one, there are plenty of places down here on humdrum old earth yet to be opened to human knowledge. Antarctica offers volcanoes, deserts, rivers and huge lakes deep beneath the ice. In more temperate climes, caves riddle the continents, offering amateurs the chance to discover places where no one has ever been before. And on the bottom of the ocean, fumaroles--"black smokers"--sear the rift valleys, spewing super-heated water and sulphuric gases from the globe's belly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of these places is hospitable to people. No one would plant a flag or build an empire there. But other organisms do not mind the dark, the heat, the cold, the poisons, or any of the other apparently dreadful conditions of these last untravelled reaches of the earth. Creatures thrive there; and they are weird.<br>
</p><p><b><b>A mere 3m years old</b></b><br>
In eastern Antarctica, the central ice sheet never melts, not even in midsummer. In the upper regions of the ice sheet, the temperature averages minus 50&#176;C. Yet four kilometres below the frozen surface lies Lake Vostok, a vast freshwater lake. According to the latest measurements*, it is in places 500 metres deep and covers 14,000 square kilometres (5,400 square miles), as much as Lake Ontario. Things move slowly down there. The average length of time a water molecule stays in the lake is about 50,000 years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lake Vostok could be a biological treasure trove. Ice samples taken from above the lake contain bacteria and other microbes such as algae, diatoms and other microfungi; the microfungi are possible sources of new antibiotics. As the gigantic lid of ice melts into the surface of the lake (something that occurs at the stately rate of about a millimetre a year), these organisms will be released into the water. At the point of their release, they will be 500,000 years older than they were when they first landed on the Antarctic ice-cap.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Work on Siberian permafrost by David Gilichinsky and his colleagues at the Russian Academy of Sciences in Pushchino shows that some bacteria can remain alive, if quiescent, for 3m years. Other microbes can certainly stay alive in ice for at least 180,000 years. No one knows the mechanics of such longevity. But one day, when sampling can be done without polluting the ice and the water, Lake Vostok could do for biologists what distant galaxies do for astronomers: it may allow them to look backwards through time, giving them a tiny window through which to explore an ancient world.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Antarctica is a good place for this. The cold is so searing that many organisms expend little energy. Indeed, the world champions of leisurely growth live in Antarctica. But these under-achieving organisms are not interesting only because of their excruciatingly slow pace of life. They have chosen an unlikely residence: they actually live inside rocks.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "endolithic" communities of Antarctica, as they are called, live where it seems impossible for anything to survive. In the dry valleys of eastern Antarctica, along the polar plateau, the cold, dry katabatic winds blow down from the central plateau at an average speed of about 70mph (110km per hour). They expose the quartz crystals of the sandstone rocks, keeping them free of snow. The year's average temperature (including the wind-chill factor) is minus 45&#176;C. Nothing, apparently, steps outdoors in this part of town. Yet the landscape is not so barren as you might suppose. Within some of the rocks, strange, layered communities of black lichens, white fungi and green algae have been living comfortably for centuries.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to David Wynn-Williams, a biologist with the British Antarctic Survey, rocks are quite cosy places to live in, once you can get inside them. Within, the temperature is hospitable (for Antarctica), hovering around 0&#176;C. They are even pleasantly humid; although no moisture lasts for more than a few minutes outside, droplets of water sometimes seep into the cracks and escape obliteration by the winds.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, even if an organism can get between the grains of the rock, another difficulty arises: food. The inside of a rock is, after all, dark. Or so it would seem. But to the algae, the basis of this quiet community, this is no problem. They are able to photosynthesise--harness the sun's energy to convert carbon dioxide from the air into the organic compounds needed for living-- with the little light that makes it through several millimetres of rock and two layers of other living organisms.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The black lichens are the first layer; then come the fungi; then, at last, the algae. The lichens live one millimetre under the rock's surface. They too photosynthesise; their black colouring comes from a pigment, melanin, which protects them from the ultraviolet rays of the sun. The stringy white fungi feed on the algae. And the algae are so efficient that they can get by with 180 times less light than most other plants. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides a little sunshine and a little water, these communities do not need much. One molecule of carbon dioxide captured from the air lasts them for 10,000 years before it is released again to the atmosphere. Yet, despite all this, the communities are relatively common in the translucent sandstone outcrops fringing the polar plateau. They may even occur on Mars. And they are probably centuries old. The key to long life, it seems, is not to do too much.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Groping in the dark</b></b><br>
A little light is, of course, different from none at all. In truly dark places, life seems impossible. Again, life surprises. Even in the blackest passages of the deepest caves, where the air is hot and foul, something is probably alive. Of all of earth's remaining frontiers, caves are perhaps the most accessible. New ones are discovered all the time, often by lucky amateurs. And, once in a while, a cave is found that has for ages been sealed off from contact with the earth's surface.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Movile Cave, underneath a cornfield in southern Romania just a few minutes' drive from the Black Sea, is one of these. Discovered by Cristian Lascu, a geologist at the Emile Racovita Speleological Institute in Bucharest, it was entered for the first time in 1986. Until then, it had been closed for more than 5.5m years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This cave has turned out to be stranger than most. Completely dark and virtually silent, it is home to a tremendous number of little animals. Part of it is quite dry; the rest is filled with warm waters (about 21&#176;C). The atmosphere is unpleasant: in parts, the cave is dangerously low in oxygen and poisonously high in carbon dioxide and hydrogen sulphide. And, most unusually, life in Movile Cave has no need of sunlight (or virtually no need--vital oxygen seeps in through cracks in the cave's walls).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For almost all organisms in almost all ecosystems, sunshine is the ultimate source of energy. Plants capture the sun's rays and, through photosynthesis, use the sun's energy to convert carbon dioxide in the air into organic molecules. Animals then feed on plants and on each other; fungi and bacteria grow on the living and dead tissues of plants and animals. If there is no light at all, life gets much more difficult.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, usually, caves do not hold much of interest. Bats sometimes roost; eyeless fish sometimes splash about in the water; the occasional spider sometimes startles an unsuspecting spelunker. But these beasties all depend indirectly on the sun. Bats fly abroad to collect their supper; the fish eat the detritus from dead things; spiders depend on straying insects that in turn depend on plants. Without some kind of regular food supply, a cave will be a desolate place, home only to small populations of just a handful of species.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence the oddity of Movile. So far, 48 definably different animal species have been found there, 30 on the land and 18 in the water. Of these, 33 are peculiar to this cave. Woodlice and millipedes graze on mats of bacteria and fungi; pseudoscorpions, centipedes and spiders gorge on the meat of whatever they can catch. In the water, leeches prey on worms; eyeless shrimps try to evade capture by water scorpions. No plants and no vertebrates (except for visiting scientists) are found there.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of the animals are troglomorphic: that is, they look as if they live in a cave. They have tiny eyes, or no eyes at all, and have often lost all colour. Their bodies are white or translucent; if you look at them with a torch, you can see their guts. They are true creepie-crawlies: they have extra-long legs and antennae (being crawled over by one of the millipedes would be, well, an experience) to feel and smell their way around. For cave biologists, Movile Cave may help to resolve an argument. One camp argues that the loss of eyes in cave animals happens because, when not much food is around, eyes become too expensive. The other argues that eye loss has nothing to do with the food supply. Movile--which is rich in food--suggests that the second camp may be right.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The water is the key to this diversity. It is "geological water"--it comes from a source far underground, not from the land above or the Black Sea. It could be 25,000 years old, and may have come, a long time ago, from the Danube. And it contains three substances that can provide energy to organisms which have evolved the equipment to take advantage of them: hydrogen sulphide, a gas that smells like rotten eggs; methane, a gas that (to humans) smells of nothing at all; and ammonium ions.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using one of these as their power supply, instead of using the sun, the bacteria in Movile Cave somehow (nobody yet quite knows how) convert carbon dioxide from the air into organic compounds. According to Serban Sarbu, a biologist at the Speleological Institute, and his colleagues Thomas Kane and Brian Kinkle, of the University of Cincinnati in Ohio, these bacteria underpin the whole ecosystem.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The upper passages of Movile Cave are like those in most caves: not much lives there. But down near the water's edge, about 200 metres below the cave's entrance, lots of animals scurry about (and occasionally one of the leeches comes out on to the bank). To get to the most interesting parts of Movile Cave, however, requires something more: cave diving. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For, although it becomes impossible to travel farther in the cave by foot, the cave continues in a series of underwater passages. Dive along one, and every so often it opens up into an "airbell"--a large pocket of air. And it is in these airbells that Movile Cave really comes alive, because it is within them that the food (huge mats of bacteria) is most abundant. Each of the three airbells investigated so far has a different atmosphere, the one farthest from the shore of the lake being the most toxic (to humans, that is). Each is inhabited by a bustling community; but the creatures that live in one airbell may not survive in the next. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Movile Cave is the first terrestrial (as opposed to aquatic) ecosystem to have been discovered that does not depend on sunshine. It will not be the last. The geological water that fuels the life in Movile extends over an area of more than 100 square kilometres. More airbells, complete with their denizens, probably live in this subterranean expanse. And networks of other, as yet undiscovered, caves in other parts of the world will probably turn out to be supplied with the energy to house even more creepy-crawlie critters in the dark.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Life under pressure</b></b><br>
Now plunge lower still. The darkest, deepest and most bizarre ecosystems of all are the deep oceans. Below the "photic zone", at depths where no light penetrates, the oceans are a surrealist desert. In the darkness, monstrous fish go for long stretches of time without food. On the ocean floor, organisms depend on falling detritus from dead creatures in the waters above. It is cold. And the pressure is immense.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Occasionally, though, the monotony of this desert is broken by equally surrealist oases. These are the deep-sea vents, known as black smokers, that belch out sulphidic water as hot as 400&#176;C. Over and around these vents live some of the wackiest creatures imaginable.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1977, deep-sea vents were discovered along a rift valley in the eastern Pacific, not far from the Galapagos islands. Since then, vents have been found scattered like islands in archipelagoes along the edges of the oceanic plates wherever the plates are spreading apart. The consequences of volcanic activity, these vents are springs of super-heated water. And, to the surprise of almost everybody, they have turned out to support ancient and complex ecosystems.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to Robert Vrijenhoek, of Rutgers University in New Jersey, exactly what you find living on a deep-sea vent depends on four things: which ocean you are in, how deep you are, how hot the water is, and how long the vent has been there.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the mid-Atlantic, the vents tend to last longer than the hotter, more ephemeral ones found in the eastern Pacific. On a vent four kilometres under the surface of the Atlantic, you might find bacteria with filamentous strands so enormous they can be seen by the unaided human eye (unaided, that is, except by a good submarine and a bright light), brilliantly-coloured mussels and clouds of small orange shrimps. The mid-Atlantic vents are often home to endemic species, suggesting that some of them have been stable for millions of years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the eastern Pacific, the shrimps are much less common; instead, gigantic tube-worms, sometimes two metres long and two or three centimetres in diameter, cluster around the mouth of the vent. Their protective tubes are white, and feel leathery. The worms themselves are purple, with bright red gills. Crabs without eyestalks prey on the worms, pulling them from their tubes like spaghetti. Also present in the eastern Pacific are mussels and clams up to 30 centimetres across. Here, the creatures have to move around because new vents erupt, ready to be colonised by the enterprising.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the western Pacific, the fauna is different again. Few worms and mussels cavort in the deep spas of these waters. Instead, hairy snails the size and colour of golf balls are stacked high around the edges of the vents. These snails do not often comb their hair; they are full of bacteria. And the shrimps of the western Pacific vents graze directly on the bacteria living among the snails' tousled manes.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several things are notable about the communities living on these vents. First, like the organisms in Movile Cave, none of them seems to depend on light. The bacteria are able to use hydrogen sulphide, or other sulphurous gases that are belched from the belly of the earth, as a source of energy. But, unlike the Movile residents, some of the other vent organisms do not depend on free-living bacteria for food.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The clams, mussels, snails and worms all have special links with their own species of bacteria. These endosymbionts, as they are known, are housed by their hosts within chosen chambers (cells in the gills in the case of clams and mussels, a structure called the "trophosome" in the worms). There, they metabolise the sulphide gases on behalf of the organisms they live in. In the clams and mussels, the bacteria are passed down the generations from parent to child; but in the worms, Dr Vrijenhoek and his colleagues have found, the symbionts must be recaptured afresh by each new generation--a curious arrangement, for, without their symbionts, these creatures cannot survive for long.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another feature of life on deep-sea vents is that all the animals seen so far reproduce sexually. This is unexpected (to those who ponder these things) for two reasons. First, organisms that live in extreme environments are usually asexual; that includes the endolithic communities in Antarctica. Those that live widely dispersed are also usually asexual; it only needs one to start a new colony. This suggests that, though boiling-hot sulphidic water at a depth where the water pressure may be 600 times greater than at sea-level sounds like a tough environment, such conditions are in fact the deep-sea equivalent of a lush tropical forest.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor are the vents as dark as might be supposed. Until recently, almost all the species were thought to be eyeless. On closer examination, some species, especially the shrimps, have turned out to have eyes of a sort. In 1996, a new species of shrimp was collected from the Snake Pit vent on the mid-Atlantic ridge. Like others previously found in the mid-Atlantic, it has a small eyespot with no lens. Instead, the eye is covered by a smooth sheet of material that is highly sensitive to light.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At first, this seems peculiar. So far under the sea, it is not immediately apparent that there is much to look at. But, of course, these creatures live near exceedingly hot water. Hot things, when viewed in the infrared, become visible. Very hot things become very bright. And, even more surprising, these vents actually give out a dim glow in the reddish end of the visible part of the spectrum. No one knows what causes it. But the shrimps can probably see it. They feed on bacteria spewed up from the fiery cauldrons below the seabed. The shrimps themselves do not actually live in the hot water: they would be boiled alive. So being able to see enough to maintain a healthy distance from the heat is a useful trick.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dr Vrijenhoek and his colleagues have traced the ancestry of the vent creatures. They have found that, contrary to some theories, the animals down there, weird as they are, have all evolved from more familiar relations in the tidepools and reefs of the more familiar earth. It just shows what too much pressure can do to you.<br>
<br>

