<html><head><title>A bit about photographs</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>A bit about photographs</h1>

<p><b>Digital photography is developing rapidly. How quickly it will overtake conventional cameras and film, though, is debatable</b></p><br>
HIGH on The Peak--the mountain that overlooks Hong Kong's famous skyline--one of the colony's more enterprising hawkers has gone high-tech. Piled on to his hand-cart are a personal computer, a monitor and a colour printer, all powered by batteries and linked to a digital camera mounted on a tripod. Tourists are offered instant souvenir pictures of themselves against one of the most spectacular backdrops in the world. And if the dramatic view is obscured by clouds, never mind: the hawker's imaging software will soon superimpose a clear skyline.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Digital cameras are the first serious change in the technology of recording static images since Louis Daguerre perfected his process in 1838. By storing pictures electronically, they avoid all the tedious mucking about with chemicals that is required to turn out photographs. And, as a bonus, they deliver their images in a form that multimedia computers can play with. Not surprisingly, sales of digital cameras are growing rapidly--up from 200,000 in 1995 to 800,000 in 1996.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It seems likely, therefore, that the digital revolution is going to ride rough-shod over photography, as it has over other areas, such as the music industry. But probably not quite yet. For electronic cameras, despite all their wizardry, still lack the thing that has given digital devices their edge elsewhere--they are not yet as accurate as the old-fashioned, analogue way of doing things.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Colouring the picture</b></b><br>
Digitising something means dividing it up into discrete parcels that can be described by numbers. In the case of pictures, these parcels are known as "pixels" (the individual spots on a television screen are one familiar example of them). A digital camera generates its pixels by focusing light not on to a film, but on to a silicon chip known as a charge-coupled device (<font size=-1>CCD</font>)--a component that also forms the core of moving-picture cameras such as camcorders.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main working elements of the best-known chips--the microprocessors at the heart of computers--are transistors. These are semiconductor switches with three wires protruding from them. One carries current in. A second carries current out. And a third tells the transistor whether or not to let the current (and thus a signal) through. <font size=-1>CCD</font>s are also made of semiconducting switches, but in this case the switches are diodes, and thus have only two protruding wires. <font size=-1>CCD</font> diodes, however, are light-sensitive, and it is this sensitivity that provides the third input--the one that controls the electrical signal. When exposed to an image, each diode produces a signal that depends on the brightness and colour of the part of the image that is falling on it. Since a <font size=-1>CCD</font> has at least several hundred thousand light-sensitive diodes, the image can be broken up into a corresponding number of pixels.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The pixels generated by a <font size=-1>CCD</font> can be stored either in an internal memory chip in the camera or in a small plug-in "flash" memory consisting of yet another type of chip. When the memory is full, the picture files stored in it are transferred to a computer where, with the appropriate software, the pictures can be viewed, edited, printed out, placed in other programs (such as desk-top publishing documents), used to decorate a web site or e-mailed to a friend.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, with no chemicals and no more films to buy, why would anyone ever bother with a conventional camera again? The reason is resolution. The light-sensitive gels on photographic film are very fine-grained, and can thus store a lot of detail. To reproduce the detail found in a good-quality colour transparency would require about 80m pixels. Even the most expensive digital cameras cannot manage this. A digital version of a Nikon single-lens reflex (<font size=-1>SLR</font>) camera, for example, can produce an image of only about 6m pixels. And at $27,000 a throw, it is unlikely to be gracing the Christmas stockings of even the most enthusiastic amateurs. Meanwhile, digital cameras affordable by lesser mortals (those retailing for less than $500) can manage but a few hundred thousand pixels.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor do the putative digital photographer's problems end there. Having taken his photograph, he must store it--and a traditional slide box will not do the trick. Instead, a fair amount of electronic memory must be available.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The simplest pixel conceivable requires one "bit" of information. Photos based on single-bit pixels would not, however, be very exciting, since one bit would allow a pixel only to be either black or white (off or on in a computer's vocabulary). Once shades of grey are included, the number of possibilities escalates-- and so does the storage space required. A simple 8-bit image allows each pixel to have 256 possible shades of grey or basic colours. For richer 24-bit colour (which many computer monitors use) each pixel can have 16.7m different colour possibilities.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each extra bit, however, requires more storage space. Exactly how big the picture file ends up depends on the size of the photo, the level of detail, the camera's colour-management software and the format in which it is stored (there are many such formats, and some use compression techniques to try to cut down on the storage capacity required). Yet even a dozen 24-bit colour snapshots, each made up of only 200,000 pixels, will occupy two megabytes of memory (a quarter as much as an average personal computer holds), while some of the professional digital cameras around spew out so much data that they have to be tethered directly to a fast computer's hard disk in order to gather it all. A picture of the quality required by a magazine could easily gobble up 60-80 megabytes. A large poster would require some 400 megabytes. Lugging around the hardware necessary to cope with all this is not going to appeal to the average holiday maker.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Digital cameras are improving, to be sure. But so is conventional photography. Chemical imaging, which has come a long way since Daguerre's day, is getting better still. Kodak and its arch-rival, Fuji, recently teamed up to launch the "Advanced Photo System" (<font size=-1>APS</font>). This employs ordinary film to capture the image, but incorporates a magnetic strip on which data such as the lighting conditions prevailing when a shot was taken are stored. <font size=-1>APS</font> is easier to use than a digital camera, and allows more accurate processing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So film wins? Not necessarily. And certainly not for many professional photographers. Even if their work is shot on film, the pictures taken by most working photographers increasingly end up as pixels anyway. In many newspapers and magazines, darkrooms are already a thing of the past. Both colour-negative and transparency film are now routinely machine-processed and scanned directly into digital files. The pictures are edited on a computer screen and placed straight into the electronic page-make-up.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, where speed is important, a growing number of professional photographers are already using digital cameras. Not just news photographers, but police-cameramen, estate agents and insurance assessors. Many of the photographs used in catalogues are also taken with digital cameras: if the final pictures are going to be small anyway, then digital cameras are already good enough. They are also good enough for images that will appear only on a computer screen, or will be printed out in a document on a low-resolution printer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is this tolerance for imperfection that may yet allow digital cameras to win the mass market. For, while a small group of well-equipped amateurs armed with <font size=-1>SLR</font>s and enough lenses to start a minor observatory might like to think themselves a cut above the average holiday photographer, most people only want to take snapshots.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those not in search of the ideal, the digital camera already is--or soon will be-- perfectly suitable for many types of photography. <font size=-1>CCD</font>s will surely get better and so will the software that the cameras use. Kodak recently joined up with Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and a new Californian firm called Live Picture in order to establish a new format for digital snapshots. Called FlashPix, it promises less memory-intensive pictures and faster editing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cost of digital photography will also fall, particularly since it will soon no longer be necessary to build your own digital dark-room at home to process and display the pictures. A plethora of new products and services to support digital photography is starting to arrive. These range from simple-to-use snapshot-quality home printing machines for digital cameras, to instant print and enlargement services from high-street film developers. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And digital photography could shake the equipment market up even further. Camera companies may know a lot about optics, but they do not necessarily have much experience with electronics. It is not just film manufacturers that should be quaking in their boots--if Nikon, Canon and Minolta are not careful, they may find themselves competing with the likes of Sony and Casio.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So eventually, as with every battle between digital and analogue, it is likely that digital will win. Film will live on, but probably only in specialist use. Just as a few die-hards still shun <font size=-1>CD</font> players and listen to vinyl discs through valve amplifiers, in years to come there will always be one tourist in that group high above Hong Kong who pulls out a battered old Nikon <font size=-1>F5</font> and delights in informing everyone that photographs never look right unless they are made from silver halide. For most people, though, the chance to alter their holiday's weather conditions after the event will win out every time.<br>
<br>

