<html><head><title>Death by the invisible hand</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="story.gif" width="285" height="28" alt="">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<img src="xth1.jpg"><br> <img src="deathby.gif"><br> <img src="ruth.gif"><p>

<img src="monmor.gif"><br> "Heresy! Rank heresy!" The editor squeezed his hands together unhappily."Come now, Geoffrey. Tom was merely being provocative."
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Edward, why do you persist in ignoring the truth about this subversive? Tom has just questioned whether we should continue to support the Anglo-American special relationship! He'll be telling us next that we should drum America out of <font size=-1>NATO</font> and rely on the French." Hodgskin's voice rose in a screech. "The French!!!"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tom St Loe Rathbone's patronising drawl cut in. "Chill out, Geoffrey. I thought the whole point of editorial meetings was to think the unthinkable."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hodgskin drew himself up to his full six feet four. "There is the unthinkable and there is the unspeakable. And what is not speakable is the querying of our fixed principles."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"In fairness, Geoffrey," said the editor mildly, "our commitment to the Atlantic alliance was relatively recent."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Geoffrey Hodgskin's enormous frame quivered. "For over a third of <i>The Economist</i>'s life a guiding principle has been the need to keep our allies from going back into Fortress <font size=-1>USA</font>."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, for heaven's sake," said the editor irritably. "You know perfectly well Tom is just expressing his own personal opinion. We don't necessarily agree with him. Just because he tilts at our sacred cows doesn't mean the cows aren't sacred."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hodgskin's voice rose to a scream. "With an editor who has chosen to abandon the monarchy, how can I have any faith that we will be true to our heritage?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The editor sighed. "We've been through all that. Bagehot took a relaxed view on that over a century ago."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"To be precise," observed the Britain editor, "Bagehot said he didn't expect the monarchy to last much beyond his life-time."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Bugger Bagehot," said Rathbone. "Who cares what he thought. It's what <i>we </i>think that matters."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Typical," shouted Hodgskin. "Typical of your complete failure to appreciate . . . "<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rathbone yawned. "Oh, for God's sake, Jeffers, you're carrying on as if we had abandoned free trade. Though I have to say I've been wondering recently if protectionism mightn't have the virtue of . . . "<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That's it," howled Hodgskin. "You infidel! You apostate!" He picked up his coffee-mug and threw it across the room at Rathbone. It bounced off the deputy editor's shoulder and shattered against the window. As Hodgskin stormed out, the assembled staff showed no emotion. As one man they shrugged and moved on to discuss whether anything useful might emerge from the latest European Union summit.<br>

<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Five minutes later, the luscious Julia Barrington, one of the editor's secretaries, emerged from the lift into the lobby and stopped in mid-stride to stare through the plate-glass window at what looked like the corpse of Geoffrey Hodgskin lying on the plaza among several pieces of wood and metal. As she exclaimed with alarm, two passers-by materialised and helped Hodgskin to his feet.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What's happened, Zoe?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The receptionist tittered nervously. "I think Geoffrey has finally gone bonkers. He came charging out of the lift, rushed over to James . . . " She waved at the forbidding marble statue of the founder of <i>The Economist</i> that stared from a corner of the lobby, " . . . waved his arms at him, shouted something like 'It'll be back to the Corn Laws next,' rushed out the door and crashed straight into that . . . that whassitsname." She consulted a piece of paper. "Oh, yes. 'Fiscal Rectitude'. Now, what's been going on? What have you been doing to him?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's not us," protested Julia. "It's him. He's off his bleeding rocker. Comes screaming out of the editorial meeting about how the world's coming to an end or something." She looked over at the statue. "If you ask me, he thinks he's James Wilson. He's nearly as ugly anyway."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Leave off making fun of James. Sanest person in this place if you ask me. At least he doesn't shout and run about. Seems to me Geoffrey is driving himself mad spending every night crouched over old <i>Economists</i>."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, blimey. Is that what he's at? So that's why he's raving on about getting rid of the welfare state, is it?" <br><img src="xth2.jpg"><br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"And why he's going blind and falling over things. Mind you, I'm delighted he's messed up that piece of rubbish. Art, indeed! With a bit of luck it can't be repaired."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Should we try to calm Geoffrey down?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Too late, love." Zoe waved towards the plaza. "I think he's taken his nervous breakdown home."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Let's hope he stays there with it. Sometimes I think Geoffrey's going to do someone an injury."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Like Tom, for instance? Serve him right. From all I hear, he's always winding Geoffrey up."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Julia looked cross. "It may seem like that from down here, Zoe, but on the 13th floor it's different. As Edward says . . . " -- her voice took on a note of pomposity-- "we have a noble tradition of dissent."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Zoe laughed coarsely. "Dissent my bum! There's nothing noble about Tom Rathbone. Nasty flashy bit of work."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You just don't like him 'cos he's a bit stand-offish," said Julia. "In editorial we admire him 'cos he's brilliant."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To Julia's relief and Zoe's regret, the arrival of a visitor brought the dispute to an end. <p><img src="wedeve.gif"><br> The editor groaned and picked up his phone. "Sophie? How the hell did Geoffrey's privatisation leader get through? For God's sake, he starts from the premise that government has no legitimate role except to organise defence and then proposes privatising the armed forces. Even James Wilson might have thought that was going a little far."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sorry, Edward. What with the allegations of group sex in the cabinet and the rapprochement between Margaret Thatcher and Ted Heath, we're all up to our eyes."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Anyone around who can write a substitute?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Tom, maybe."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Don't tell Geoffrey. He'll go completely off his head."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"How would we know the difference?" enquired the Britain editor icily. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was unfortunate, the Britain editor agreed, after the murder of Tom St Loe Rathbone, that she had not ensured that Geoffrey Hodgskin had gone home rather than--as it turned out--having been on the 14th floor obsessively reading 1840s <i>Economists</i> and occasionally keying into the system to find out what had happened to his leader. It was even more unfortunate that no one had time that evening to read and amend Tom's proposition that privatisation was yesterday's solution to tomorrow's problems and that the time had come to look again at the merits of public ownership of the means of production. Unfortunately, the senior editorial staff were working frantically to cover an unprecedented series of political crises.<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At 7.00pm the cabinet sex story which had formed the basis for a leader on terminal sleaze had turned out to have been invented by a disgruntled secretary at No. 10 who had had her advances rejected by the prime minister; at 8.30 the cover showing Thatcher and Heath in an embrace under the heading "Bygones will be bygones" had to be replaced when the Moscow correspondent sent through the news about Boris Yeltsin's double; the flash from the Washington office that there was to be a congressional inquiry into the allegation that the cat Socks occasionally ate food paid for from the White House Hospitality Budget came at 9.30; and at 10.30, just as the remnants of the graphics department were leaving, came the news from Reuters that Rupert Murdoch had bought Indonesia, necessitating a change of cover for three editions, a new front leader and a complete reorganisation of two sections. Mass hysteria at 11.00 when the computer system crashed was narrowly averted by a successful rescue mission by the technical department's Donald Barrington. <p><img src="thumor.gif"><br> <img src="xth3.jpg"><br> At 2.00am, having indulged in mutual congratulation, discussed the latest stage of the Hodgskin-Rathbone feud and consumed wine and sandwiches, the five senior editors left the building together.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As they walked towards the waiting taxis, the deputy editor stopped.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"'Market Forces' seems to have come a cropper. No doubt Geoffrey will blame Tom."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's certainly been an expensive week on the sculpture front," said the foreign editor. "I hope it's not an omen. There's only one left intact."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The quintet walked over to inspect the damage. It was the finance editor who spotted a flash of beige cloth and the deputy editor who said worriedly that it looked like an arm.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"And isn't that a leather glove?" asked the editor.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As one they dashed back into the building, instructed the security guard to call the police, took the lift back to the editor's office and broke open a bottle of whisky. "That looked like cashmere to me," said the Britain editor, as she tremblingly raised the glass to her lips. "The only person I know who wears a cashmere coat is Tom Rathbone."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Where's Geoffrey?" asked the other four, in unison. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It took an hour for the police to summon up the block-and-tackle necessary to restore "Market Forces" to its vertical position. Having identified the squashed and bloody remains of Rathbone, at 3.30 the senior editorial staff went shakily home; the editor had time only to shower and change before making it back at 5.30 to start reading the first proofs.<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By 10.00am he had joined Detective-Inspector Greg and Detective-Constable Asquith in the board room.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I hope my secretary was able to assist you, gentlemen."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Thank you, sir. Mrs Barrington made us very comfortable. Now would you be so kind as to tell us which of your colleagues would have wanted to kill Mr Rathbone."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Surely it was an accident?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sorry, sir. It won't wash. The sculptor's been round; the constructor's been round; the security guards have had a look. They're all adamant that that whateveritwas . . . "<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sculpture. An abstract representation of Adam Smith's invisible hand."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Whose what?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The economist Adam Smith agreed that selfish, individual actions work together, through market forces, to the benefit of society as a whole--as if guided by an invisible hand."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"He did, did he? Well, there's no accounting for taste, sir. Well, then, this very large and--if Mr Smith will forgive me-- visible triangular object was rock-solid on its base. It simply could not have fallen over without help." He gazed severely at the editor. "What's more, it will have taken three people to push it over on top of that unfortunate gentleman. What have you to say to that, sir?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The editor took a grip on himself. "I'm sorry, Inspector Greg. You've lost me. What exactly are you implying?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That the deceased was murdered by at least three people on the staff of your magazine."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Newspaper," corrected the editor absent-mindedly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"If you say so, sir. For all I care you can call it a comic. What I want to know is which of your staff you think might be responsible for this dastardly deed."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Why should you point the finger at my staff? I am responsible only for the journalists. This building also houses <i>The Economist</i>'s management as well as six different organisations."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inspector Greg looked at the editor sternly. "Come now, Mr Strachey. You are wasting your time and mine. Thomas St Loe Rathbone was murdered at some time between midnight and 1.30. The likelihood has to be that the murderers were in your building at the time. How else would they have known that Mr Rathbone was around and available to be murdered? Mrs Barrington tells us that if it hadn't been for all the unexpected news he'd have been gone hours earlier."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You're begging a large number of questions, inspector."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I'm only a policeman, sir. Not an intellectual. Now Mrs Barrington's given us a list of who was on the premises at the relevant time. Can you confirm it?" He shoved a piece of paper at the editor, who scanned it and sighed. "Not a complete list, inspector. Julia can be forgetful. She hasn't put her husband on it, for instance. Or the security guards. Or Geoffrey Hodgskin, who spent much of the night on the 14th floor. Or even the finance editor, who, as you know, was one of those who discovered the body. And she's misspelled some names."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He amended the list and tossed it back. "You were asking which three people on that list might have had a motive."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"At least. Of course, there might have been more than three of them in it."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The editor sat bolt upright. "This is ridiculous, inspector. My colleagues are journalists, not members of the Mafia. They often have robust arguments with each other; on occasion some will get excited and raise their voices; one of them has even been known to throw a typewriter through a window. But in 153 years they've never resorted to homicide."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"There's a first for everything," said the inspector genially. "Now, sir, I'm sorry, but I'm going to have to take you through this list and ask you to tell me what relationship the late Mr Rathbone had with each of his colleagues. <p><img src="thuaft.gif"><br> "My head's spinning, lad. I can't take much more of this. I don't understand the half of what they're going on about."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You mean about the ideological differences, sir?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Whatever they call them. What was it that bird said?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Which one, sir?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The one that had swallowed a dictionary and kept going on about dead economists."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Ah, yes. Sophie Hamilton, you mean. She certainly seems to be a true intellectual."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"They're all bluestockings here if you ask me. The men as well as the women. But she takes the biscuit. What was all that about . . . " He consulted his notes. " . . . the revolt against classical economics? And what are Canesians and Freedmanites when they're at home? Football teams?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asquith smiled rather condescendingly. "In <i>Economist</i> terms they are, sir. Keynes and Friedman were two of the most influential economists of this century. Dr Hamilton was explaining that their adherents on the paper had had a sharp difference over the causes of inflation, that a few young neo-Keynesians on the staff who favour an attack on high unemployment are prepared to consider an incomes policy, how the Friedmanites are still convinced that inflation is purely linked to the money supply and why . . . "<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Stow it, will you? It's bad enough being lectured in double dutch by a bossy cow in jeans who looks about 12 without having my own constable following suit."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He looked at his subordinate with ill-concealed resentment. "You should be one of them too, if you ask me, instead of working for the humble police force." He glowered. "Bloody graduates. All the same. No common sense. Nothing to beat the university of life."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asquith, who was well used to this line of attack from his superiors, gazed expressionlessly at the table.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, all right then. I suppose you're only doing your best. But stop showing off and call in the next git."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Which git, sir?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That Geoffrey Hodgskin that had a row with the corpse on Monday. Maybe he'll make a bit more sense."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was a pity, Asquith remarked afterwards to his wife, that Hodgskin's answer to a question about why he thought Rathbone had ended a promising career underneath "Market Forces" should have led to a harangue about the invisible hand and the poetry of laisser-faire. Inspector Greg eventually erupted with rage. "Shut up," he bellowed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a moment Asquith thought Hodgskin had been shocked into sanity, but he then leaped to his feet, cried "<i>L</i><i>&egrave;se majest</i><i>&eacute;</i>," and rushed from the room. Before he banged the door behind him, he turned and glared malevolently.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You're just like him. Meddlers. Statists. Possibly even protectionists! And not a fixed principle between you!"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Hodgskin banged the door, Inspector Greg put his elbows on the table and clasped his head tightly in his hands. After a moment he looked up. "What was that about? As far as I could tell, he seemed to be saying Adam Smith did it."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Well, of course, in a sense he did," said Asquith. And then hastily, seeing Greg's face, "I think Mr Hodgskin isn't well, sir. He wasn't making any sense."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"If it could have been done by one of them, we'd have him," said Greg. "He's barking." He shook his head. "But it's just not possible that he could have worked without accomplices. There's something funny going on here."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sir, could I just . . . ?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sssshhhh, lad. Stay quiet. Let's go and get lunch." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As they passed the reception desk, Zoe beamed cheerfully. "Found out whodunnit?"<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Fat chance." Greg stopped. "Are they as mad as they seem? Some of them don't seem to be on this planet."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, they're all right, most of them," she said indulgently. "It's just that they live in their heads too much. Anyway I'm sure none of them murdered Tom. Lots of them would have liked to get rid of Stuck-up Mr Superior Rathbone--including me--but they're not practical enough, for one thing."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The inspector's attention was caught by a screen on the wall behind her. "What's that."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's all part of the exhibition."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What exhibition?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"We had a competition among the art schools to show the essence of <i>The Economist</i>. That's a film made up of identical photographs of James Wilson's statue that plays round and round in slow motion 24 hours a day."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Why?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"'Cos James is our founder.'<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What's the point of the film?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She took out a leaflet and read aloud: "The perceptual response of the ever-revolving loop is a metaphor for the velocity of circulation." Seeing the inspector's uncomprehending face, she added helpfully, "I think it's something to do with money. James was very interested in that sort of thing."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Was he interested in over-filled wastepaper baskets, too?" asked Greg, pointing to a large mess to the right of Wilson's statue. "Is that art as well? Or are you waiting for the garbage collectors?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Zoe was enjoying herself. "Surely you realise that's what's known as an installation. This one's called 'Paper Covered with Adam Smith's Invisible Ink'. And then out there used to be 'Fiscal Rectitude', until Geoffrey fell over it. And 'Market Forces', until it fell over on Tom. And that thing that's still standing--the giant kid's football with the question mark on top--is 'The Pursuit of Reason'."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inspector Greg sighed. "From what I've seen of this place, they're not pursuing it fast enough. Come on, Asquith."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Shouldering their way through cameras and importunate reporters, they set off to a pub. <p><img src="xth4.jpg"><br> Mollified by a vast plate of steak-and-kidney pie and a pint of bitter, Greg beamed at his subordinate. "All right then, brains. What do you think?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I think Rathbone was murdered by just one person, sir."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"How do you work that out? Is there an Arnie Schwarzenegger on the staff I haven't met yet?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"A lever, sir. You wouldn't have to be strong to lever up that sculpture and then push it over."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg ruminated for a moment. "You're seriously suggesting that Rathbone obligingly stood still while someone levered up that pile of metal and then shoved it on top of him?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Not quite, sir." Asquith took a handkerchief from his pocket and opened it to reveal a large pebble. "I found this lying near the . . . ", he hesitated, " . . . the murder weapon."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"So what? There are lots like that around the place."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"My theory, sir, is that Rathbone made a date to meet someone by 'Market Forces'. The murderer equipped himself with a crowbar, levered up the sculpture beforehand and wedged the pebble underneath. That gave him the purchase to push the sculpture over on Rathbone and disappear, knowing no one would pay any attention to a pebble."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Far-fetched."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Less so than a murderous troika, sir, if you'll forgive me."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg drained his second pint. "Sometimes I see the point of having graduates in the police force, son. Come on back to the Tower and let's ask about crowbars." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Summoned by Zoe, the head of maintenance went in search of <i>The Economist</i>'s crowbar and returned to announce its disappearance from its accustomed spot in the basement. "It'll be in some litter bin, somewhere, I expect," said Greg.<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"But who'd have known where to find it?" enquired Asquith.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Put it this way, constable," said the maintenance supremo. "Anyone working here knows we're located in the basement. It wouldn't take a genius to guess we'd have a crowbar and to slip downstairs and find it after we'd gone home."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg nodded his thanks. "I'm going back to the board room, Asquith. Find the editor and bring him to me." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What do you mean he says no? Who does he think he is?"<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"He's got a crisis, sir. The <font size=-1>US</font> Secretary of the Treasury's just been forced to resign over a Chinese rent-boy, Wall Street's taken a nosedive and they've got to change the first leader and give the American edition a new cover. He sends his apologies and will be with you as soon as he's sorted things out."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What about the others who were with him last night?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"They've gone home to rest: he's holding the fort."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Bugger. I wanted to hear more about Hodgskin."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Surely he's First Suspect now, sir."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You may be right, lad, but my guess is he wouldn't know a crowbar from a slide-rule."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He noticed Asquith's puzzled expression. "Don't you know what a slide-rule is? Oh, God. I suppose to you it's as relevant as a bloody abacus. Never mind. Just find Hodgskin."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No one could be found who had seen Hodgskin since late morning. The police whiled away the next hour or so taking unhelpful statements from whatever members of editorial were around. As with their colleagues that morning, there was a general consensus that <i>Economist</i> staff settled their differences at worst with rows or sulks or back-biting. No one was prepared to suggest any likely murderer, and all of them indicated that they couldn't imagine Hodgskin having the ability to unzip a banana, let alone locate a crowbar and do something murderous with it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Why, he's a computer illiterate," observed Henry Lathbury, the classics double-first who informed the world what South American greybeards were doing wrong.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"But we were told that he would have seen on the system that his leader had been scrubbed in favour of one by Rathbone which he'd have hated."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, yes. He could manage that. But he still used a portable typewriter. Couldn't even manage e-mail. Always barged into people's offices instead." He smirked complacently. "Too old to learn, I expect."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg was overwhelmed by a wave of hatred. "Thank you, young man. Now run along and tell your elders and betters how to run their affairs."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Lathbury left, the editor came in. "Sorry about that," he said. "We're having a bad week for crises. There was just time to stop the American presses. Now how can I help you? I'd like this cleared up as fast as possible. The tabloids are going to play merry hell with our anonymity. Ever since they cottoned on to the fact that we're not all middle-aged men with pointy heads, they're trying to get together a of page mug-shots.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Now what do you want to know?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Strachey was in the midst of an impassioned defence of Hodgskin when the door opened to reveal a young woman who said breathlessly, "Edward, the foreign secretary's crossing the<br>
floor over Europe. Shall we stop the presses?"
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the editor ran from the room he called, "Sorry, but the way things are happening Deng will die just in time for us to stop our Asia edition. Come back tomorrow." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I'm not happy with ideological murder, Asquith. People don't kill people over points of principle. They kill them for old-fashioned reasons like money or sex."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asquith looked shocked. "But this is <i>The Economist</i>, sir. They do things differently here."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Even intellectuals feel greed and lust, son."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Not Hodgskin, from what we've seen. Or Dr Hamilton, for that matter. They seem to be pure intellects."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To Asquith's astonishment, Greg leaped to his feet and declaimed: "Hath not an intellectual eyes? Hath not an intellectual hands, organs, dimensions, senses, affections, passions?" He grinned triumphantly. "If you prick us, do we not bleed?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He fell back into his seat. "Just because I didn't go to university doesn't mean I'm completely ignorant. I do dramatic recitations at the Freemasons' charity Christmas concert. Now you mark my words, son. As Kipling said, 'The colonel's lady an' Judy O'Grady are sisters under their skins!' I'll bet my shirt the same's true of Sophie and Julia." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I know what he's getting at," said Asquith to his wife, who was a lecturer in political science. "And I'm not saying that intellectuals can't be driven by base passions. But I've been reading <i>The Economist</i>'s history, and from what I can see, Hodgskin is pretty typical. The founder, for instance, used to get his rocks off on arguments about currency."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She yawned. "Sorry, Richard. I'm knackered. I had two seminars, a lecture and four distressed students today, quite apart from marking essays. And a faculty meeting to boot."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"There you are. You may be an intellectual, but you've got students to keep your feet on the ground. These people get plucked out of Oxbridge or Harvard or wherever and transported to the 13th floor of the Economist Tower where they sit in cubicles so small they'd disgrace a Singapore prison, think deep thoughts and debate with each other like members of a senior common room."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He would have gone on, but his wife was asleep. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Poor kids," said Mrs Greg. "Sounds as if they don't get much fun."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You're as bad as Asquith. Just because they argue about things we don't understand doesn't mean they don't have fun on the side. The kids are probably off clubbing as we speak. And I wouldn't be surprised if Dr Hamilton wasn't a right little raver when she's off duty. It's just that they've got to pretend to be serious."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"In that case, why have they murdered someone because they didn't agree with him?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Oh, never mind, dear. Let's see what's on telly." <p><img src="frimor.gif"><br> "Why didn't the security guard hear this thing falling over, Greg?" asked Chief Inspector Palgrave.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"He had a hoax call around midnight from an unidentified chap claiming there was an intruder in the garage. Reckons 'Market Forces' must have been pushed on to Rathbone by the time he got back. He wouldn't have seen it, of course, in that dark corner beside Boodles."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Do we know what Rathbone was doing hanging about the plaza at that time of night anyway? Seems a funny time and place to make a date."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Indeed it does, sir. We're pursuing the matter."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Damn slowly," said Palgrave. "Get a bloody move on, Greg, and make that toffee-nosed little constable of yours shake a leg as well." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"All this praise of competition that you get here is infectious, Asquith. We'll split up. You take the intellectuals. I'll take the plebs. And I'll get the answer afore ye."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Will Hodgskin be mine, sir?" asked Asquith eagerly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg chuckled. "For all the good he is to you, lad. I've just had a call that he was home before midnight and safely in the arms of his landlady. She is, I'm told, a lady of mature charms who said with a wink that she'd succeeded in calming him down by the traditional methods."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"You can't believe her, sir, surely?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Her next-door neighbour, a busy-body of the first order, agrees that he came home at around that time. Apparently he fell over several milk-bottles, woke her up and she rushed to the window and saw him just before he closed his front door."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asquith swore. "Never mind, lad," said Greg gaily. "Cherchez l'intellectual. See you for lunch. <p><img src="friaft.gif"><br> "By the time they met, Asquith's spirits had recovered. "I think I've got it, sir. It's much more important than we thought. The prime suspect is the editor."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Wait until I've ordered my shepherd's pie, lad. A pint?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Just a half," said Asquith, who hated drinking at lunchtime but feared ridicule.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"OK, then," said Greg, when they had settled. "Why the editor?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"He's not an economist and Rathbone was brilliant, arrogant and delighted in showing him up in front of his staff. The editor's prestige was slipping."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Couldn't he have fired him?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's not the sort of place where you can afford to fire your intellectual superiors. Everybody would know why'd he done it. According to a few of the people I talked to today who like him and think him a competent and decent bloke, the editor was getting increasingly pressurised at the Monday morning meetings as Rathbone pushed him to justify all the paper's traditional attitudes. It was like a weekly viva."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"So he murdered him?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That's certainly what some of them are suggesting. Apparently, he suffers from an inferiority complex because he got only a second-class degree."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"We all have our crosses to bear," said Greg. "It's your round, lad." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Julia Barrington broke down under Greg's harsh questioning that afternoon. "It's all my fault he's dead. I should have known that e-mail cancelling our date wasn't his. It hadn't any quotations. If I'd kept our date he'd be alive now."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg patted her shoulder. "Look on the bright side, love. If you'd met him, you might both be dead." <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"So you've won," said a disgruntled Asquith. "It was her husband, I suppose."<br><br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Certainly seems like that on the face of it. You can't read people's e-mail unless you have their passwords, but the technical department would have no difficulty in cracking that."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Congratulations, sir. Simple marital jealousy, then."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg sighed. "Would that it were so simple. I've had an instructive chat with Zoe and the guys in the post-room. I need the answers to a few key questions."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Like what?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"How could Rathbone afford cashmere? Why does the editor have a secretary as dim as Julia? Why was Geoffrey Hodgskin taking everything so personally? Why did the Britain editor put up with Rathbone when the American and foreign editors had chucked him out as unendurable? And why do people as intelligent as these like such idiotic modern art?"<br>

<p><img src="xth5.jpg"><br>

