<html><head><title>The wrong design</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>The wrong design</h1>


<CleverDrop>LEADERS of the European Union meet in Dublin this weekend to discuss, among other things, the budget-deficit rules that will apply to members of their planned economic and monetary union. To most readers, whether in Baltimore, Bangkok or even Brussels, this might seem an abstruse technical matter. Yet it goes to the heart of the debate over Europe's future and the prospects for its new currency. The details of the proposed "stability pact" have proved contentious, but governments seem willing to accept that tight restraints from the centre should apply to national policies on taxes and spending. That would be a far-reaching decision, and one that sets <font size=-1>EMU</font> on a wrong and dangerous course.
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a view may seem odd, given <i>The Economist</i>'s earlier support for monetary union in principle; or unduly dramatic, given that so few other voices have been raised against the stability pact. It will strike some as a reversal of our earlier stance. It isn't, and it may be useful to say why.<br>
<b><br>
</p><p><b>A design for diversity</b></b><br>
For years, since long before monetary union began to be seriously discussed, <i>The Economist</i> has maintained an unusual position on the matter. Our view has been that <font size=-1>EMU</font> could be a good thing or a bad thing depending on how it is done. This has offended Euro-visionaries, eager to see monetary union proceed on almost any design, and it has disgusted Britain's minds-of-oak Eurosceptics, who think <font size=-1>EMU</font>, however conceived, is a foreign plot to enslave them.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Monetary union has long been more than an academic curiosity. Despite that, public debate on the subject has been dismally poor right across Europe. This is worrying. Without broad and informed consent, <font size=-1>EMU</font> may prove fragile--and informed consent requires proper debate. Equally, the costs of staying out, if that is what Britain or other countries choose, need to be widely understood. Far from engaging in argument, the pro and anti tribes ignore each other resolutely. Neither seems interested in the commonsense proposition that the case for monetary union turns on what kind of monetary union it is. In our view, that question--what kind of <font size=-1>EMU</font>?--remains the central issue. The budget-rules are crucial because of the light they shed on it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Before coming to that, however, what would a good <font size=-1>EMU</font> look like? It would derive the greatest gains from Europe's single market while preserving the broadest political autonomy for its nation states. There need be no conflict between those goals: it is wrong to argue that further economic integration requires further political integration. If the system's foundations were properly laid, political autonomy and economic integration could be mutually strengthening.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A truly single market in Europe, based on a single currency, could support competition among governments across nearly the full range of domestic policy--on education, welfare, taxes, public investment, labour-market regulation and more. Different ideas on particular policies, and on the overall role of the state, could be tested in a uniquely revealing way. Efforts to suppress such competition by harmonising large areas of economic policy are not just unnecessary; they militate against exploiting the single market to the full.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You might ask, why should money be exempt from this competition among governments? Why harmonise currencies, as it were, and not those other things? The answer is simple. Allowing competition in monetary policy, which means letting currencies float, is collectively damaging. It causes volatility and misalignments in exchange rates. Coping with this consumes resources: it puts costs on business, impedes competition and retards investment. And in return for these public bads, there is no long-term advantage. In other areas of policy, differences over what works best (should labour markets be lightly or heavily regulated?) or what is right (how much should a country spend on its welfare state?) are inescapable. In these cases, diversity is good--a method of economic discovery and a necessary form of political self-expression. In monetary policy, there is no such uncertainty. Its only long-term purpose is to secure low inflation.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advantage derived from retaining national monies is strictly short-term: the freedom to cushion a local economic slowdown by devaluing the currency. Notwithstanding Britain's experience since 1992, this freedom is much less than it is held up to be. Devaluation ends in tears (higher inflation, no lasting gain in competitiveness) far more often than in triumph, as Britain's longer-term record confirms.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is well-trodden ground. Rather than tread it again, let us move on. Suppose that we have been right in the past to argue that there is much to be said for a monetary union of Europe's nation states. Suppose too, as we have also argued, that moving towards political union faster than the citizens of Europe want is wrong in principle and runs the risk of a bitter falling-out in due course. Supposing all that is true, why would a stability pact of the kind that Europe's leaders are contemplating be such a disturbing development?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After all, its defenders could argue as follows. Rules requiring governments to curb their debts and run small budget deficits do no more than codify good fiscal practice. Why should responsible governments feel threatened? Moreover, once <font size=-1>EMU</font> starts, there may be an opportunity for governments to borrow partly at their partners' expense. Fiscal rules are needed to guard against this. Finally, it might be argued, rules on deficits and debt leave entirely unconstrained the bigger decisions that governments make about how much to spend and on what; they require only that governments collect enough in taxes to pay their bills.<br>
<b><br>
</p><p><b>An awfully big adventure</b></b><br>
This may seem a powerful line of argument. We <a href="sf0803.html">return</a> to a detailed discussion of its economic aspects-- in particular, to the idea that rules are needed to restrain excessive borrowing. Our conclusion there is that, judged in narrow economic terms, the rules are not merely unnecessary but positively undesirable. For the moment, though, put the economics to one side and consider the politics.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The case for budget rules in Europe may be compared with the case for a balanced-budget amendment to America's constitution. Regardless of whether or not such an amendment would make sense, if the United States were ever to enact it the effect would be to set one branch of the government to restrain the others, according to a procedure that would be democratically well-grounded. What Europe is considering stands in stark contrast. Governments are to be held accountable not to separate powers at the national level but to supranational discretion; they are to be not merely restrained but, if they break the rules, punished, along with their citizens; all this according to procedures that command little or no popular consent. You could be forgiven for thinking the whole idea a plot to destroy the <font size=-1>EU</font> from within.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is possible that the <font size=-1>EU</font> will proceed by its usual methods--making progress incrementally, reacting to changing political and economic circumstances, interspersed by bursts of constitution-making by treaty. Those who argue that the stability pact is acceptable, because it won't work anyway and will eventually have to be ditched, are presumably making this assumption. At the end of that course may indeed lie the perfect Union sought by Euro-visionaries. Yet <font size=-1>EMU</font> is a far bigger and riskier adventure than any that the Union has previously embarked upon. The risk of doing so with a poor design, amid a constitutional arrangement that still lacks popular support in many member countries, is that if an economic crisis comes, pitting member against member, or member against the Union, it will come too quickly and on too large a scale to be dealt with in the usual way. When <font size=-1>EMU</font> fails that test, the entire structure could fold.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no need to take this risk. The best course would be to fix <font size=-1>EMU</font>, rejecting both Germany's stability pact and France's counter-proposal of a "stability council", which is unnecessary and looks designed to put political pressure on the supposed-to-be-independent European Central Bank. Admittedly, if a badly designed <font size=-1>EMU</font> is indeed launched in 1999, each country will still then have to balance the costs and benefits of joining in or staying out, and that balance will vary from country to country. But such a calculation lies in the future. The priority now, for all the governments of the Union, must be to improve the design. There is still time.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
