<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Holding pattern</h2>
 <h4><a href="bw1.gif">(See chart)</a></h4><p>
The Japanese government is set to lift the country's ban on holding companies. American occupation authorities forbad them in 1947 so as to break the hold of the <i>zaibatsu</i> (conglomerates). The catalyst for the change is the decision to split the world's largest company, <b>Nippon Telegraph & Telephone</b>, into three--all to be owned by one holding company. The change will allow Japanese companies to spread their liabilities and also shed excess capacity more readily.<p>
Germany's <b>Hoechst</b>, one of Europe's biggest drug and chemical groups, made an FFr18.1 billion ($3.5 billion) offer for the 43.3% of Roussel Uclaf it does not already own. Anticipation of the bid had driven up the French drug group's share price by 70% this year. Hoechst also plans to merge its DM6.5 billion ($4.2 billion) specialty-chemicals operations with Clariant, a Swiss chemical firm, creating a market leader.<p>
After a week of dithering, the French government announced <b>a new plan for Thomson</b>. It now says that next year it will privatise the troubled defense and consumer-electronics company in two parts. <p>
Homestake Mining is paying $2.3 billion for Santa Fe Pacific to create a <b>gold producer </b>in North America second only to Barrick Gold of Canada. An unwelcome bid from Newmont Mining for Santa Fe was earlier rejected.<p>
Britain's Monopolies Commission is to investigate the proposed takeover of <b>Carlsberg-Tetley</b> by <b>Bass</b>. The two combined would become the country's largest brewer with a 38% share of the beer market.<p>
The Australian Senate narrowly approved the A$8 billion ($6 billion) sale of one-third of <b>Telstra Corp</b>, the country's telecoms carrier. It will be the biggest share offering in the country's history. <p>
Aiming to hang on to its 12m cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> subscribers as competition from satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font> mounts, <b>Time Warner </b>is buying 1m new digital-<font size=-1>TV</font> set-top boxes, at a cost of around $400m. The new boxes will more than treble the average subscriber's choice of channels to about 175.<p>
<h2>Question:</h2>
"How do we know when<p>
<b>irrational exuberance</b> has unduly escalated asset values, which then become subject to unexpected and prolonged contractions?" The answer to Alan Greenspan was a bout of rational depression which continued to upset shares during the week after the Fed chairman's speech.<p>
Russia's main stockmarket regulator scored a modest, but important, point for <b>shareholder rights </b>when it insisted that Surgut Oil and Gas, one of the country's biggest energy firms, call off a controversial share-dilution scheme.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
In the first pay-out since the <b>Bank of Credit and Commerce International </b>was closed down by regulators five years ago, liquidators are paying out $1.35 billion to over 25,000 creditors, 24.5% of their losses. The final dividend is likely to be between 30% and 40%.<p>
<b>Aon Corporation</b> agreed to buy Alexander & Alexander Services, another American insurance broker. The deal, worth $1.2 billion, will create the world's biggest broker.<p>
<h2>Consuming less</h2>
 <h4><a href="bw2.gif">(See chart)</a></h4><p>
Sluggish consumer spending in North America and Europe this year has brought a sharper slowdown than expected in the growth in <b>world trade</b>, said a report released to coincide with the first ministerial gathering of the World Trade Organisation, held in Singapore. The <font size=-1>WTO</font> made some progress in its talks on liberalising trade in telecoms and technology. China also indicated that it would lower trade barriers to gain admittance to the <font size=-1>WTO</font>. <p>
The strong dollar produced America's largest-ever quarterly current-account<b> deficit</b>. It rose to $48 billion, 19% more than in the previous quarter, as quarterly merchandise exports fell for the first time in three years. Japan's current-account <b>surplus</b> in October was down 19.6% on the year, to &#165;367.4 billion ($3.27 billion), a sharper drop than predicted.<p>
<h2>Regrets, a few</h2>
The <b>industrial-espionage spat </b>between General Motors and Volkswagen shows no signs of ending peacefully. Ferdinand Piech, <font size=-1>VW</font>'s chairman, expressed regrets over the legal costs and the "confusion and anger", but did not apologise. An apology is a prerequisite, as far as <font size=-1>GM</font> is concerned, for an out-of-court settlement. <font size=-1>VW</font> also said 1996 profits and sales would be well up on last year. Meanwhile, German prosecutors indicted four <font size=-1>VW</font> employees, including Jose Ignacio Lopez, on criminal charges.<p>
The British government said the proposed alliance between <b>British Airways </b>and <b>American Airlines </b>would not face a monopolies inquiry if the two gave up 168 take-off and landing slots at London's main airport, Heathrow. <font size=-1>BA</font> has 3,100 slots there. Other American airlines said <font size=-1>BA</font>'s concessions were not enough. <p>
After years of wrangling, nine oil and gas companies, including America's Chevron and Russia's Lukoil, and the governments of Russia, Kazakhstan and Oman signed a $2 billion agreement to build a 1,440km (895 mile) <b>Caspian pipeline </b>that will connect remote but oil-rich western Kazakhstan with the Black Sea.<p>
<p>

