<html><head><title>Bookies raise the stakes</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>National Lottery</b></p>
<h1>Bookies raise the stakes</h1>

THOSE Britons not hoping for a share of the National Lottery's enormous winnings seem to have their eyes fixed on the enormous profits earned by the lottery's operator, Camelot. The Labour Party has announced that after Camelot's franchise runs out, it will either cap the next operator's profits or hand over the lottery to a non-profit-making outfit. The Virgin group has long offered to hand over a higher proportion of earnings to worthy causes in an effort to secure the franchise. Many charities argue that they deserve a bigger share. Now Britain's bookmakers have devised a scheme to win back the slice of the winnings they have lost to Camelot.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since it was launched two years ago, bookmakers have complained that the lottery lures their clients away with huge jackpots, reducing their profits. A study by the Henley Centre, a consultancy, calculated that the betting industry lost nearly 3,000 employees, 400 shops and &#163;47m in profits during the lottery's first year. A reduction in betting duty in the 1996 budget offset the worst of the downturn, but did not restore earlier profit levels. So in an effort to regain some of the lost ground, the three biggest bookmakers, Coral, William Hill, and Ladbroke's, will launch a daily rival to the National Lottery on December 16th.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Doing so has not been easy. When the government devised the lottery, it took great pains to safeguard the monopoly of the franchisee. Apart from Camelot, only charities and private clubs are allowed to run lotteries. The former can sell a maximum of &#163;1m of tickets, while the latter can cater only to members. Prevented from running a lottery themselves, the bookmakers might ordinarily just take bets on the outcome of Camelot's, as they do on the result of the Irish national lottery. But the government closed that loophole too.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now bookmakers think they can get round these regulations (Camelot disagrees) with a new daily draw, called 49's. Although it follows the format of the National Lottery closely, with six winning numbers drawn from a pool of 49 (hence the name), it will not technically be a lottery, since betting shops will not sell any tickets. Instead, they will take fixed-odds bets on the outcome of the draw. This method seems to evade the side-betting ban too, because although the 49's draws may vividly resemble those of the National Lottery, they will be completely separate. Basically, bookmakers will take side bets on a lottery-style event of their own devising.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 49's draw comes with all the trimmings. <font size=-1>SIS</font>, a company which broadcasts racing to betting shops, will televise the daily draw. Arthur Andersen, an accounting firm, is monitoring the proceedings, while Group4 will handle security. Any betting shop can participate for a weekly fee of &#163;5; about 7,000 have already signed up. The organisers aim initially to capture 2% of the industry turnover, or roughly &#163;120m a year.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thus, 49's does exactly what the government hoped it had prevented: it creates a non-charitable rival to the National Lottery. Unhampered by the financial burden of shelling out to charities, the betting-shops can offer bigger prizes than the National Lottery. They might therefore entice customers away from Camelot.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But bookies point out that many people placing side bets on the Irish lottery also buy tickets for the main event. Anyway, the British lottery is likely to dwarf 49's. Camelot brings in more revenue in two weeks than the bookmakers expect to in a year, and is starting a second weekly draw.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government might have prevented this challenge to the lottery if it had offered another cut in betting duty or simply caved in over side-betting. But 49's, once launched, is unlikely to disappear. Nor will the saga end there: as long as the National Lottery continues to make money, it will continue to attract competitors hoping to win their own jackpot.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
