<html><head><title>Breeding bugs</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Police powers</b></p>
<h1>Breeding bugs</h1>

THE government is full of new schemes to crack down on crime: handgun bans, stalking laws, mandatory sentencing, combat-knife regulation and so on. On top of all this, the Police bill currently making its way through Parliament will increase police powers to combat organized crime. Labour, keen to jump on the bandwagon, has lent its support. The police and public also seem to welcome all moves which promise greater security. But a handful of law lords are giving warning that the bill will hit civil liberties harder than it will criminals.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most contentious clause deals with surveillance, especially bugging. Under the new law, chief constables could authorise bugging without needing to seek a judge's approval, if they thought it might help solve a "serious" crime. The person bugged need not be a suspected criminal--just someone who might reveal some useful information. The only external supervision would come from a senior judge, who would review buggings after the event to check that the police had not exceeded their powers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bill's supporters argue that it does nothing more than give a legal footing to a common practice. In 1995 the police in England and Wales used such surveillance techniques 1,300 times, following Home Office guidelines in place since 1985. And regulating this practice is really just a precaution, they argue, since few complaints have been made against the police under the current system, and none upheld. <font size=-1>MI</font>5<t--mode> </t--mode> has similar powers, and nobody makes a fuss about that. To insist that the police get a warrant from a judge first would simply introduce an unnecessary complication into the procedure; anyway, there is always a trade-off between preserving freedoms and reducing crime.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the sceptical law lords put the opposite interpretation on the same facts. Just because bugging has gone on for a decade without any legal sanction, that is not a good reason to make it legal now. To them, 1,300 seems an alarmingly large figure, while the scarcity of complaints simply indicates how few people even realise they are being listened to. <font size=-1>MI</font>5 has to get permission from the home secretary to place a bug, whereas police officers will only need to go to their chief constable.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And on top of that inconsistency, an open police search of private property will still require a warrant, but a secret one now will not. As for the argument that applying to a judge would be too complicated, the law lords point out that the police manage to go to judges for certain warrants at the moment, and there is no reason why this should not be extended. Behind all this lies the value the objectors place on privacy, liberty and due process of law. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite these objections, the bill looks set to sail through Parliament, since both the government and opposition support it, and there is not enough cross-bench enthusiasm to scupper it in the Lords. But the issue may come back in a more embarrassing form. Liberty, a civil liberties advocacy group, believes the bill violates provisions on privacy and the right to judicial redress in the European Convention on Human Rights. So Labour, if it forms the next government, might find itself having supported a measure which violates a set of rules it has promised to incorporate into British law.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?850525200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
