<html><head><title>Copywrongs</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Copywrongs</h1>

LIKE Chicken Little waiting for the sky to fall on his head, Internet enthusiasts wander around waiting for the death of the Net. The latest threat comes from the World Intellectual Property Organisation, which is in the middle of a three-week conference to replace the outdated Berne Convention on copyright. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three new treaties are being proposed--two about copyright of music and artistic works (which covers computer software) and one about databases. The supposed danger: the proposed changes will throttle the flow of information on the Internet, end the notion of "fair use" for educational and personal copies, and make companies that provide access to the Internet liable for copyright infringements.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So will the 156 delegates really have choked the Internet by the time they adjourn on December 20th? The answer is no. But the scaremongers include groups as diverse as the American Association for the Advancement of Science and some of America's biggest telephone companies. Most of them are frightened by the idea that temporary copies of documents--created ten-a-penny automatically during Web browsing--should, under the letter of the treaties, be treated as infringements of copyright. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Computer companies have a particular complaint. They are aghast at another article under negotiation, which proposes banning devices that might circumvent copyright-protection systems. As this could conceivably cover a typical multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font> with sufficient brainpower to manipulate sound and video information, it has enraged <font size=-1>IBM</font>, Hewlett-Packard and Compaq. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A total ban on temporary copying is unlikely to survive in the treaty. "No one wants to stop use of the Internet," says Bruce Lehman, the assistant secretary of commerce who heads the American delegation. Some of the criticisms have been addressed: Norway and Israel have suggested amendments tackling temporary copies which (in their roundabout legalese) exclude the sort of incidental copying that occurs during Web browsing. But the central question remains unresolved: how to ensure that copyright is protected as more information travels upon computer networks without unnecessarily draconian measures?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The solution to that is unlikely to come out of Geneva. What may well emerge is a sensible framework around which future protection and exemptions to copyright can be created. The sky may, after all, stay up for a while longer.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
