<html><head><title>Humbled, not hobbled</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Technopolist IBM</b></p>
<h1>Humbled, not hobbled</h1>

<p><b>The days when IBM ruled the computer world are gone, but it still dominates its rich traditional markets. So what happened to the complaints?</b></p><br>
IT WAS not long ago that the name of <font size=-1>IBM</font> was practically synonymous with the word "monopoly". The computer giant's dominance of the mainframe market it created made it one of America's most successful companies. By the early 1980s, pressure from trustbusters had forced it to split off its services arm to stop complaints that it was abusing its dominance. Yet, even as the lawyers were signing the final documents, <font size=-1>IBM</font> was losing its grip: it was being overtaken in the computing marketplace at large by the companies that grew up around the personal computer, a technology launched by <font size=-1>IBM</font> but no longer under its sway.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today, the <font size=-1>PC</font> market is the empire of Microsoft and Intel. But the world mainframe market is still worth a tidy $8 billion a year, and is even growing again. There, <font size=-1>IBM</font> is still as dominant as ever. Despite decades of competition from two Japanese firms, Hitachi and Fujitsu, <font size=-1>IBM</font> has never had less than 70% of the world mainframe market. This year its share will be around 83%, according to Annex Research, a consultancy in Phoenix, Arizona. Its clout has more to do with the nature of the business than with any great technological superiority. Unlike <font size=-1>PC</font>s, mainframes cost millions of dollars each; so decisions, once taken, cost a fortune to reverse. Suppliers and customers therefore tend to mate for life. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dominant though <font size=-1>IBM</font> is in mainframe hardware, it is even more so in software. Indeed, were <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s software division a stand-alone company, it would be by far the biggest software firm in the world. Its mainframe software business is 50% larger than its hardware business, and had revenues of $9.6 billion in 1995 (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). Overall, <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s software sales (including software for minicomputers and <font size=-1>PC</font>s) were worth $12.7 billion last year, almost 50% more than Microsoft's total (see <a href="wb2.gif">table</a>). <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although <font size=-1>IBM</font> is the market leader in most of the software markets it is in, from transaction processing to "groupware" (thanks to its purchase of Lotus and its "Notes" software), it has plenty of competition from other software firms such as Oracle (in databases) and Computer Associates (in system-management software). The one exception is the operating systems that run the machines. Here <font size=-1>IBM</font> has an almost total monopoly--more absolute, indeed, than Microsoft's monopoly on the <font size=-1>PC</font>. <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s <font size=-1>OS/390</font> operating system has almost all the market for <font size=-1>IBM</font>-compatible mainframes outside Japan, where Hitachi and Fujitsu sell their own operating systems.<br>
</p><p><b><b>True Blue</b></b><br>
The Microsoft comparison is apt in some ways. <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s <font size=-1>OS/390</font> business brings in $2 billion a year in annual sales--about the same as Microsoft brings in annually from its Windows family of operating systems for <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Yet there is one big difference between the two: for most of this decade Microsoft has endured almost constant antitrust investigations. <font size=-1>IBM</font>, on the other hand, has had little trouble from the trustbusters this decade: indeed, the 1983 restrictions quietly expired earlier this year. Nobody now seems to worry much about <font size=-1>IBM</font> the monopolist. Why not?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The simple answer is that the mainframe and <font size=-1>PC</font> markets are different. Microsoft's critics have accused it of modifying its Windows operating system to make its own application software look better, thus using its dominance in one market to grab another. True or not, the same accusation is rarely levelled at <font size=-1>IBM</font>. That is because <font size=-1>IBM</font> still sees itself primarily in the business of selling hardware. If it tinkered with its operating system to make it work less well with other firms' programs, its customers might simply stop buying <font size=-1>IBM</font> machines.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, <font size=-1>IBM</font> now has more competition than its market share reveals. This competition is not within the mainframe market, but outside it, in the increasing range of other machines that can do much of what a mainframe does. In the early 1980s, most big companies had little real choice. The <font size=-1>PC</font> was at best an unknown quantity, at worst an underpowered novelty. Minicomputers could not handle enough users. Yet today, top-of-the-range <font size=-1>PC</font>s, connected in "client-server" networks, can do better than both for many jobs. (These networks can even do the jobs of supercomputers: see <a href="st4096.html">page</a>)<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Throughout the first half of the 1990s, this Lilliput-like attack by <font size=-1>PC</font>s drastically reduced demand for mainframes (today sales are at just half their 1989 peak). This drove <font size=-1>IBM</font> almost to bankruptcy. But the company responded by slashing prices and developing new mainframes that shared many of their components (such as memory) with <font size=-1>PC</font>s, thus benefiting from the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry's economies of scale. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These price cuts were felt most strongly in the operating-system market--the one area in which <font size=-1>IBM</font> had appeared to extract monopoly rents. Having first given away its operating-system software for free, <font size=-1>IBM</font> took to charging for it in the 1980s with a vengeance. Prices rose by more than 30% a year for much of the 1980s, says Annex's Bob Djurdjevic, rising 19-fold over the decade. Eventually they reached a point where the average large firm might be paying more than $20,000 a month per mainframe for a licence to use the software, which remained <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s property. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since 1990, when the mainframe market began to slide, this gouging has stopped. Prices have fallen slightly. One prompt came in 1993 when Louis Gerstner became the firm's chief executive: he ordered discounts to spur mainframe sales. But the real reason for the firm's newly competitive prices is the emergence of <font size=-1>PC</font> networks as a threat to the mainframe.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now the company is trying to turn the arrival of networked <font size=-1>PC</font>s to its advantage. The most important part of a networked system is the centralised server that holds collective data and programs. High-end <font size=-1>PC</font>s can serve several dozen users simultaneously within an office, but when companies apply the same principles to their Internet connection, they often find that they need more capacity: customers and sightseers are sure to outnumber employees. <font size=-1>IBM</font> has been quick to remind them that mainframes can accommodate hundreds or thousands of users. To make the point, it now calls its mainframes "superservers".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But to make a pitch for that market, <font size=-1>IBM</font> has had to make its machines talk to other machines more easily. Moving to "open interfaces" such as the Internet's communications standards can give mainframes a new life, but John Thompson, <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s software chief, argues that it also carries a risk. The better a mainframe fits into the rest of the computing world, the more the distinctions between types of machines blur, and the more easily any one can be replaced with another. This competition, argues Mr Thompson, helps keeps <font size=-1>IBM</font> honest: it cannot count on customer loyalty forever.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Mr Thompson puts it, "It's not illegal to be dominant. It's illegal to abuse your dominance." Today, <font size=-1>IBM</font> looks like a model citizen in that respect. It keeps its prices down and its standards largely open. But this kinder, gentler <font size=-1>IBM</font> is a creature of pragmatism, chastened by its brush with bankruptcy. The markets it dominates are blurring into markets where it has hardly any share at all. If <font size=-1>IBM</font> looks like a benevolent monopoly today, that may be because the company is seeing its dominant position being eroded from the outside. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?850525200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
