<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/14-12-96/st4096.html 199.173.162.110 19970113135226 text/html 7641
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 13:48:21 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 12-Dec-96 17:08:10 GMT
Content-length: 7456
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Divide and conquer</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Supercomputers</b></p>
<h1>Divide and conquer</h1>

<p><b>Might a network of personal computers prove to be as formidable a number- cruncher as a supercomputer?</b></p><br>
THE rapacious curve of Moore's Law (expounded by Gordon Moore, the co-founder of Intel) states that the density of components on a silicon chip doubles every 18 months. Thus, today's <font size=-1>PC</font>s are faster and cheaper than last year's models and will, no doubt, look clunky and over-priced compared with next year's.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, some computing tasks will still stump tomorrow's desktop computers. The reason is simply one of speed. Some jobs (such as forecasting the weather and modelling nuclear explosions) require astronomical numbers of calculations. Performing them on a <font size=-1>PC</font> is possible in theory--but the result would arrive several million years after the weather it was intended to forecast or the war it was meant to forestall. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the moment these sorts of chores can be carried out only by giant supercomputers. These are far quicker, but also much more expensive. For instance, America's Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (which, since the moratorium on real nuclear explosions, is restricted to testing bombs in cyberspace) recently ordered a new supercomputer from <font size=-1>IBM</font> that will be able to do 3 trillion numerical calculations per second. The best desktop <font size=-1>PC</font>s can barely produce one ten-thousandth of that. But 10,000 desktop <font size=-1>PC</font>s cost less than $20m. <font size=-1>IBM</font> is charging $93m for its machine.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ideal solution, then, would be to link lots of small <font size=-1>PC</font>s so that they can perform bigger tasks together (especially as many <font size=-1>PC</font>s are idle for much of the day). At first sight this seems a simple matter of replicating a machine that already has several brains. Many of the latest supercomputers are not the single-processor machines that Seymour Cray, the doyen of the subject, once made so famous. They are "parallel computers": linked arrays of microprocessors (or "nodes") similar to those that lie at the heart of humble desktop drudges.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, making a parallel computer out of linked <font size=-1>PC</font>s instead of nodes all linked inside the same box is tricky. To begin with, the number of nodes matters (regardless of whether they are housed in one box or spread out across a network). A calculation designed to run on a computer with, say, 64 nodes typically has to be rewritten for a computer with 128 nodes. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difficulty lies in the software. Breaking a problem into meaningful sub-problems, allocating them to different processors, co-ordinating the processors so that the answers come out in the correct order, and then stitching the sub-answers together to arrive at a conclusion, is a programming nightmare. Programming the largest of the modern parallel supercomputers, with up to 2,048 nodes, is ghastly. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Programmers, though, are rising to the challenge. In the summer of 1995 around 200 volunteers co-ordinated by Piete Brooks, at the University of Cambridge, deciphered a message encrypted using a secret code. They employed a motley assortment of machines, including Apple Macintoshes, "Windows"-based <font size=-1>PC</font>s and Hewlett-Packard workstations, to break the code in 32 hours. A single <font size=-1>PC</font> would have taken 200 times as long to do it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the problem solved by Dr Brooks and his crew was not that difficult. It was "loosely coupled": the crackers knew that the secret code had to be just one of 1,099,511,627,776 combinations. All they needed to do was work through each one until someone reached the answer. The more volunteers, the sooner the answer could be expected to arrive.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, dividing most problems into separate chunks is less easy: the result from one part of, say, a weather forecast affects the result in another part. This is why the programs used to solve such "tightly-coupled" problems have to know in advance how many processors are available, what they are, and how they speak to each other. And, in tightly-coupled problems, the speed (or lack of it) at which processors can communicate is a serious constraint--the networks connecting <font size=-1>PC</font>s can significantly slow down inter-processor chats.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the University of Virginia in Charlottesville, Andrew Grimshaw reckons he is close to solving these difficulties. His system, Legion, is an attempt to build a "virtual" parallel computer across the Internet. Legion's particular strength is that it can co-ordinate several different types of computers, including old-style supercomputers, modern parallel computers, workstations and desktop <font size=-1>PC</font>s. The existing system at the University of Virginia, for instance, uses more than 100 computers from several different manufacturers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Legion also looks like a single computer to its users. A set of programs, which Dr Grimshaw calls "metasystems software", hides the quirks of its constituent machines and the network connecting them. Instead, Legion works out where and when to perform particular calculations on its network. To reduce delays in communications between processors, Legion prefers its machines to have fast network connections (some of them use a proprietary system 80 times faster than a typical university network). If, however, such connections are not available, it will simply change the order in which it processes particular requests so as to minimise delays. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dr Grimshaw's approach does not produce a computer that is as well-designed for solving tightly-coupled problems as a normal parallel computer. All the same, Legion has been used successfully to solve fluid-dynamics calculations--classic examples of tightly-coupled problems--which are generally difficult for networks of workstations to manage. Biochemists at the University of Virginia have been able to enlist Legion's help to discover the structure of new proteins. And above all, unlike a real supercomputer, Legion can easily grow: each new <font size=-1>PC</font> adds a little bit more to its virtual power. Sometimes the best way to become faster is to grow slowly.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?850525200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a>
</p>
