<html><head><title>The real slick Willie</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The real slick Willie</h1>

IN THE middle of November, Willie Brown apologised. It made headlines. The mayor of San Francisco had called Elvis Grbac, a quarterback in the 49ers football team, "an embarrassment to humankind" for the way he was playing, ignoring the fact that Mr Grbac had problems at home that were distracting him. San Franciscans were appalled at the mayor's disloyalty to the home team, and the mayor--hot back from a trip to Paris-- went to the practice field to say he was sorry in person. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This was uncharacteristic. Ever since he became mayor in January this year, Mr Brown has been so lionised that his occasionally brutal remarks have gone almost unnoticed. Nobody much minded when he accused California's attorney-general of "Gestapo tactics" for busting a marijuana shop on Market Street, or when he cancelled a conference on the homeless at the last minute on the ground that homeless activists were going to try to steamroller him. Certainly no apology was needed. His approval ratings in San Francisco have been consistently higher than 70%. He has been on the cover of <i>Newsweek</i>, together with Rudolph Giuliani of New York, as one of "the 25 most dynamic mayors in America"; and he has been in a fashion advertisement in <i>Esquire</i>, confidently perched on a motorbike. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why has Mr Brown been getting all this national attention and local affection? A one-word answer: style. Mr Brown has bags of it, and he knows how to put it on public display. Whereas Mr Giuliani is racked by jealousy, and Richard Daley of Chicago is about as interesting as a city budget, Mr Brown is everybody's favourite dinner companion. He dresses impeccably, in $400 shoes, starched shirts and $3,000 Armani or Brioni suits. (A local joke has it that San Franciscans think Brioni is Italian for brown.) "Da Mayor", as he likes to call himself, is an incessant socialiser, moving easily between black-tie functions on Nob Hill and block parties in the Tenderloin; he is also a regular feature of the city's night clubs and restaurants, with a table permanently reserved at the Top of the Mark. In a city that thinks of itself as the embodiment of style, all this goes down like a dream. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Brown has a raffish side to him too, which also matches San Francisco's image of itself. He was recently given the Cancer Society's Humanitarian of the Year award, despite having received more money in campaign contributions from cigarette companies than any other politician in America, including Jesse Helms. He squires a succession of beautiful women around town, despite being married with three children. On becoming mayor he complained that it was impossible to live on his salary of $140,000 a year, and the parties he throws are fabulous. For his inauguration he invited 100,000 people, sweet-talked 70 restaurants into donating food, set up soup kitchens all over the city, and hired Huey Lewis and Santana to play. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, Mr Brown is an American success story. He was born into a chaotic family in a segregated town in Texas and started work as a shoe-shine boy; yet he rose to become speaker of the Assembly in the nation's most populous state and then mayor of its most beautiful city. He also has luck on his side. Just as term limits were about to end his career in the state legislature, the job of mayor of San Francisco fell vacant. When it looked as if San Francisco was having second thoughts about embracing a flashy political boss as its mayor, his chief opponent, Frank Jordan, decided to liven up his image by appearing naked in a shower with two disc-jockeys, killing his campaign dead. San Francisco's recent economic recovery has also meant that Mr Brown has been able to avoid bringing in the job cuts and tax increases that had become routine in recent years. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet luck and style are not all the city needs. San Francisco has the highest proportion of <font size=-1>HIV</font>-positive people in the country, a dismally visible homeless problem, and a chaotic transport system. Culturally, the city is an island of 1960s liberalism in an increasingly conservative country. Mr Brown seems to represent the most irresponsible side of his city: San Franciscans, having realised that their problems are intractable, have decided to have a party. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the surface, that charge may seem hard. Mr Brown has attacked the jobs-for-life system that clogs up the city's bureaucracy; he has got rid of several notoriously incompetent officials, some of them black; he has handed over the running of the housing department and the probation service to the federal government (though without much choice), and he has improved safety on the buses by using reformed gang members as guardian angels. Above all, he has inspired a new enthusiasm for civic affairs. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Brown clearly relishes the process of politics far more than the humdrum business of administration. He loves playing interest groups off against each other and brokering deals between them. (This is, after all, the man whom Bill Clinton complimented as being "the real slick Willie".) Boasting better national connections than most other mayors, he has brought a cavalcade of Clinton cabinet members through the city; he is also hand in glove with Diane Feinstein, one of the state's senators. He understands the importance of projecting a positive image of the city, and this is good; but the running of any city cannot be simply a process of cocky salesmanship.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A year into his term, Mr Brown's plans to reform the city's management are little more than clich&eacute;s. He has neither Mr Giuliani's ability to think the unthinkable--that the tide of crime and casual lawlessness that was engulfing New York could be reversed--nor Mr Daley's relentless appetite for detail. Part of him still clearly dismisses his job as nothing but "street lights, dog doo and parking meters". A little more appetite for the daily realities of city life would do Mr Brown no harm. And a little humility, as seen unexpectedly on the 49ers' practice field, might make a good basis on which to start.<br>

<p align=center>
