<html><head><title>Reading, writing and writs</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Litigation</b></p>
<h1>Reading, writing and writs</h1>

IF LITTLE Johnny flunked his exams, his parents used to send him to his room in disgrace. Now they send for the lawyers. As two 17-year-olds who got lousy <font size=-1>GCSE</font> results began proceedings against their school, teachers trembled at the thought of a flood of litigation.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the British public, after years of pooh-poohing the Americans for demanding millions of dollars for being scalded by a cup of coffee, seems to think it is not such a bad idea. Despite the government's efforts to restrict legal aid for personal-injury actions, the gross bill in England and Wales for such suits rose from &#163;77m in 1991-92 to &#163;200m in 1994-95. However, damages are not yet American-style: judges, who try most British actions, do not award the astronomic sums handed out by American juries.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government is partly responsible for this development. By promoting the Citizens' Charters and pushing public services to publish performance records, it has supported the idea that those who do not meet measurable standards, such as school league tables, should pay compensation. In the exam case, the lawyer, Jack Rabinowicz, will draw on inspection reports which said their two schools had failed to provide an acceptable standard of education.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The exam case is also the consequence of judgments by the House of Lords. In July 1995, in three cases concerning the special needs of dyslexic children, their lordships decided that schools and local education authorities could be sued for failing to carry out their duty of care. Mr Rabinowicz subsequently won a &#163;30,000 out-of-court settlement last month for an ex-pupil bullied for three years at a school in London.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where does this trend lead? Litigation leads to insurance, which risks driving some businesses to the wall. Parts of America, for instance, are short of obstetricians because the risks of litigation have made delivering babies prohibitively expensive. But in moderate doses, it may be beneficial. So, anyway, argues Peter Watson, a Glasgow lawyer who acted for the relatives of victims of the Piper Alpha oil platform disaster and the Lockerbie air disaster. He says that American-style lawsuits are an effective force for change. "The traditional British method of forming a committee, passing a few health and safety regulations which fine a defaulting company tuppence-halfpenny, is a waste of time," he says. In both cases, he says, the companies ignored regulations and safety procedures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The threat of litigation is raising the costs of bad decision-making, but it does not necessarily make it clearer how people should do their jobs. Environmental health officials delayed publishing lists of shops selling meat which caused the current food poisoning outbreak in Lanarkshire, fearing legal action by a wrongly-identified shop. Health officials, more concerned to stop the death toll (seven by December 5th) from the <i>E. coli</i> 0157 bug, over-ruled them.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The courts may eventually decide who was right. On December 4th, lawyers acting for seven children in Stoke-on-Trent poisoned by <i>E. coli</i> in a separate incident said they were going to sue the government for not properly publicising information about the bug.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
