<html><head><title>Crippling?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Disability law</b></p>
<h1>Crippling?</h1>

WHEN America passed the Americans with Disabilities Act in 1990, sceptics said it should really be called the lawyers' retirement act. The language was a lawyers' dream: it included such notions as common sense, reasonable accommodation, essential functions, undue hardship and readily achievable goals. Businessmen predicted a litigation nightmare.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain's Disability Discrimination Act has come into force this week, and many British businessmen have similar fears. Some disability campaigners, meanwhile, have been protesting that it does not go far enough. The American experience suggests that the disabled will end up better off than they were, though not completely satisfied, and the new regulations will not prove too burdensome to business.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both the American law and the British one prohibit discrimination against disabled people in hiring, firing and promotion. This in effect extends civil rights protections to the disabled. The laws also require restaurants, shops, libraries and so on to make efforts to serve the disabled-- perhaps by reading out the menu to blind diners. Both laws are intentionally vague: the idea was to establish broad principles.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem, say American businessmen, is that they don't know how they are required to respond until they are hit with a complaint. A survey in 1995 of 35,000 employers by the National Federation of Independent Business found that two-thirds wanted the law clarified. For instance, the definition of disability remains murky. Some 49m Americans--or more than one in six--are considered disabled under the act, an implausible figure. Among those included are former drug addicts, a categorisation employers dispute, and there is worry that the obese and smell-sensitive will litigate their way in as well.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A second complaint is that some regulations are too broad. The Los Angeles school district, for example, hesitated to fire a teacher who had killed a woman and spent ten years in a hospital for the criminally insane: under the law, former mental illness is not a ground for firing. There is also concern that the "reasonable accommodation" standard can be unreasonably applied. A self-serve car wash in Michigan had to install a $12,000 lavatory for the handicapped, even though the site is visited by employees for only half an hour a week.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the feared litigation frenzy has simply not happened; the Department of Labour records 650 suits nationwide in the first five years. Moreover, the experience has been that much "reasonable accommodation" is cheap and easy--putting a desk up on bricks, perhaps, or installing large-print software. Employment rates in America among disabled people have been increasing. The act can probably take some credit for that.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849920400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
