</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Jubilation?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif"
width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0> <p><font size=-1> These
articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition
only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK
editions. </font></p></td><td></td> <td align=right valign=top><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39"
alt="The Economist" border=0> </td></tr></table>

<p><b>London's development</b></p> <h1>Jubilation?</h1>

WHEN the Docklands development crashed in the early 1990s, investors
blamed the lack of proper infrastructure. Narrow roads, the tiny
capacity of the Docklands Light Railway (<font size=-1>DLR</font>) and
the encircling Thames had, developers said, left large-scale commercial
or residential complexes too inaccessible to be attractive. The
government's response, along with an upgrade for the <font
size=-1>DLR</font> and a revamping of the roads, was a rambling
extension of London Underground's Jubilee line from the West End to
south and east London.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The
construction of the Jubilee line extension, the biggest development in
the capital's transport system for over two decades, has clogged
London's traffic for a year and maddened Londoners. Now that it is
nearing completion, however, things seem to be looking up for the
Docklands.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Office occupancy has risen
from 62% in 1993 to 75% this year. In the riverside area of Southwark,
where four of the 11 new Jubilee line stops will be located, the number
of planning permissions granted has tripled since 1992. Housing sales
have hit their highest level since the 1980s. Chic waterside apartments
now routinely sell a year before their scheduled completion. Citibank
and <i>Readers</i>' <i>Digest </i>are moving to Canary Wharf. Add the
extra impetus of the Jubilee's arrival in March 1998 to falling
unemployment and rising rents, and it looks as though Docklands is
poised for a second 1980s-style boom.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Docklands today is not the wasteland
it was in the early 1980s, when Tower Hamlets had a higher proportion of
residents in public housing than did the Soviet Union. The London
Docklands Development Corporation (<font size=-1>LDDC</font>), set up by
the government to by-pass left-wing councils and promote private-sector
development, once owned swathes of derelict land. Now, the only large
vacant tracts are in the remote Royal Docks (see <a
href="br2.gif">map</a>).<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the
Victoria line came to Brixton in 1971, the increased accessibility sent
property prices soaring. But along the Jubilee's route through Southwark
a sea of dilapidated council estates rubs shoulders with cheap and
cheerful low-cost housing built by the <font size=-1>LDDC</font> as a
sop to local objections that it was doing nothing for the poor. It is
not the stuff of estate agents' fantasies.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Surely, if property prices soar, all this
could be replaced by higher-value housing? It could, except that
planning authority in Docklands will soon revert from the <font
size=-1>LDDC</font> to the local borough councils. Southwark takes over
Surrey Quays later this month, and Tower Hamlets regains the Isle of
Dogs next year.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All the local councils
are Labour. The hard left has mostly gone; and council officials,
between enthusiastic references to "housing choice", "efficiency" and
plans to eliminate 95% of unnecessary bollards, privately welcome any
scheme which will bring wealthier residents to areas which are still
among the poorest in London. But indigenous Docklanders have always been
suspicious of East London's gentrification. One popular grafitto
rechristens the <font size=-1>LDDC</font> "Locals Don't Dig Cobbles".
Local politicians cannot publicly support replacing poor people's
housing with houses and offices for the rich.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, local residents will benefit
from better transport. Local businesses are less certain to. Good
transport can bring people into an area; but, as Brixton learned, it can
also free them to do their shopping elsewhere. Brixton's shopping centre
died once the Victoria line shipped people off to Oxford Circus.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The one sure winner from the Jubilee line
extension is Canary Wharf. The new station there will handle over 15,000
people every hour at peak times, with capacity for many more. The
current owner of the Canary Wharf development, International Property
Corporation, not only stands to see the value of the existing complex
increase; roughly 8m of the 10m square feet of office space in the area
with planning permission are in two further planned towers on the
development.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Seeing Canary Wharf's
huge potential profit from the Tube access, the government insisted in
1993 that the then owners pay &#163;398m towards the projected &#163;1.2
billion cost of construction. But although Canary Wharf's contribution,
spread out over 25 years from 1998, will be hugely discounted by
inflation, the cost of the extension has risen to &#163;2.6 billion in
today's money. It has proved an expensive way of remedying an
embarrassing failure.<br> <br>

