<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>On track</b> &nbsp; Eurotunnel restarted some passenger services between London, Paris and Brussels using only one of its two rail tunnels under the Channel. Repairs to the other tunnel, which was damaged by fire in November, will take six months. Full freight services will not resume until the cause of the fire has been established.
<p><b>Down and out</b> &nbsp; Kensington and Chelsea Conservative Association dropped Sir Nicholas Scott, a former minister, as their parliamentary candidate. Police had found him face-down on the pavement during the Conservative party conference in Bournemouth in October. He will remain an <font size=-1>MP</font> until the general election.<br>
<p><b>Dearer loans</b> &nbsp; Abbey National announced it would raise its mortgage rates by a quarter of a point. Three other building societies followed suit, but the largest, the Halifax, held steady.<br>
<p><b>Deadly outbreak</b> &nbsp; Four students died of meningitis at three different universities in England and Wales. Eight more cases have been diagnosed.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Youth wins jackpot</b> &nbsp; Labour proposes to add young people to the list of good causes helped by profits from the National Lottery. Jack Cunningham, the shadow national heritage secretary, suggested spending the &#163;250m currently allocated to the Millennium Fund each year on children after the millennium celebrations have ended.<br>
<p><b>Artful</b> &nbsp; Sir Denis Mahon, an art collector, offered to donate Italian baroque paintings worth &#163;25m to the National Art Collections Fund, on condition that the museums which house them never sell anything from their permanent collections.<br>
<p><b>Watered down</b> &nbsp; The new owners of Southern Water, Scottish Power, announced plans to cut staff by 2,000 and increase profits by &#163;50m.<br>
<p><b>Piddling offence</b> &nbsp; Suffolk police detained a couple of Dutch yachters for breaking quarantine rules by allowing their dog ashore to relieve itself.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

