<html><head><title>Germany's Herr Handy</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table
width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26"
alt="Business" border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Germany's Herr Handy</h1>

<p><b>Is a pinch of telecoms enough to spice up an old-fashioned, feudal European conglomerate? Georg
Obermeier hopes so</b></p><br> ONE of the more fashionable things to do if you are a slightly stodgy but
rich European utility is to branch out into telecoms of one sort or another. It is not just that the phone
market seems to be growing whilst most other public services look a little sluggish. It is also a question of
sex appeal: who wants to be in the boring old business of delivering electricity, pumping water or bringing
commuters to work when there are things like satellite telephony and multimedia in the air? And, even if it
takes a little time to make money, there is always the hope that some of that snazzy new culture will infect
the more dowdy parts of your organisation.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this explains
why Britain's regional electricity companies have got together to form Energis, a telecoms firm that uses
their lines. A group of the continent's national railways have set up Hermes, a telecoms consortium.
Compagnie G&eacute;n&eacute;rale des Eaux, a French water company, is also now in the telecoms
business. But few are pushing in as aggressively as Georg Obermeier, the irascible 55-year-old Bavarian
who runs <font size=-1>VIAG</font>.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In many ways <font
size=-1>VIAG</font> is a caricature of a regional monopoly. Although it was privatised in 1986, its largest
shareholder is the Bavarian state government, and it makes most of its money from electricity generation
in that state. Now it is run very much as a personal fief by Mr Obermeier (his latest "disagreement" was
with his finance director, whom he has not yet replaced). Mr Obermeier has helped tighten up <font
size=-1>VIAG</font>'s finances (its head office has only 100 people); but it is still a sprawling group with
interests in businesses like packaging and freight. The performance of <font size=-1>VIAG</font>'s shares
has lagged behind those of both <font size=-1>RWE</font> and Veba, two other utility-based German
conglomerates that have been more aggressive about reshuffling their business (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now Mr Obermeier scents salvation in his country's notoriously
poorly-served telecoms market, which is still largely monopolised by Deutsche Telekom. Although Germans
flocked to buy shares in the company when it was partially privatised last month, they are disenchanted
customers. Many would switch to another telephone company, especially one offering lower prices and
greater flexibility. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>VIAG</font> hopes to woo
them through mobile telephony. Germany's internationally minded businessfolk have given their favourite
gadget an English name: <i>das Handy</i> is the German for mobile phone. Handy they may be, cheap they
are not. A talkative business user can expect to pay around DM487 ($311) a month, according to Analysys,
a consultancy; his British counterpart would shell out only &#163;85 ($140). Mr Obermeier wants to
change this. He aims to make the gadget into a <i>Volkshandy</i>--cheap enough to tempt millions of
households to abandon conventional phone lines altogether.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>VIAG</font> is set to get its mobile phone licence in
February, in a joint venture with Britain's <font size=-1>BT</font>. It will begin operating in early 1998,
just when Germany's telephone market is due to be liberalised. Its strategy should give it a head start:
while other new entrants are having to use Deutsche Telekom's local circuits, at great expense--or, even
more expensively, dig up the streets to put in new lines--<font size=-1>VIAG</font> will avoid all this
trouble by using wireless transmission rather than cables. Even better, it will be using a higher radio
frequency than its mobile competitors, meaning better-quality sound and greater capacity (which will be
useful for customers using modems and other gadgets). And whereas its rivals are putting their main effort
into setting up new long-distance networks, <font size=-1>VIAG</font> will save money by renting what it
needs.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <font size=-1>VIAG</font>'s advantages may look
more slender as the months go by. Belatedly, a price war is now raging in mobile phones, between
Mannesmann, a big engineering company which has already thrashed Deutsche Telekom to become market
leader, and the third network, <font size=-1>E</font>-Plus, which has several owners including Veba. By
early 1998, <font size=-1>VIAG</font>'s promised cut-price rates will probably look less spectacular.
Meanwhile, the price of ordinary telephony will also probably fall, as Deutsche Telekom comes under
pressure from <font size=-1>RWE</font> and Veba. Much will depend on the expertise of <font
size=-1>VIAG</font>'s British partner and on how Mr Obermeier's somewhat feudal management style
adapts to the task.<br> </p><p><b><b>A sideshow with a meaning</b></b><br> Mr Obermeier's advance
into telecoms has all the makings of an exciting tussle. But <font size=-1>VIAG</font> shareholders might
wonder whether he is putting too much effort into the project. In five years' time, telecoms are expected to
contribute sales of only DM2 billion, rising to DM5.5 billion by 2008. By contrast, group sales for 1996 are
forecast at some DM43.8 billion, most of which comes from electricity. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From this perspective, the foray into telecoms might indeed help
spice up some of <font size=-1>VIAG</font>'s other businesses (trying to wrest the cellular telephony
business from Mannesmann will be a far more cut-throat affair than, say, selling nuclear power in
Bavaria). But <font size=-1>VIAG</font> is in so many businesses that it is hard to see how all of them can
be infused with this entrepreneurial spirit. And the telecoms fuss may prove a distraction to the harsher
matter of selling off its more lacklustre businesses and, perhaps (whisper it very quietly), making <font
size=-1>VIAG</font>'s boss a little more accountable. The leonine Mr Obermeier's eyes glint dangerously
as the topic of his management style is raised. "Very fast decisions are the key to our success," he purrs.
The telecoms battle will be a good test of that.<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
