<html><head><title>Where are they now?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Where are they now?</h1>

<font size=1>LOS ANGELES</font><p>
AS THE second Simpson trial gathers pace, we catch up on the careers of the leading players in the first: <ul><p>
<b>The "dream team" of defence lawyers</b> has broken up.<b> Johnnie Cochran </b>thrives, trotting the world giving lectures on civil rights and appearing endlessly on radio and television. He is the author of "Journey to Justice", and his legal career booms. <b>Robert Shapiro </b>has tried to reintegrate himself into the white world of west Los Angeles. His recent book, "The Search for Justice", elaborates his thesis that "not only did we play the race card, we dealt it from the bottom of the deck." The two men no longer talk.<p>
<b>Marcia Clark</b>, the leading prosecutor, received a $4m advance for a book on the trial. This is believed to be the third-biggest non-fiction advance in publishing. <br>
<b> </b><br>
<b>Lance Ito, </b>the judge, continues to try cases. His second most famous case also ended in disaster: a federal judge overturned the conviction in California of Charles Keating, a financier involved in the S & L debacle of the 1980s, because Judge Ito instructed the jury erroneously.<p>
<b>Kato Kaelin</b>, the house-guest whose name became synonymous with freeloading, has acquired a fan club and become a talk-show star. To judge from his evidence in the current trial, he has also learned how to use verbs. <p>
The <b>Ford Bronco</b> has been put up for auction, but was priced too high and attracted no bidders.</ul><br>

