<html><head><title>Consuming passion</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The economy</b></p>
<h1>Consuming passion</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
THE Thanksgiving turkey digested, Americans perform a favourite rite: they go shopping. The day after Thanksgiving marks the beginning of the retailers' holiday season, the busiest shopping day of the year. But are Americans today in the mood to consume?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much hangs on the answer to this question. After spending furiously during the first half of the year, consumers suddenly held back over the summer. Since consumer spending--on everything from cars to haircuts--makes up around two-thirds of overall demand, the result was a sharp slowing in the economy's pace. According to the Commerce Department's latest estimate, released on November 27th, America's <font size=-1>GDP</font> rose by an annualised 2% between July and September, well below the booming 4.7% of the second quarter. Were it not for a sizeable rise in business inventories, the growth rate would have slipped further. Whether this was simply a much-needed moderation of pace or the beginning of a more marked slowdown depends a great deal on what American consumers do over the next few months. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are several reasons to expect consumption to recover. Unemployment remains extraordinarily low, and real incomes are rising strongly. Wall Street is also behaving spectacularly: the Dow Jones Industrial Average has risen 8% since the election alone, and is up 70% since the beginning of last year (see <a href="fn6502.html">page</a>). Higher share prices make shareholders feel richer, and perhaps inclined to spend more. In the past two years the soaring stockmarket has added more than $2.3 trillion to household portfolios. Although most of these shares are held by the richest, millions of ordinary Americans now have mutual funds and retirement accounts. A boom on Wall Street could therefore affect consumption more than it used to.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, people say they are confident. The two indices of consumer confidence most closely watched by economists both show Americans feeling bouncy. The Michigan index of consumer sentiment, released earlier in November, has hit its highest level since 1986. The Conference Board survey on consumer confidence (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>) shows that Americans are more upbeat about current business conditions than at any time in the 1990s, although they are slightly more worried about the future. Put these factors together, the optimists argue, and you will get exactly the kind of moderate rise in consumption the economy needs for "Goldilocks growth"--not too fast and not too slow. Although the actual fourth-quarter <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth figures may look anaemic as firms reduce some unwanted inventory, the stage will be set for the expansion to continue into the indefinite future.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not everyone shares that view. Pessimists point to the fact that consumers are heavily indebted and the growth of new consumer credit has been slowing. Both factors might suggest that Americans will save rather than spend more. This analysis is right, to a point. Total household debt (including mortgages and other consumer credit) now amounts to 84 cents out of every dollar of after-tax personal income, the highest level ever. More important than the stock of debt is the burden of servicing it. Measured correctly this, too, is high. For example, many Americans now lease their cars rather than buying them. Including car-lease payments as well as car-loan instalments brings total household debt service to 18 cents out of every dollar of income, about the same as it was at its peak in 1989. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Less clear, however, is how far all this debt will weaken consumption. Debts have been rising for some time, but did little to dampen demand earlier this year. A greater risk is that consumption may rebound too strongly, pushing the economy to grow too quickly. Any sign of rapid acceleration or whiff of inflation might prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates, a move some people had expected in September. That is something that financial markets and most Americans have stopped worrying about. They may come to regret that.<br>

<p align=center>
