<html><head><title>Fissiparous fortunes and  family feuds</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Fissiparous fortunes and  family feuds</h1>

<font size=1>HONG KONG</font><p>
<p><b>As Asia's business empires have grown and diversified, many have begun to  hit the limits of the founding family's ability to manage. But for the moment,  family squabbles are just as likely to split them as business logic</b></p><br>
FAMILIES are the bedrock of Asian business. Paternalistic firms have carefully cultivated their personal connections, darted into every business opportunity and amassed some of the world's largest fortunes by assembling some of the world's most convoluted conglomerates. But as competition increases, the pressures for change are growing. From South Korea to Indonesia, Asian families are now thinking about restructuring their empires. Some have already begun.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A spate of listings on Hong Kong's roaring stockmarket has shown that some of the region's businessmen are now willing to split up their conglomerates. In October New World Development, a listed property, hotels and telecoms giant controlled by the Cheng family, floated off a separate company called New World Infrastructure. Its shares have soared and the Chengs are now considering listings for a construction firm and also for their property business in China.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Are the Chengs simply cashing in on a bull market? No, says Henry Cheng, the group's managing director. The intention is to give subsidiaries managerial and financial independence, allowing New World Development to concentrate on what he describes as its "core activity", investing in the Hong Kong property market.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other Hong Kong tycoons are thinking in this way. On November 29th Citybus, one of the more profitable bus companies in the colony, will be spun off from <font size=-1>CNT</font>, a listed firm controlled by the Tsui family, who aim to concentrate more on expanding their large but loss-making paint business. In December, the family owners of Tem Fat Hing Fung, a big listed jewellery maker and property developer, will obtain a separate listing for their gold-bullion business. They believe that splitting the company will make it simpler for investors to understand (see <a href="wb8480.html">page</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Interest in restructuring and reducing the portfolio of family businesses has spread to Taiwan, too, according to Chu Tian-cho of the Hong Kong office of McKinsey, a firm of management consultants. One reason companies hesitate, says Mr Chu, is that they dread making workers redundant. In a family-run firm, both workers and owners tend to assume that jobs are guaranteed for life. Families hate being seen to abandon that guarantee. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even South Korea's conglomerates, known as the <i>chaebol</i>, have begun spinning off subsidiaries. On November 20th Hyundai listed its electronics division, one of the world's biggest producers of memory chips. It followed a similar listing by the electronics division of the <font size=-1>LG</font> group. The subsidiaries of many other South Korean firms are starting to lead lives increasingly independent of their parent companies-- and even of their founding families.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the moment, though, most Asian businessmen believe the conglomerate is well suited to the region. A big group, they reckon, has more clout with governments, which in Asia still dole out many lucrative business concessions. Diversification, they add, permits a firm to take risks (and gain rewards) it might not otherwise have been able to afford. Could Samsung, they ask, have gone into the car business if it had not already been one of South Korea's biggest groups? Or could Charoen Pokphand, an enormous company from Bangkok, have become one of China's biggest foreign investors if the family-run firm had not previously diversified from chicken feed into myriad activities ranging from pot noodles to motorcycles?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Scepticism about the value of core businesses is particularly rife among the ethnic Chinese who migrated to East Asia from the mainland. They founded most of the region's largest conglomerates, and many still run the companies they created. These so-called "overseas Chinese" dominate the ranks of the region's billionaires. They control eight out of ten of Indonesia's top companies, for instance; a similar proportion of Thailand's leading firms; and numerous corporate giants in the Philippines. They are also the biggest investors in China. <br>
</p><p><b><b>Bamboo network</b></b><br>
In these businesses, the family is particularly strong. There may be a veneer of modern corporate governance, but contracts can be sealed by a handshake without a lawyer, accountant or consultant in sight. And even though parts of the family group may be listed on one or more of the region's stockmarkets, most of the really lucrative bits are still closely held. Assets are shuffled at will. Published sets of consolidated accounts are as rare as rickshaws. Harvard Business School gurus may preach that Asian conglomerates are doomed to become bit-players in the global marketplace unless they specialise in a core activity. Chinese patriarchs ignore them.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dominance of the family endures because, whatever the gurus say, the system works--up to a point. Even the most patriarchal overseas-Chinese firm is a "fast and extremely efficient opportunity-seeking machine," says Gordon Redding, a professor of management studies at the University of Hong Kong. The firms are not burdened with bureaucracy. They have fast and inexpensive access to market intelligence and investment cash through a "bamboo network" of relatives and business contacts. Yet the limits to the family conglomerate are the size and complexity of the business it can manage. Those limits are starting to matter more.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of Asia's business empires have begun to outgrow the ability of their founder to manage them, as they become ever more complicated to run. The need to delegate is urgent, but the patriarch is often unwilling or unable to do so; and even the largest family has only so many sons and cousins capable of managing, and only so many management slots they can usefully fill.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, it is because Chinese businesses find it so hard to separate management from ownership that they tend to avoid industries that require the complex integration of many different skills, such as car making or aerospace. These businesses require a great deal of delegation in order to encourage the talent needed to research and develop new products, organise large numbers of subcontractors and plan international marketing campaigns. There are simply too many important decisions for family members to take on their own. Although some South Korean, Malaysian and Indonesian groups have ventured into such industries (well protected by import barriers), Chinese entrepreneurs would rather stick to what Professor Redding calls "machine bureaucracies": businesses such as property, shipping, hotels, and telecoms which are easier to run.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even here, though, many of Asia's family-run conglomerates are building an internal lobby for change, as they acquire a cadre of professional, western-educated managers. More and more Asian managers, including the sons (and occasionally daughters) of the owners, have been to American business schools. South Korea's <i>chaebol</i> have recently been energetically recruiting business-school graduates, whatever their nationality. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But in the end, the main threat to Asia's family-run conglomerates may be something much more old-fashioned: succession squabbles. Sometimes, the handover goes smoothly: Anthony Salim, the youngest son of 79-year-old Liem Sioe Liong, a Chinese migrant who built Indonesia's Salim group into one of the region's biggest conglomerates, is taking charge of that empire. And in Hong Kong, even 68-year-old Mr Li Ka-shing, the colony's best-known tycoon, is talking of retiring in 1988 and handing on his flagship company, Cheung Kong, to his eldest son, Victor.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet even Asia's supposedly strong "family values" cannot guarantee that a business will survive in the same family beyond the third generation. Some may not get even that far. In Taiwan, the family that controls the country's biggest company, Formosa Plastics, is embroiled in a vicious feud. It began a year ago when the firm's elderly founder, Wang Yung-ching, banished Winston, his eldest son and heir apparent, from the company for 12 months for allegedly having an extramarital affair. The thrice-married Wang <i>p&egrave;re</i> now seems intent on extending the ban, even if it tears the firm apart. Family feuds are not something management gurus know much about.<br>
<br>

