<html><head><title>Glittering prizes</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Glittering prizes</h1>

<font size=1>HONG KONG</font><p>
ONE day in 1946 Chan Muk-tim, a merchant sailor, visited a gold mine while on shore leave in South Africa. Ignoring the order to extinguish cigarettes, Chan held his cigarette, cupped, worker's style, in his palm. It took so long to reach the bottom of the shaft that the cigarette had burnt down to his fingers. If people went to such lengths to mine such small amounts of gold, he thought, it must be a commodity worth having. Three years later, he started a gold business that is now one of Asia's biggest. That business, Tem Fat Hing Fung, has been the best-performing share on Hong Kong's roaring stockmarket this year, rising fourfold in price.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now run by Chan Muk-tim's two sons, the company has thrived in the confluence of two trends. People in Asia have developed a seemingly insatiable desire to possess ever more gold. At the same time, the world's central banks are keeping more of their reserves in interest-bearing bonds. As they have dumped their unwanted gold on the market, dealers such as Tem Fat Hing Fung (the name means Bountiful Increase) have been snapping them up. "Gold", says Tem Fat's chairman, Raymond Chan, "has gone from being a trading commodity to becoming a consumer product."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Chan's ambitions do not stop at metal. Like many Hong Kong companies, Tem Fat is involved in property. A state-owned Shanghai copper company asked Tem Fat to invest in its plant. Mr Chan refused, but offered $10m for its site, bang next to a smart hotel. The copper firm used the proceeds to build a new plant on Shanghai's outskirts, and Tem Fat developed 26,000 square metres (279,860 sq feet) of prime downtown property. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That deal may partly explain the prodigious rise in the company's share price this year. Tem Fat shares are selling for 22 times current earnings, compared with around seven times earnings at the start of the year. That is hardly explained by post-tax profits, which in the year to April were flat, at HK$106m ($13.7m). Instead, the shares have been variously seen as a hedge against inflation and a cheap bet on Shanghai's property market.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Chinese property connection has worried bankers who lend to gold-bullion dealers. That is one reason its gold-bullion operations are to be floated on the Hong Kong stockmarket on December 2nd.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet with a faith that has accompanied a dozen earlier bull markets in Hong Kong, Mr Chan sees only rosy times ahead. What with Christmas and Chinese New Year sales running briskly, gold stocks in Hong Kong are reckoned to be down to just two weeks' worth of demand. And Hong Kong's return to China next year will bring a stream of new customers. But what most excites Mr Chan is the prospect of access to millions of tons of scrap jewellery lying, unused and unsold, in China. "Imagine: 50 years' worth of supply, and they don't even have a refinery."<br>

<p align=center>
