<html><head><title>Now, bondmania</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Now, bondmania</h1>

<p><b>Fast-rising stockmarkets are eye-catching. But bond markets around the  world are also enjoying heady times. Too heady, perhaps</b></p><br>
WALL STREET'S rise has been mesmerising. It took the Dow Jones Industrial Average a mere 30 trading days to rise from 6,000 to more than 6,500, a mark it reached on November 25th. The market has risen by 8% since the presidential election. So it was only natural that investors should focus most of their attention on sky-high share prices. Other stockmarkets have been dragged to records by America's bullish lead. Seven European markets, as well as Hong Kong, touched new highs along with the Dow.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But another bull market is equally deserving of attention. With few exceptions (Britain a notable one), bond markets around the world are enjoying an astonishing boom (see <a href="fn1.gif">chart</a>). In their exuberance, investors are signalling that there is a strong consensus. Interest rates will stay the same or continue to fall almost everywhere, the markets are saying, and there is almost no risk that they will rise. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This euphoria is widespread. The yield on America's 30-year Treasury bond has fallen to around 6.4%, more than three-quarters of a percentage point lower than its level in July. Canada, still worried by fears of secession in Quebec and mired in economic gloom, has seen interest rates on ten-year bonds drop below their American equivalents, a phenomenon last witnessed nearly two decades ago. Spanish short-term bonds are at 6%, a record low. On November 21st post-communist Russia's first ever bond issue was wildly oversubscribed. Even Japanese bonds have managed a small rally, fooling those who doubted that investors would go for ten-year government bonds yielding less than 2.7%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This global case of fixed-income fever rests on three main assumptions. Should any of them prove wrong, today's bond rally will become tomorrow's bear market. <br>
<font size=-1><li></font> <b>Steady growth, low inflation.</b> The markets are assuming that the world economy will continue on its current, even keel. The evidence: in many countries, long-term bonds now yield little more than short-term bonds, an indication that investors expect inflation to remain quiescent.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;John Lipsky, chief economist at Salomon Brothers, points out that current bond prices will not be justified should growth in leading industrial countries pick up sharply next year. If that happens, interest rates in big markets, such as America and Japan, are more likely to rise than to fall, sending bond prices tumbling. That happened as recently as 1994, when a sharp rise in interest rates knocked $1 trillion off American bond values over a few months.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is a revival of growth likely? Stephen Roach, chief economist at Morgan Stanley, thinks it is. Several industrialised countries, notably Britain, Germany and Sweden, are showing signs of new strength, while emerging economies in Asia and Latin America are likely to grow faster in 1997 than they have this year. True, the third-quarter <font size=-1>GDP</font> figures in America have just been revised downwards. All the same, that slowdown may not continue and consumer spending looks strong (see <a href="am3148.html">page</a>). If growth around the world proves stronger than bond markets expect, that would suck money away from bonds. <br>
<font size=-1><li></font> <b>EMU goes ahead.</b> Confidence that Europe's economic and monetary union (<font size=-1>EMU</font>) will start, as planned, on January 1st 1999 has contributed to the bond rally. Italy's re-entry on November 25th into the exchange-rate mechanism, something that is essential if it is to qualify for <font size=-1>EMU</font>, drove that country's short-term bond yield below Britain's. There has been a remarkable narrowing of the gap between bonds issued by Europe's traditionally more spendthrift countries, such as Spain and Italy, and those of famously prudent countries, notably Germany. A year ago, the spread between Italian bonds and German ones was greater than five percentage points. Now, the gap is less than two points.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The markets seem to be expecting a wave of economic conservatism. Qualifying for <font size=-1>EMU</font> will require Italy and Spain to slash spending and bring down inflation. So far, they seem willing to do it. Italy's inflation has fallen to a 27-year low of 3%, barely half the level of a year ago. In Spain, the inflation rate has dropped by one-third, to 3.5%, since April 1995. Budget deficits in both countries have fallen sharply.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such improvements lend weight to the idea that a combination of steady growth and fiscal tightening leave little scope for inflation in Europe. Indeed, a virtuous circle operates: falling interest rates slash debt-servicing costs for indebted governments, reducing budget deficits further.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet things could easily go wrong. Several countries may be massaging their budget numbers to meet the Maastricht criteria. If Germany insists that those criteria are observed strictly, then investors might lose confidence in budget projections that they are willing to endorse at the moment. Italy's 1997 budget purports to reduce the deficit by 63 trillion lire ($42 billion), for example, but 60% of this reduction is due to come from "new revenues" which include a partially refundable one-off tax. In a less bond-friendly climate, such legerdemain could go wrong. But if Italy were kept out, then the tensions over <font size=-1>EMU</font> membership would rise sharply.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For bondholders this is a minefield. If only France, Germany and a few other nations constitute the initial core of <font size=-1>EMU</font>, Spanish and Italian bonds will quickly lose their lustre. But if entry criteria are fudged to bring Italy (and Spain) aboard, the bonds of less deficit-ridden countries may well suffer from fears that Europe's single currency will begin life as a weakling.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> <b>No more business cycles.</b> This is the least tangible, but perhaps most profound of the assumptions made by today's bond enthusiasts. Thanks in equal parts to America's prolonged expansion and to the quiescence of inflation, it has become accepted wisdom in some circles that rich countries have entered a near-permanent condition of low-inflationary growth. Central banks merely have to remain vigilant in order to maintain Nirvana.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Proclamations that the business cycle is dead fly in the face of economic history. It is true that there have been important structural changes in economies around the world, partly driven by the spread of information technology. But at best the economic effects of such changes are poorly understood. And the chances that the world economy could be disrupted by, say, governmental economic mismanagement or a rise in oil prices, have not diminished simply because businesses now manage their affairs with computers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will bonds nosedive tomorrow? No one can know. But rarely has so much money come flooding into the bond markets so quickly. And rarely have investors been so ready to play down risks that their predecessors would have taken for granted. Amid America's bear market in the early 1980s, almost any piece of economic news was automatically deemed bad for bonds. Today, investors seem intent on finding only good news.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849315600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
